<1ST_LINE>u w AM-FinanceMinisters 2ndLd-Writethru a0811 04-15 1089</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Finance Ministers, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0811,1050</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US, Allies Try To Put Best Face On Dollar's Tumble</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: INSERTS 1 graf after 9th graf pvs bgng, `In Europe' to UPDATE
with dollar opening lower but then stabilizing in Tokyo early
Friday</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar plunged on world currency markets
Thursday in reaction to bad news on the U.S. trade deficit despite
a massive coordinated effort on the part of the United States and
its economic allies to halt the slide.
   The dollar's steep dive served served as an ominous reminder to
the world's economic powers that their best-laid plans to steady
the global economy can be quickly disrupted by events.
   Just as it had done several times last year, the weakness in the
dollar quickly spread to other financial markets, sending interest
rates up sharply and pushing the Dow Jones Industrial Average down
by more than 100 points, its second three-digit loss this year.
   The market turmoil came only a day after the world's seven major
industrial countries had issued a glowing communique bragging about
their ability to hold the dollar stable for the past four months.
   Finance ministers and central bank presidents of the seven
nations _ the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britian, France
and Italy _ reaffirmed on Wednesday their commitment to keep the
dollar stable.
   They pledged to back up the commitment with coordinated
intervention, the process by which governments dump other
currencies in exchange for dollars as a way of supporting the
greenback.
   Participants in the day-long Wednesday meeting said they had not
been told in advance by Treasury Secretary James A. Baker III that
the February trade deficit would be an unexpectedly large $13.8
billion, triggering the need for intervention. Baker is briefed a
day in advance on government economic reports.
   The finance ministers professed satisfaction with the way their
cooridnation effort had worked Thursday, but the dollar still
closed sharply lower against other currencies.
   In Europe, the dollar fell to 123.60 yen, breaking through a
125-yen barrier which has been considered the lower level for the
greenback over the past four months.
   In Tokyo on Friday, the dollar opened a sharp 1.7 percent lower
against the yen but stabilized later at that level on reports of
heavy dollar-buying by the Bank of Japan.
   While the global recession which some predicted following last
October's market collapse has not materialized, the turmoil
Thursday served as an chilling reminder of the continued fragility
of world economy.
   Baker and finance ministers from other countries tried to put
the best face on the dollar's tumble Thursday, contending that the
speed with which the countries intervened to support the dollar
showed that the drive for international cooperation was working.
   Currency traders reported that the Federal Reserve in the United
States and the central banks of West Germany, England, Switzerland
and Italy were among those intervening to brake the dollar's fall.
   ``I think what you see today is a very good example of
international cooperation because there has been concerted
intervention in support of the dollar involving a very large number
of countries,'' Nigel Lawson, the British chancellor of the
exchequer, said in a briefing for reporters.
   The surge in the trade deficit and the dollar's tumble were
among the items discussed by the world finance leaders as they
continued their talks Thursday.
   Baker, the prime architect of the three-year effort to manage
the level of the dollar, was grim-faced when he arrived for the
meetings, held at the headquarters of the International Monetary
Fund in Washington.
   He brushed past reporters without answering any questions, but
later his office released a text of comments he made during the
closed-door session in which he played down the significance of
February's widening of the trade deficit and stressed the resolve
of the United States and its allies to keep the value of the dollar
stable.
   ``Monthly trade figures are by their nature erratic. What is
important is that we are continuing along the general path of
reduced imbalances,'' Baker said.
   He said the United States has made progress in reducing its huge
federal budget deficits, something other countries have long urged.
Baker singled out Japan, West Germany and Britain for praise in
efforts to stimulate their domestic economies as a way of keeping
the global economy growing.
   Baker's comments were echoed by other finance ministers, who
also dismissed the February jump in the deficit as an aberration.
   But the swift drop in the dollar's value raised questions of how
successful countries will be over the long term in keeping the
dollar at its present levels. Many economists have forecast that
the dollar will eventually have to decline more to solve America's
trade problems.
   In their Dec. 22 accord, the countries pledged to keep the
dollar stable around current levels. While the governments have
never been specific about just what those levels were, speculation
has put the lower limit for the dollar at 125 yen.
   After it fell below that level Thursday, West German Finance
Minister Gerhard Stoltenberg, was asked whether the countries would
have to accept a new level for the dollar.
   ``That is a very good question, a thousand-dollar question,'' he
answered.
   The dollar turmoil also raised the possibility that the Federal
Reserve would be forced to tighten interest rates further in this
country to defend the dollar. Higher U.S. interest rates, while
slowing the American economy, are seen as a positive for the
greenback because foreign investors are able to earn more on their
dollar-denominated investments.
   Karl Otto Poehl, head of the West German central bank,
sidestepped questions about whether the Fed should tighten up
during a speech to the National Press Club.
   With Federal Reserve Chairman Alan Greenspan looking on, Poehl
said, ``I don't want to comment on American monetary and fiscal
policies.'' He said he believed that his country had done its part
to stimulate world growth by lowering West Germany interest rates.
   ``As far as (our) monetary policy is concerned, we couldn't have
done more. We have the lowest interest rates in the world ... and
it would be irresponsible to pursue more expansionary monetary
policies,'' Poehl said.
   It was a heated dispute between Baker and the West Germans last
year over interest rates which has been cited as one of the
contributing factors to Oct. 19 stock market plunge.
   Since that time, world finance leaders have gone out of their
way to stress harmony and coordinated efforts to keep the global
economy from toppling into another recession.
</TEXT>
