<2ND_LINE>AM-Alcohol Ban,0256</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Rally Against Alcohol Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AMHERST, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 500 University of Massachusetts
students, some carrying beer cans and liquor bottles, held a Bring
Your Own Booze rally on campus Thursday night to protest a ban on
alcohol at outdoor events.
   About 200 of the students marched to the home of Chancellor
Joseph Duffey, who imposed the ban last week. No arrests were
reported. The chancellor was out of town.
   Students sang ``Give booze a chance'' to the tune of ``Give
Peace a Chance.''
   ``This could definitely get out of hand but everyone here is a
responsible drinker,'' said student Tim Hopper, 19.
   Deirdre Ling, vice chancellor for university relations and
development, stood outside Duffey's house. ``As long as it's a
peaceful demonstration, students have the right to express their
opinion,'' she said.
   Students began defying the ban en masse Wednesday when nearly
1,000 marched on the administration building.
   ``Students who are of legal age have the right to drink
responsibly at public events,'' said Michael D. Ross, president of
the campus Republican Club, which sponsored the Wednesday rally
with other student organizations.
   He said students were particularly annoyed because Duffey failed
to consult with a student-faculty committee on campus drinking
before issuing the ban.
   The chancellor contended alcohol played a large role in several
racial incidents on campus, including a fracas involving hundreds
of students after the 1986 World Series and an attack on two blacks
by five whites in February.
</TEXT>
