<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Drugs 4thLd-Writethru a0873 04-15 0900</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Drugs, 4th Ld-Writethru, a0873,860</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>URGENT</HEAD>
<HEAD>Senate Votes Aid Sanctions On Mexico</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: SUBS 8th graf pvs bgng, `During more,' with 4 grafs to UPDATE
with Mexican foreign ministry reax</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JIM DRINKARD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate voted overwhelmingly Thursday to
slap aid and trade sanctions on Mexico for failing to do enough in
the war on drugs, ignoring a plea from President Reagan and
warnings that sanctions would do more harm than good.
   The move, on a 63 to 27 vote, came after backers of the
legislation said it would shock Mexico into doing more to combat
the growing drug flow coming across the United States' southwestern
border.
   Earlier, the lawmakers had voted voted 54 to 40 against taking
the same action against the Bahamas.
   Similar bills were pending in the House, but the measures were
given little chance of being finally enacted into law because of
remaining procedural hurdles in the House and a threat that Reagan
would veto any such measure to reach his desk.
   Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., sponsor of the Mexico resolution,
conceded that point, but said passage in the Senate would ``send a
message to the government of Mexico'' and added, ``We are compelled
to face reality.''
   Opponents of the anti-drug sanctions protested that both Mexico
and the Bahamas, while they can be faulted for shortcomings, are
making good-faith efforts to halt the flow of drugs through their
countries into the United States.
   And Reagan, in a letter to Senate leaders, had argued that
imposition of sanctions against Mexico because would ``adversely
affect every aspect'' of U.S.-Mexican relations.
   The Mexican Foreign Ministry released a statement Thursday night
rejecting the Senate vote as ``foreign interference.''
   ``It is a profound conviction rooted in our history and in our
laws that it only falls to one's own people to define without
foreign interference their institutions and that at all time only
they have the inalienable right to conduct their destiny,'' the
statement said.
   In addition, the statement said, ``No one has the right to
impose from abroad conduct, ideas, political or economic systems on
other peoples.''
   During more than five hours of Senate debate, several lawmakers
suggested that backers of the sanctions were jeopardizing bilateral
relations in response to election-year political pressure.
   ``It's a great opportunity to show them we're tough, show them
who's boss, and that we're against drugs,'' said Sen. John Chafee,
R-R.I. But he noted that the Bahamian government has won praise
from drug authorities for its cooperation. Penalizing the islands
``just doesn't make much sense,'' he said.
   Senate Foreign Relations Committee Chairman Claiborne Pell,
D-R.I., noted that Mexico is the third largest customer for U.S.
exports and that the United States gets 14 percent of its petroleum
imports from its southern neighbor.
   ``This is likely to have a serious negative impact'' on that
relationship, he said.
   Under a 1986 law, countries identified as production or transit
points for illegal drugs must lose half their U.S. foreign aid
unless the president certifies that they are ``fully cooperating''
with the war on drugs.
   Reagan made such a certification on March 1 for 17 of the 24
countries on the drug-trafficking list, including the Bahamas and
Mexico.
   After that certification, several lawmakers in both the House
and Senate began efforts to undo it.
   ``The purpose of this resolution is not to bash Mexico, but to
defend the United States,'' said Wilson, sponsor of the Mexico
resolution along with Sen. Alfonse D'Amato, R-N.Y.
   But one colleague suggested that the United States has little
room to criticize its southern neighbor. Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz.,
noted that marijuana is one of California's largest cash crops and
that New York streets are unsafe because of drug-related crime.
   ``I wonder if we shouldn't decertify those states'' and cut off
federal aid, McCain asked.
   While neither the Bahamas nor Mexico receives substantial U.S.
economic aid, losing the administration's drug certification could
lead to loss of other benefits, including lucrative sugar-import
quotas, airline landing rights and trade preferences.
   Of particular concern to Mexico was a requirement that if
certification is lost, U.S. representatives to international
development banks must vote against future loans to the affected
country. The United States has a weighted vote on the banks, but
not a majority. Loans from the banks have been crucial to Mexico,
which is laboring under a mammoth foreign debt.
   Mexico had sent private diplomatic signals that if Congress
persists in publicly embarrassing it through resolutions of
non-cooperation, it is likely to evict U.S. drug agents and wage
the anti-narcotics fight without outside aid, according to
congressional and diplomatic sources.
   In other action, the Senate approved, on a voice vote, a
non-binding resolution to place Haiti on the list of drug producing
and transit countries, subjecting it to greater scrutiny and to
possible similar sanctions next year.
   Reagan, in his letter, said the impact of the legislation
``would almost certainly be an increase in the flow of drugs to the
United States.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater had said earlier that the
administration was aware of congressional concerns about the
international drug trafficking problem. But he said that Reagan's
advisers were prepared to recommend that he veto any legislation
imposing sanctions on Mexico.
   He said it was necessary to ``keep in mind the broader national
security interests of our two countries and other interests such as
trade, immigration and so forth.''
</TEXT>
