<DOCNO> AP880415-0015 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0201EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Meese-RealEstate Bjt   04-15 0972</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Meese-Real Estate, Bjt,950</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Meese Grand Jury Hears Testimony From Real Estate Magnate</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL J. SNIFFEN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>and</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>JOAN MOWER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writers</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal grand jury is weighing testimony
from a wealthy couple who won a $50 million lease for Justice
Department offices after arranging to pay a $40,000 salary for
Attorney General Edwin Meese's wife, Ursula.
   Independent Counsel James McKay on Thursday personally
supervised the questioning of Howard M. Bender and his wife,
Sondra, before the grand jury, something he does only when major
witnesses are summoned.
   Bender spent about three hours before the grand jury; his wife
was there only an hour. She left at the grand jury's normal
quitting time, indicating she might be called back. The Benders
were accompanied by their attorney, Seymour Glanzer.
   McKay is investigating whether Meese violated federal law
through any conflict between his personal financial dealings and
his government job.
   Although McKay said April 1 he did not have evidence to indict
Meese in cases involving telephone stock and a Mideast oil
pipeline, Thursday's appearance by the Benders underscored the
prosecutor's other announcement at that time: that he still had
some cases to pursue.
   Meanwhile, trustees of the Multiple Sclerosis Society said
Thursday that they never voted on the plan to hire Ursula Meese at
$40,000 a year with money donated by the Bender family foundation.
   The Associated Press reported Wednesday that a partnership
headed by Howard Bender won a $50 million lease on Justice
Department offices after the Bender Foundation put up the money to
pay Mrs. Meese's salary at the MS society.
   Meese, in Atlanta to attend a drug conference, was asked by a
reporter about the matter but declined to comment. During a later
stop at an Immigration and Nationalization Service center in
Decatur, Ga., he turned aside several questions about the lease
arrangement, saying ``that's not on the subject of immigration.''
   White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said Thursday that he
knew nothing about the lease but that President Reagan ``still has
full confidence in Ed Meese.''
   MS officials have said the Bender Foundation, of which Sondra is
president, donated the money in October 1985 to give Mrs. Meese,
previously a volunteer, the salary for three years. Mrs. Bender and
Mrs. Meese are MS trustees.
   Several MS trustees said they did not learn of that arrangement
until newspaper accounts appeared in the last two weeks. Others,
however, said the board had been advised earlier.
   Susan Sikorski, wife of Rep. Gerry Sikorski, D-Minn., said she
first learned about Mrs. Meese's salary when her husband read a
newspaper account. Mrs. Sikorski, a trustee, said the issue of Mrs.
Meese's job was never discussed in any board meeting that she
attended.
   Another trustee, Remmel Dudley, gave a different version.
   ``I guess you might say it was reported to the board,'' said
Dudley. ``I cannot say that a proposal was put before the board,
discussed pro and con and then a vote was taken, but we were
informed that this had been proposed.
   ``I was pleased,'' Dudley said. ``I was told the Benders had
this foundation and they could make a contribution to MS or pay for
someone's salary or designate for a specific purpose. We were
delighted to know she (Mrs. Meese) would be a full-time employee
because she's a worker.''
   The board meets quarterly and not all the trustees attend each
meeting.
   Another longtime trustee, who spoke on condition she not be
identified, said, ``I was shocked ... I was aghast when I saw it''
in a newspaper. She said she never missed a board meeting, but had
no idea Mrs. Meese was being paid as MS development director.
   Attorney Bryan Barkley, also a trustee, said, ``I don't recall a
discussion at a board meeting'' about the plan to hire Mrs. Meese.
   He said, ``It is not normal to earmark a grant for the salary of
a specific person. That's a little unusual.'' But he added, ``It's
not necessarily something the board would get into to vote on or
ratify.''
   MS society attorney James Bierbower said the arrangement was
brought up in October 1985 at a special meeting to discuss
expansion of Operation Job Match, a program to help MS victims find
work. Mrs. Bender was at the session, he said.
   McKay has subpoenaed records of Mrs. Meese's job at the society
and is known to be interested in a $50 million lease renewal won by
the Bender partnership in May 1987.
   Most of the offices in the lease were occupied by the Justice
Department's Immigration and Naturalization Service, which had
complained about the building's maintenance, size, location and
security.
   The Bender partnership sold the building 13 days after the lease
renewal, earning a $22.6 million profit on a two-year investment.
The lease was crucial to the sale, the new owner said.
   The Bender partnership had bought the building in March 1985 for
nearly twice its assessed value at a time when the government
wanted to move more than a third of its offices elsewhere.
   Three months after the Bender partnership purchased the
building, the Reagan administration disclosed publicly that it had
decided to retain the building.
   An attorney for the Meeses, James Rocap, denies any wrongdoing
on their part in the transactions, but acknowledges that the
Benders and Meeses know each other. The Benders refuse to discuss
the matter publicly. A key government official said Meese played no
role in the real estate decision.
   Other Bender buildings have done business with the Justice
Department. Government documents show that Howard Bender and his
two brothers, Morton and Stanley, as a partnership, signed a lease
in June 1985 to give the government more space in a downtown office
building, One McPherson Square, where it has leased several floors
since 1971.
   The Justice Department occupies part of one floor there.
</TEXT>
