<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ToxicContaminants     04-15 0422</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Toxic Contaminants,410</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PCB Contamination of People a Six-Generation Problem</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM BOVEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   For children born in the 22nd century, the
adage ``You are what you eat'' may need to be rewritten to read:
``You are what your great-great-great grandmother ate.''
   PCB contamination of people who eat tainted food is a problem
than can span six generations, a researcher told a House Public
Works and Transportation Committee subcommittee on Thursday.
   A 20-year-old woman giving birth to a child passes on sufficient
PCBs so that even if all exposure to the substance were stopped,
``I would still measure PCB in the body fat ... six generations in
the future,'' said Wayland R. Swain, vice president of Eco Logic
Inc. of Ann Arbor, Mich.
   Swain's figures suggest that at 30 years to a generation,
children born in the year 2138 would still suffer contamination
from PCBs ingested in 1988, inherited through the female line.
   PCB production has been banned for years, but the substance,
believed to cause cancer, continues to enter the environment
through such sources as old electric transformers.
   Using earlier research into the transmission of polychlorinated
biphenyls _ PCBs for short _ Swain calculated the amounts of the
substance passed to an infant through nursing and retained in the
infant's body.
   He said an infant nursed by a mother who regularly consumed Lake
Michigan fish, which have been found to contain small amounts of
PCBs, would be exposed to 6.2 milligrams of PCB by the end of 12
months, and 5.3 milligrams would be retained in the infant's body.
   ``It is clear that infants nursed by mothers who have consumed
Lake Michigan fish exceed recommended consumption guidelines (for
adults) for their entire breast-feeding experience,'' he told the
subcommittee on investigations and oversight.
   The level of PCBs retained by such infants, in terms of body
weight, was more than seven times the maximum consumption level
recommended by the Food and Drug Administration, Swain said.
   A mother passes PCBs to a child not only through beast feeding
but through the placenta before birth, Swain said.
   Infants exposed to excessive PCB levels tend to be shorter, have
smaller heads, be more likely to catch infectious diseases, and
exhibit an inability to focus on their surroundings, Swain said.
   A recent decline in PCB levels in the Great Lakes has slowed,
recent research suggests, with the substance circulating from the
sediment into the water and back into the sediment again in a cycle
of continuing contamination of the food chain.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0019 </DOCNO>
