<1ST_LINE>u a AM-Trade-Markets 3rdLd-Writethru a0886 04-15 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade-Markets, 3rd Ld - Writethru, a0886,0562</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Another Bad Trade Deficit Report Roils the Markets</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 10th graf pvs, `In Tokyo ...' with two grafs to UPDATE
with end of morning session in Japan.</NOTE>
<HEAD>With AM-Trade Deficit, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Dow Jones industrial average plunged more
than 100 points, the dollar sank and interest rates jumped Thursday
after the government announced a $13.8 billion trade deficit in
February, the biggest since last October.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 stocks skidded 101.46 points to
2,005.64, a 4.8 percent decline. It was the year's second worst
drop after a 140.58-point slide Jan. 8.
   The value of U.S. stocks fell $99.7 billion, or 3.7 percent,
according to Wilshire Associates of Santa Monica, Calif.
   The White House and most economists said the trade deficit was
still improving in spite of the setback, but the markets took the
news badly anyway.
   Most traders had convinced themselves the imbalance between
imports and exports would be less than $12 billion, and they bailed
out when the disappointing report hit at 8:30 a.m. EDT.
   ``There was a lot of wishing-makes-it-so (attitude). People
wanted to see a good number,'' said Carl B. Weinberg, chief
economist of High Frequency Economics. He had predicted a $14
billion gap.
   The decline in the Dow triggered a ban on a form of computerized
program trading on the New York Stock Exchange. It was the first
time the ban has been prompted by a decline of more than 50 points.
Last week, it was triggered by an increase of more than 50 points.
   The Dow had climbed nearly 130 points from April 5 through
Tuesday, largely on anticipation of favorable trade news. The news
killed that rally as declining issues outnumbered advancing ones
nearly 11 to 1 on the NYSE.
   The trade deficit report also battered major foreign markets. In
London, the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index fell 1.3
percent.
   In Tokyo, stocks fell sharply from their record highs at the
opening of trading today but later recovered much of their losses.
The key Nikkei Stock Average of 225 issues, down more than 250
points at one time, finished the morning session at 26,967.83, down
143.52 from Thursday's record close.
   The dollar opened a sharp 1.7 percent lower against the Japanese
yen but later stabilized at that level on reports of heavy
dollar-buying by the Bank of Japan.
   In U.S. activity, the dollar had lost roughly 2 percent of its
value against the yen, British pound and West German mark in spite
of heavy intervention by virtually all the major central banks.
   Big trade deficits tend to push the dollar down by giving
trading partners an oversupply of the U.S. currency.
   Interest rates leaped as pessimism swamped the bond market. The
trade deficit signaled to some investors that an overly strong
domestic economy was sucking in too many imports. Traders also
feared a weak dollar could push up import prices, causing inflation
and hurting fixed-income securities.
   The Treasury Department's benchmark 30-year Treasury bond
recovered about halfway late in the day as stocks were sinking, but
still finished with a decline of roughly $11 for every $1,000 in
face value. Its yield, which moves inversely to the price, rose to
roughly 8.87 percent, a three-month high.
</TEXT>
