<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0159EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Dance     04-15 0311</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dance,0331</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Paul Taylor Premiere: `Counterswarm'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will stand for PMs.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Always interesting, the Paul Taylor Dance
Company was not trying for ``pretty'' with its premiere of
``Counterswarm'' at the City Center Thursday night.
   Consider Taylor's 1986 ``A Musical Offering,'' danced in caveman
costumes to Bach. Or his 1985 ``Last Look,'' danced by apparently
insane spastics.
   In ``Counterswarm,'' dancers proved they were up to Taylor's
choreographed speed and athleticism.
   Music for the 25-minute ``Counterswarm'' is from the Hungarian
composer Gyorgy Ligeti and contains droning and shimmering tones.
   The two swarms were eight dancers in purple and eight dancers in
red.
   The purple swarm dances first, with elbows bent and close to the
body and hands cupped like cobra heads. They dart their arms out
and back, looking like snakes striking. One couple dances, with
cupped hands together behind their backs. They strut, giving the
appearance of peacocks.
   A couple in red enters and dances briefly, the man seeming to be
subservient, lifting the woman, who maintains a regal posture. The
red swarm dances about, with shoulders shrugging, looking like
chickens.
   Suddenly the red swarm turns futuristic, arms shooting up and
back like antennae on robots.
   The purple swarm enters doing backward sommersaults, then walks
around with knees bent, arms dangling like those of monkeys.
   A woman in red and two men in purple dance, looking like insects.
   After a blackout, a short final section has everybody on stage
for a not very serious war. One person in red and one in purple
rush together and bump stomachs.
   One couple grappled arms in an unfriendly stance as the curtain
fell.
   We don't know what ``Counterswarm'' represented. But it didn't
represent either the lyrical or humorous, more fun side, of Paul
Taylor.
   The company dances at the City Center through May 1.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
