<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0202EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-NewYorkPolls     04-15 0446</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-New York Polls,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Polls Show Dukakis Continues To Lead Among NY Democrats</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Polls in the last week before the New York
primary show Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis well ahead of Jesse
Jackson in the race for the Democratic presidential nomination, and
Sen. Albert Gore Jr. mired in single digits.
   Dukakis had the highest measure of support, at 49 percent, in an
ABC News-Washington Post poll released Thursday. The poll also gave
Jackson his highest numbers, at 34 percent.
   Dukakis led Jackson by 45 percent to 28 percent in a CBS News
poll and 46 percent to 34 percent in a Marist College poll, also
released Thursday.
   Gore had only 8 percent support in the first two polls and 7
percent in the third.
   ``Certainly nothing much moved this week except for solidity to
the front-runners,'' said Marist pollster Lee Miringoff.
   A Marist poll last week had Dukakis at 47 percent, Jackson at 31
percent and Gore at 6 percent _ virtually the same results as the
new Marist survey, conducted by telephone Monday and Tuesday among
359 likely Democratic voters.
   Dukakis' strong support went from 53 percent to 67 percent.
Jackson's became nearly unshakeable, moving from 67 percent to 82
percent strong.
   Gore's strength remained at about 40 percent despite the
Tennessee senator's aggressive campaign style and a television
advertising budget that aides hope will reach $1 million.
   In another bad sign for Gore, the Jewish voters surveyed by
Marist still supported Dukakis overwhelmingly, despite efforts by
the Gore campaign to win them over by taking a hard pro-Israel line
on Middle East issues.
   Seventy percent of the Jews in the Marist poll backed Dukakis,
just 12 percent chose Gore and 6 percent favored Jackson. Jews
account for up to a quarter of the Democratic primary vote in New
York.
   The Marist poll found Jackson with his customary overwhelming
black support and support from about 16 percent of white voters.
``The number really needs to reach into the 20s in order for him to
overtake Dukakis,'' Miringoff said.
   The polls did indicate some room for movement: 5 percent were
uncommitted and 8 percent undecided in Marist's poll, 8 percent
uncommitted and 11 percent undecided in the CBS survey. The
ABC-Post poll had 6 percent favoring some other candidate and 2
percent undecided.
   The CBS poll was conducted by telephone Monday through Wednesday
among 581 likely Democratic voters and has a margin of error of 4
percentage points. The ABC-Post poll was conducted by telephone
Wednesday among 176 likely voters, and has a margin of error of 9
points.
   The Marist poll has a margin of error of 5 percentage points.
</TEXT>
