<1ST_LINE>r w PM-ArmsTreaty     04-15 0614</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arms Treaty,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Reagan May Go To Moscow Without Ratified Arms Pact</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate leaders say the chamber is not in any
hurry to vote on the U.S.-Soviet treaty eliminating medium-range
nuclear weapons, raising the possibility the pact may not be
ratified before President Reagan visits Moscow six weeks from now.
   ``I'm not driven by a calendar deadline. I want first, last and
always to have a good treaty,'' Senate Majority Leader Robert Byrd,
D-W.Va., told reporters Thursday.
   The Reagan administration has pushed for a ratification vote
before Reagan's May 29-June 2 meeting with Soviet leader Mikhail S.
Gorbachev, but Byrd said there is a possible ``hole in the treaty''
that first has to be filled.
   That question revolves around whether the treaty bans so-called
``futuristic'' weapons, using exotic technologies such as lasers,
plasma, or ion beams.
   Sen. John Warner of Virginia, ranking Republican on the Armed
Services Committee, said the treaty is not likely to come to the
Senate floor before early May, after the chamber returns from a
week-long recess.
   When the Senate finally votes, ratification is probable,
according to both Byrd and Republican leaders. Ratification
requires a vote of 67 of the 100 senators, and both parties say the
treaty will likely be supported by 88 to 90 senators.
   The Armed Services Committee has been meeting behind closed
doors with administration officials, including chief treaty
negotiator Maynard Glitman, to try to resolve the issue of which
technologies are banned.
   The treaty doesn't mention futuristic weapons, but Glitman and
administration officials have said the Soviet Union understands the
pact bars the possession or flight testing of all medium-range
weapons, no matter how they are armed or operate.
   The Armed Services panel has already endorsed the pact, but it
is planning to issue another report on the ``futuristic'' weapons
issue, and Byrd said no floor action is likely before that report
is done.
   Two former top Reagan administration officials said in letters
released Thursday they don't believe the treaty bans futuristic
weapons.
   The pair, former Defense Secretary Caspar Weinberger and former
Arms Control and Disarmament Agency Director Kenneth Adelman,
outlined their views in letters to the Armed Services Committee.
   Weinberger wrote, ``I can simply state that there was no
understanding of any kind that I knew about that the treaty covered
anything related to these so-called futuristic weapons.''
   ``Certainly, there was no discussion or evaluation of the
military sufficiency questions involved in banning futuristic
weaponry that I ever participated in, and I never heard any others
having such a discussion,'' said Weinberger.
   ``Indeed, had there been any suggestions that `futuristic'
weapons were banned, I would have opposed it in the strongest
possible terms, because it would have had an obvious adverse effect
on (the Strategic Defense Initiative) for us to agree to any
limitation on any systems not yet designed or `futuristic' systems
...'' Weinberger said.
   Adelman said he never knew about any such ban that was discussed
in National Security Council meetings he attended or in ``any
meeting with Soviet officials with which I am familiar.''
   Meanwhile, Howard Phillips, chairman of the Conservative Caucus,
a private group, announced a nationwide campaign to defeat the
treaty or to delay the Senate vote.
   Phillips said black umbrellas emblazoned with anti-treaty
rhetoric would be sent to all senators to symbolize the campaign.
   ``Open, the umbrella symbolizes the protective shield which, for
more than four decades, has prevented Soviet domination and
intimidation of Europe,'' said Phillips.
   ``Closed, the umbrella today symbolizes the spirit of
appeasement and the lack of resolve which characterized (British
Prime Minister) Neville Chamberlain's dealings with Adolph Hitler
at Munich precisely 50 years ago.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0029 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0407EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Arias-CentralAmerica     04-15 0605</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arias-Central America,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Costa Rican President Concerned about Soviet Arms Shipments</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE GEDDA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias is urging
President Reagan to tell Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev at
their summit meeting that continuing Soviet weapons shipments to
Central America are undermining peace efforts in the region.
   Arias rejected Soviet denials that they are supporting rebels in
Guatemala and El Salvador and said a stable peace in Central
America may be beyond reach if the Kremlin does not change its
policy.
   Arias said Thursday that Secretary of State George P. Shultz
should prepare for the Moscow summit next month by meeting with the
five Central American foreign ministers, Nicaragua's included.
   Such an encounter would end a three-year freeze on substantive
diplomatic contacts between the United States and Nicaragua's
leftist government.
   U.S. officials, insisting on anonymity, said there is no
prospect for a meeting along the lines proposed by Arias unless the
Sandinista government demonstrates a clear will to negotiate
seriously with the Contra rebels when talks on a permanent
settlement are held.
   U.S. special envoy Morris Busby sounded out leaders from four
Central American countries friendly to the United States last week
and they generally agreed the time was not ripe for a regional
consultation that would include the United States and Nicaragua,
the officials said.
   Arias himself had expressed that view last week and one U.S.
official expressed surprise that the Costa Rican leader had made
the proposal Thursday without reference to the qualifications he
had made in his talks with Busby.
   Arias, author of the Central American peace plan, talked about
his proposal during a luncheon appearance before the American
Society of Newspaper Editors and later discussed it with Vice
President George Bush.
   At the luncheon, he was sharply critical of the Soviet Union.
   Following the congressional cutoff of U.S. military aid to the
Nicaraguan rebels in February, Arias sent an open letter to
Gorbachev appealing for similar Soviet restraint. He said he
received a response from the Soviet Foreign Ministry that contained
a ``lot of cynicism.''
   The Soviets denied sending aid to leftist rebels in El Salvador
and Guatemala and also said they were supporting Nicaragua's
leftist government militarily because the United States was
supplying its allies in the region, Arias said.
   He said it is ``quite obvious'' that both Cuba and the Soviet
Union are supporting the leftist insurgencies in El Salvador and
Guatemala in violation of the peace plan the five Central American
president signed last August.
   The Reagan administration has accused Cuba of sending weapons to
leftist forces in the region but has not made the same allegation
recently about the Soviets.
   Cuban President Fidel Castro said recently that his country
provides ``political and moral support'' to the Salvadoran rebels
but that there is no need to send them weapons because they are
self-sufficient.
   Arias said he decided to write to Gorbachev and not to Castro
because the Cuban leader would not be sending weapons to Central
American insurgents without the Kremlin's consent.
   In his prepared remarks, Arias said the Soviets send military
supplies ``worth millions'' to Central America.
   ``We ought to obligate the Soviet Union to rectify its policy
about Central America, and we need for it the political backing of
all friendly nations,'' he said.
   ``The coming withdrawal of Russian troops from Afghanistan
provides hope for the political rectification needed in Central
America.''
   The Reagan administration has said the Soviets sent about $450
million in military supplies to Nicaragua last year and that
shipments over the first two months this year were above the
comparable period in 1987.
</TEXT>
