<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TaxNight     04-15 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Tax Night,740</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Postal Service Preparing for Tax Onslaught</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Tax Time Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RANDOLPH E. SCHMID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dreaded income-tax deadline is here, but
some folks headed for the midnight mail will also be given a chance
to bash a used car, gobble headache powder, sip coffee or nibble
frozen yogurt.
   Some communities have decided to brighten the typically somber
undertaking by making it into an ``event.'' Those frustrated by the
new tax forms, for example, may want to do their mailing in Little
Rock, Ark.
   Radio station KZOU-FM will broadcast from a parking lot where
the Postal Service has set up a special mail box, to be collected
at midnight.
   The station will offer last-minute taxpayers a chance to vent
their feelings by taking a sledgehammer to a used car. A small
charge for taking part will be used for charity.
   Things will be a little more festive in Phoenix, where the
Postal Service has set up special collection points at shopping
centers.
   Frozen yogurt bars will be offered to taxpayers by radio station
KOOL-FM, while at another location KESZ-FM will give out fast food
coupons, said postal service spokeswoman Margot Myers.
   Tax night in her city has become ``quite an event,'' she
remarked.
   The nation's capital isn't exempt, either, with the Kennedy
Center for the Performing Arts joining in.
   The Center is using the rite of last-minute tax filing to
promote the performance of ``The Rite of Spring.'' A postal clerk
will set up shop at the Center from 6:30 to 8:30 p.m. for patrons
of the arts to buy stamps and mail their taxes en route to their
dose of culture.
   For Arkansans who have been too busy completing their taxes to
consider going to a concert, North Little Rock radio station
KSSN-FM is setting up a ``tax aid'' station to give out coffee,
donuts and headache powders at the general mail facility there, the
Postal Service reports.
   Those who prefer Alka-Seltzer with their coffee, donuts and
taxes can head north to Madison, Wis., where station WIBA will
offer succor to the late filers.
   Postal Service consumer advocate Ann Robinson in Washington said
she couldn't be specific about the last day, but that the post
office expects to handle 30 million tax returns nationwide in the
``last couple of days.''
   Robinson reminded taxpayers to use the correct postage _ under
this month's rate hike, it now costs a quarter for the first ounce
and 20 cents for each added ounce. She also encouraged use of the
Internal Revenue Service envelopes because they make the mail
easier for postal workers to handle.
   Taxpayers seeking last-minute postmarks annually flock to post
offices, and service until midnight will be available in many
communities to accommodate them, she reported.
   Indeed, streetcorner collection for people driving by will be
available in dozens of cities.
   In Baltimore, the move this year is to decentralize the postal
rush.
   ``Traditionally we have quite a bit of congestion at the main
office on that night, so we're trying to solve that,'' explained
spokeswoman Gloria Cheek.
   Special pickups have been scheduled for mail deposit boxes in
front of Baltimore's 33 postal stations. That mail will be
collected at 11:30 p.m., and postmarked April 15, she said.
   Washington radio station WCXR is offering contest winners free
stamps and a limousine ride to the post office.
   Volunteer or government tax preparers will be on hand to help
late filers in many locations including New York, Little Rock,
Peoria, Milwaukee, Philadelphia, Richmond, Va., Baltimore and
Washington.
   Postal workers will collect tax returns from motorists at all
four corners of the Birmingham main post office and a clerk will be
stationed inside to weigh items and sell stamps until midnight.
   In Los Angeles, the Terminal Annex and Worldway Postal centers
will be open until midnight, and a hotline to the main post office
will give information on other late collection points in Van Nuys,
Santa Ana and Long Beach.
   An Express Mail van manned with two clerks will be parked in
front of the Denver Main post office to collect tax forms until
midnight. And in Minneapolis, two-ton collection trucks will loom
at three locations around the main post office.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
