<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0226EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Budget     04-15 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Budget,580</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>House, Senate Will Spar Over `Creative Accounting' In Budget</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Senate passage of a $1.1 trillion fiscal 1989
budget sets up a battle with the House over domestic spending and
how far Congress can stray from its deficit-reduction pact with
President Reagan.
   This year's budget debate is framed by the bipartisan agreement
with the president, which sets out limits for taxes and major
spending categories.
   Both the House and Senate have now passed budgets obeying the
pact's spending caps of $294 billion for the military and $16.1
billion in foreign aid. And neither chamber included tax increases
beyond the $14 billion enacted last December.
   So when the two sides begin meeting next week to resolve their
differences, the focus will be on domestic programs.
   The Senate plan, approved Thursday by a 69-26 vote, is similar
to the House plan in supporting large increases in spending on AIDS
research, education, and aviation safety. Both also reject Reagan's
request to terminate several domestic programs.
   But the Senate plan is closer to the president's in several
areas. It contains sharp increases for the space program and
science. The House last month opted for more modest boosts in those
areas in order to better protect mass transit, housing and
development programs.
   Both plans fudge the numbers in order to claim they stay within
the domestic spending limits, but they do it in different ways.
   The House voted to use what Senate Budget Committee Chairman
Lawton Chiles, D-Fla., called ``creative accounting'' _ simply
declaring that some expenses were not covered by the agreement.
   The Senate, eager to make room for a new $2.6 billion anti-drug
program but unwilling to make cuts elsewhere in the budget, at the
last minute set up a special fund. Declaring the money wouldn't be
tapped unless a ``dire emergency'' were declared, the budget simply
doesn't count that spending yet.
   Still, budget leaders from the two chambers said they hoped to
reach agreement quickly.
   ``There are obvious differences,'' House Budget Committee
Chairman William H. Gray III, D-Pa., said in a written statement.
``With good will, I am sure these differences can be resolved.''
   Chiles said the talks between the two chambers would begin next
week and, he hoped, go quickly.
   But Sen. Pete V. Domenici of New Mexico, the senior Republican
on the budget committee, said, ``It is a more formidable challenge
than I thought it would be'' in the wake of the deficit agreement.
   The budget is a congressional resolution which does not require
the president's signature, but it guides lawmakers as they pass
their annual fiscal legislation.
   Congress has a self-imposed deadline of April 15 for finishing
the budget. It has failed to meet the deadline again, but things
are closer to being resolved at this date than they have been in
recent years.
   There was no expression of concern in either the House or Senate
about the tardiness. While millions of taxpayers must file their
returns by midnight tonight or face a penalty, there's no
punishment for the lawmakers if they don't figure out on time how
to spend the tax dollars.
   Those tax dollars still don't cover government expenses in
either the administration's or Congress' budgets. But they all
claim to meet the $136 billion deficit target of the Gramm-Rudman
budget-balancing law.
   Sen. J. James Exon, D-Neb., said even those deficit numbers were
based on too-optimistic White House estimates of a growing economy.
   ``The wreckage of our fiscal policy will haunt the next
president and presidents to come,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
