<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0428EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-TurtleExcluders     04-15 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Turtle Excluders,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Stays Enforcement of Allegedly Cumbersome, Costly Devices</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JENNIFER DIXON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Shrimpers nationwide have been granted a
reprieve from federal regulations requiring them to outfit their
vessels with devices to exclude turtles from their nets.
   U.S. District Judge Patrick Carr in New Orleans told the
government Tuesday to stop enforcing the regulations until the 5th
U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals rules on a lawsuit filed by the
Louisiana attorney general's office and Concerned Shrimpers of
Louisiana.
   Shrimpers contend the devices are expensive, cumbersome, and
would drastically cut the size of their catch. Environmentalists
say they are necessary to protect endangered and threatened species
of turtles.
   Carr upheld the regulations as lawful in a Feb. 29 ruling but
decided this week to prohibit enforcement while his earlier ruling
is appealed.
   ``We're pleased that Judge Carr agreed with the state's argument
that little harm, if any, would be done to sea turtles if shrimpers
continue to trawl without TEDs (turtle excluder devices) until the
case is finally adjudicated,'' Louisiana Attorney General William
Guste Jr. said on learning of the ruling Thursday.
   ``We argued that shrimpers would have to go to great trouble and
expense to equip their nets with TEDs,'' he said. ``The possibility
remains that the appeals court will reverse Carr's (earlier) ruling
and not require shrimpers to use TEDs.''
   Guste said Louisiana shrimpers could lose up to 15 percent of
their catches if they have to use the devices, meaning less tax
revenue for the state.
   In his order this week, Carr said shrimpers have had trouble
obtaining the TEDs and getting adequate training in their use.
   ``We still maintain the regulations are valid and lawful and
necessary to protect turtles,'' said Jay Johnson, an attorney for
the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration in Washington.
``We're preparing the papers to seek a cancellation of his order
and an expedited ruling from the court of appeals.''
   NOAA drafted the regulations to protect endangered and
threatened turtles, most notably the ``critically endangered''
Kemp's ridley sea turtle, Johnson said.
   ``I'm thrilled with Judge Carr's ruling. This is the first major
victory in the shrimpers' battle to stop TED regulations, and it is
important recognition that the TED regulations are impractical,''
said Rep. Solomon Ortiz, D-Texas.
   ``NOAA and the environmentalists will probably ask that the
court of appeals to overturn this decision, but I believe that the
evidence is overwhelming that shrimper compliance is impossible,''
said Ortiz.
   NOAA was phasing in the regulations depending on location _ they
took effect March 1 along the Gulf Coast, on Jan. 1 in southwest
Florida near the Keys, and in October near Florida's Cape
Canaveral, Johnson said. The regulations were to take effect for
the rest of the Atlantic coast May 1.
   ``We know they don't work,'' Tee John Mialjevich of Louisiana,
president and executive director of Concerned Shrimpers of America,
said of the TEDs.
   More than 100 shrimping vessels converged on the Florida Keys in
February to protest the regulations, Mialjevich said.
   Elizabeth Megginson, an assistant state attorney general in
Louisiana, said the devices would create enormous problems for
shrimpers and the state, which would have to help enforce the law.
   Louisiana has 32,000 commercial and recreational shrimpers, and
there weren't enough of the devices on the market to go around, she
said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
