<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-Smell     04-15 0194</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Smell,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Strange Smells Prompts Evacuation, Confounds Experts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Strange smells noticed by noses from London to
France in the last week have confounded experts, who sniffed out
possible causes ranging from a No. 73 city bus to a freak change in
the atmosphere.
   After an unpleasant gas-like odor caused one of the biggest
evacuations in peacetime Britain Wednesday in a busy shopping area,
an even more widespread smell Thursday was reported by hundreds of
people in calls to fire and environmental officials.
   ``I could smell it when I left my home in Kingston (southwest
London) this morning,'' said a fire brigade spokeswoman. ``When I
got off the train in central London I could still smell it.''
   Friends of the Earth environmental group was inundated with
calls from residents in Oxfordshire, Kent, London and Essex, all in
the south of England within a 50-mile radius of London.
   ``I contacted our office in Paris and apparently there was a
similar smell in France last week,'' said an official from Friends
of the Earth, speaking anonymously in keeping with British practice.
   ``The theory is that it was caused by a freak atmospheric
condition.''
</TEXT>
