<HEAD>Traficant Campaign Admits It May Win No Delegates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>YOUNGSTOWN, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lack of funds and the growing populist
appeal of Jesse Jackson are convincing U.S. Rep. James A. Traficant
Jr. that his presidential campaign may win no convention delegates,
a staff member says.
   Traficant press secretary Paul Marcone confirmed Thursday a
report the previous day in The (Youngstown) Vindicator that the
two-term Democratic congressman no longer expects to do well even
in his own state.
   Traficant launched his presidential bid last year, saying he
hoped to control a bloc of delegates that would give him bargaining
power with Democratic presidential contenders and draw attention to
Rust Belt economic problems.
   But the congressman told the newspaper he is no longer raising
funds for his presidential campaign and will buy only a few small
newspaper advertisements prior to the May 3 Ohio primary.
