<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Japan-Markets 3rdLd-Writethru a0419 04-15 0246</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0419,0250</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Prices Rebound From Early Lows; Dollar Stabilizes Lower In
Tokyo</HEAD>
<HEAD>LEADS with 3 grafs with closing figures; pickup 4th pvs, `Dealers
in ...</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed sharply lower against the
Japanese yen in Tokyo Friday, following the release of
higher-than-expected U.S. trade deficit figures. Stock prices also
declined.
   The dollar ended trading at 124.13 yen, down 2.02 yen from its
close of 126.15 yen Thursday. It had opened the day on Friday at
123.95 yen and ranged between 123.90 and 124.22 yen.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which closed at a record 27,111.35 points
Thursday, lost 217.78 points to end the day at 26,893.57.
   Dealers in stock and currency markets said the unexpectedly
large U.S. trade deficit of $13.8 billion in February, as reported
Thursday by the Commerce Department in Washington, was the sole
factor behind the twin plunges.
   But in the stock market, prices rebounded on strong buying
sentiment among institutional investors, who saw no reason to sell
their holdings, said Hiromi Yoneyama of Wako Securities.
   ``The dollar does not seem to be falling further and there is no
pessimism in the air,'' he added.
   The dollar stabilized after reports that the Bank of Japan
stepped in to brake the currency's fall.
   Noburu Yokohashi, an official in the treasury division at
Dai-Ichi Kangyo Bank, said Japan's central bank was placing orders
to buy dollars in ``considerable amounts.''
</TEXT>
