<1ST_LINE>r w PM-WashingtoninBrief     04-15 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Washington in Brief,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Panel Approves Mandatory Life Sentence for Genocide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The full Senate is being asked to consider
legislation under which Americans convicted of genocide killings
would receive a mandatory sentence of life imprisonment without
parole.
   Genocide is the attempt to destroy or the destruction of a
national, ethnic, racial or religious group.
   The legislation, approved unanimously Thursday by the Senate
Judiciary Committee, would be the final step in linking the United
States with 96 other countries that have ratified the Genocide
Convention approved by the United Nations on Dec. 9, 1948.
   The Senate ratified the treaty 83-11 on Feb. 19, 1986, but it
could not be put into force without the criminal penalties
established in the current legislation. The mandatory life sentence
would apply to anyone found guilty by an international tribunal of
participating in acts of genocide that result in death.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Companies To Phase Out High-Estrogen Birth Control Pills</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government says birth control pill
manufacturers have agreed to phase out high-estrogen pills based on
a finding that they are no more effective than lower-dose pills and
could heighten the risk of blood clotting.
   The Food and Drug Administration said Thursday the three
manufacturers _ G.D. Searle and Co., Ortho Pharmaceutical Corp. and
Syntex Corp. _ will phase out distribution of the pills over a
six-month period to allow physicians time to switch their patients
to lower-dose estrogen pills.
   The action follows a recommendation by an FDA advisory panel
that the high-dose pills _ those containing more than 50 micrograms
of estrogen _ be withdrawn because of the heightened risk of blood
clotting.
   ``I applaud the responsible decision of these manufacturers,''
FDA Commissioner Frank E. Young said in a statement. ``Low dose
contraceptives are quite safe and, for healthy young women, are
considered to be the most effective reversible means of preventing
pregnancy.''
   The most commonly prescribed birth control pills contain 30
micrograms to 35 micrograms of estrogen and are not affected by the
phaseout. The ones being withdrawn contain from 75 micrograms to
100 micrograms of estrogen.
   They are sold by Syntex as Norinyl 2 and Norinyl 1 + 80, by
Searle as Enovid E-21 and Ovulen, and by Ortho as Ortho-Novum 1@80
and Ortho-Novum 2 mg.
</TEXT>
