<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0620EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DonorDilemma     04-15 0550</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Donor Dilemma,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Doctors Discuss Ethics of Harvesting Donor Organs from Doomed
Infants</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES LITKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The immediate harvesting of organs from infants
born with most of their brains missing could threaten entire groups
of patients who have lost the capacity for thought, two medical
ethicists say.
   Such a policy of taking the organs for transplant before the
infants are declared brain dead also violates medical ethics, said
John Arras and Dr. Shlomo Shinnar, writing in today's Journal of
the American Medical Association.
   Because these infants, called anencephalic, inevitably die
within days or weeks and many children require organ transplants, a
debate has begun over the appropriateness of using anencephalics as
donors _ and how soon.
   ``These arguments are by no means unique to anencephalic
newborns,'' Arras and Shinnar wrote in their commentary.
   ``They are equally applicable to other severely damaged infants
as well as adults in permanent vegetative states. We do not believe
society is willing to harvest organs from living patients who have
permanently lost the capacity for intelligent thought.''
   Anencephalic infants have a brain stem, enabling them to
breathe. They have no cerebral cortex, the part of the brain
allowing thought and voluntary movement.
   Between 2,000 and 3,000 anencephalic infants are among the 3
million children born in the United States each year, the federal
Centers for Disease Control estimates.
   ``Organ donation is very laudable, and people say these kids
will inevitably die,'' Shinnar, a pediatric neurologist at
Montefiore Medical Center, The Albert Einstein College of Medicine,
said in a telephone interview from New York.
   But he added, ``What if there are not enough anencephalics and
the transplant needs are greater two years from now? Who do we look
at next?''
   The debate intensified in October following newspaper reports
that organs had been harvested from anencephalic infants and
transplanted into other children in West Germany and California.
   ``In the West German case, they took a baby from delivery, put a
tube (of oxygen) in its mouth, took it to the operating room,
harvested the organs and buried it,'' Shinnar said.
   ``And in the United States, although it did not pass, there was
a bill in the legislature in California to have these children
declared `brain-dead' at birth,'' he said.
   Legal definitions of brain death used in making medical
determinations require an end of all brain functions, including
those of the brain stem, Shinnar said.
   In December, the Loma Linda (Calif.) University Medical Center
developed a medical protocol under which anencephalic babies are to
be used for transplants only after brain death occurs.
   Six anencephalic infants were kept alive by respirator for a
week under those guidelines, though none ultimately became an organ
donor, said Loma Linda spokeswoman Anita Rockwell.
   ``We wrote our article before the protocol was developed,''
Shinnar said, ``and this certainly lessens the magnitude of the
ethical debate.''
   But, he said, ``this protocol is not without its problems as
well. What about extending the tragedy for the parents of an
anencephalic child?''
   Anencephaly can be detected before birth with ultrasound, the
commentary said, and some doctors consider abortion appropriate as
late as the final three months of pregnancy.
   ``Should we be encouraging pregnant women, in essence, to carry
these children to term to provide spare parts?'' Shinnar said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0047 </DOCNO>
