<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Afghan-Reax     04-15 0553</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Afghan-Reax,0570</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Afghans in Camps Greet Accord with Skepticism, Indifference</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Afghanistan, Bjt</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for item listed as PM-Afghan-World Reax on digest.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BRYAN WILDER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PESHAWAR, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   There was no signs of celebration in
Peshawar's hot and dusty streets, no shots fired into the air as
people do in Central Asia when they are happy about something.
   The Soviets had just signed the Red Army's ticket home from
neighboring Afghanistan, but the prevailing mood among Afghan
refugees encamped here for years was skepticism and indifference.
   Tanvir Ahmad, a taxi driver, said: ``Agreement? What agreement?
... It will make no difference. The war will end when the refugees
go home.''
   In Camp No. 6 of the nearby border town of Munda sat 34-year-old
Israyal Ghairad, a school teacher from Kunar province in
northeastern Afghanistan
   ``We're not concerned with this agreement,'' Ghairad said of the
accords signed Thursday in Geneva.
   The Afghan Moslem guerrillas were not invited to the
negotiations that produced the withdrawal settlement. The accord
was signed by Pakistan, Afghanistan, the United States and Soviet
Union.
   Ghairad said Pakistan and Afghanistan are not ``the real parties
to this war.''
   The Afghan rebels say the conflict is with the Soviets and not
the government in Kabul, the Afghan capital, which they consider a
Kremlin puppet. The guerrillas say no agreement is valid without
their participation.
   The seven-party guerrilla alliance did not issue a statement
after the signing Thursday, but said a resolution would be read
Saturday at a public rally outside Peshawar, the Pakistani border
city that serves as its headquarters.
   The statement is expected to repeat the guerrillas' position
that they will continue fighting until the last Soviet soldier
leaves Afghan soil. The Geneva agreement calls for the estimated
115,000 Soviet troops who began arriving in 1979 to begin leaving
May 15 and be out within nine months.
   Ghairad said: ``We will wait and see if there is entire peace in
Afghanistan and the Communists are no longer in power.''
   He said his family of five will not return home until he feels
it is safe there, and predicted the 5 million other Afghan refugees
in Pakistan and Iran would do the same.
   Tony Land, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees
representative in Peshawar, said it was too early to prepare for a
return home by the refugees.
   Countries in both the East and West hailed the troop withdrawal
accord as a vital first step toward peace, and some offered to help
Afghan refugees.
   But skepticism remained over some aspects of the agreement,
particularly continued aid to combatants.
   The Times of India, an independent English-language daily, said
in an editorial titled ``Meaningless Agreement'':
   ``Moscow will be able to withdraw its troops without having to
acknowledge the plain fact that it has failed to pacify Afghanistan
in the face of resistance by U.S.-backed mujahedeen (guerrillas).
But on the face of it, the agreement will be pretty meaningless
otherwise.
   ``For it will stipulate that the Americans and the Russians will
continue to be entitled to provide arms to their respective
clients. And while Pakistan will formally agree not to interfere in
Afghanistan's internal affairs, it will in reality continue to do
so inasmuch as it will still serve as a conduit for U.S. arms
supplies to the mujahedeen.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
