<DOCNO> AP880415-0049 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0601EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-CDC-AIDS     04-15 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-CDC-AIDS,0527</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Early Results Show 0.3 Percent of Hospital Patients AIDS-Infected</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Three patients in 1,000 were infected with the
AIDS virus, according to anonymous blood tests at four Midwestern
hospitals, but researchers say that rate of infection doesn't
necessarily apply to the nation.
   The national Centers for Disease Control, attempting to gauge
the prevalence of AIDS infection of the virus that causes AIDS,
tested blind blood samples from non-AIDS patients at 40
``sentinel'' hospitals in 30 cities.
   In results from the first four hospitals enrolled in the
program, all in the Midwest, 0.3 percent of the 12,000 tested
patients showed signs of AIDS virus infection, the CDC said in a
report made public Thursday.
   The early data, however, may not be representative of the
nation, said Dr. Tim Dondero, a CDC AIDS researcher. ``You can't do
a national estimate based on four spots,'' he said.
   Federal health officials continue to estimate that between 1
million and 1.5 million Americans are infected with AIDS virus.
   ``No new data have become available to prompt a change of this
estimate,'' the CDC said, adding, ``accurate estimates of the
prevalence ... of (AIDS virus) infection in the entire U.S.
population are not possible at this time.'' The agency expects to
enroll all 40 hospitals in its testing program by September.
   If 1.5 million of the nation's estimated 240 million population
were infected, the rate would be about 0.6 percent, about twice as
high as the early CDC results. One million Americans would be about
0.4 percent.
   The four hospitals reported that antibodies indicating AIDS
infection were more common among adults 25 to 44. Rates also were
higher for blacks and Hispanics than for whites, and higher for men
than for women, the CDC said.
   Those rates are comparable to national AIDS statistics, Dondero
noted, adding, ``The data look right.''
   As of this week, 59,287 cases of acquired immune deficiency
syndrome itself have been reported in the United States, according
to the CDC. The disease has so far killed 33,060, or 56 percent of
those patients.
   The CDC's report summarized the agency quarterly presentation on
AIDS to the Domestic Policy Council last month. The report also
reviewed tests among prisoners and among childbearing women.
   Out of 29,193 federal inmates tested by the U.S. Bureau of
Prisons since last June, 843, or 2.9 percent, have tested positive
for AIDS virus infection. That is little changed from a Justice
Department announcement last fall, when 3 percent of the first
inmates tested were positive.
   The CDC said it hopes to contract with the National Institute of
Justice and with a ``major university'' for AIDS testing of 10,000
inmates at 10 state prisons beginning this June.
   In 52,326 tests of childbearing women in the state of New York,
researchers found an AIDS virus infection rate of 0.8 percent, the
CDC said. In New York City, one woman in 61 showed antibodies
against the AIDS virus, and 40 percent of those women passed the
infections on to their newborn children, the CDC added.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0050 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Clanton     04-15 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Clanton,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Inmate Who Escaped from Death Row Is Executed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE TAYLOR</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>RICHMOND, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Earl Clanton Jr. had pleaded for his life
and even escaped once from death row, but in the end he walked
wide-eyed and silent to his death in Virginia's electric chair for
the 1980 killing of a librarian.
   Rebuffed by the U.S. Supreme Court after his lawyers made a
frantic plea, Clanton, 33, was administered two jolts of
electricity late Thursday night and pronounced dead at 11:07 p.m.
   Outside the prison, about 50 opponents of capital punishment
conducted a vigil and prayer service. They were interrupted by a
single supporter of the death penalty who shouted, ``Pray for the
woman that died.''
   Clanton had been on death row since 1981 for the robbery and
strangling of Wilhemina Smith, a Petersburg school librarian who
lived in his apartment building.
   On Tuesday, U.S. District Judge Robert R. Merhige Jr. granted
Clanton a stay to review evidence of childhood abuse that the
condemned man said he suffered. Attorneys for Clanton said he had
suppressed memories of the abuse and thus was incompetent to help
his trial lawyer in offering mitigating evidence at the sentencing
hearing.
   A three-judge panel of the 4th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals
overturned Merhige on Thursday afternoon, prompting a hurried
effort by Clanton's lawyers to stop the execution.
   The federal appeals court said that Clanton's case had been
given least 10 reviews in state and federal courts and that his
sentencing had been found constitutional.
   On Thursday night, the U.S. Supreme Court refused a stay in a
7-2 decision, with Justices William Brennan and Thurgood Marshall
dissenting, and Gov. Gerald L. Baliles turned down a petition for
clemency.
   Clanton was visited by his mother, sister, two aunts and his
lawyers as the execution hour approached, said C. Dwight Perry, the
prison's operations officer.
   He also was visited by Jay North, the 1960s child television
star of ``Dennis the Menace.'' North has been working on a movie
about the 1984 escape of Clanton and five other Virginia death row
inmates.
   ``We became extremely close friends,'' said North, who opposes
the death penalty. ``We've been in contant communication, wrote and
called. We became like brothers.''
   Witnesses to the execution said Clanton was wide-eyed and
impassive and appeared only a little nervous as he was led into the
death chamber.
   In an interview Monday with the Norfolk Virginian-Pilot and The
Ledger-Star, Clanton complained about pressure being exerted by the
state to have him executed at the scheduled time.
   ``Why kill me today and be wrong in just a few months later?''
he said. ``What is the urgency? Why such an urgency to take such a
life.''
   In May 1984, Clanton was one of six death row inmates who
escaped from the Mecklenburg Correctional Center. He was recaptured
the next day at a coin laundry in Warrenton, N.C.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
