<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-Simon     04-15 0257</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Simon,0264</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Simon Says It's Time to Slow Down</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   After 40 years as one of America's most
successful playwrights, Neil Simon says he's thinking about taking
things a little easier.
   Simon, 60, was just 31 when his first play, ``Come Blow Your
Horn,'' opened on Broadway. Prior to that, he was a television
reporter for 10 years.
   ``That's 40 years of writing,'' he said in a recent interview.
``I don't anticipate grazing on a farm someplace, but this pace I
don't need anymore.
   ``Maybe I'll just write plays for regional theaters an not think
about going to Broadway. Maybe I'll stop in a couple of years and
just do watercolors. I don't know. I can't think beyond these two
plays. I only think in the present,'' said Simon, who has had 22
plays on Broadway.
   The two plays that are currently occupying his thoughts are
numbers 23 and 24.
   His 23rd Broadway production is ``Jake's Women,'' which is
already finished. The story of a writer and the ladies in his life
is scheduled to open in New York next year.
   Number 24 is a farce he is rewriting called ``Rumors,''
scheduled to make its world premiere at San Diego's Old Globe
Theatre in September before becoming his 24th play for the Broadway
stage.
   ``There's nothing safe in `Rumors,''' he said. ``It's a farce _
a style of comedy I've never written before. It's the most
complicated thing I've ever written .... I doubt if I'll ever do
another farce, because it's exhausting.''
</TEXT>
