<1ST_LINE>r a PM-HungryMigrants     04-15 0489</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hungry Migrants,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Workers Going Hungry Waiting For Berry-Picking Season to Open</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARILYNN WHEELER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As many as 25,000 migrant workers have
arrived in Oregon more than a month before the strawberry crop is
ready to pick, and thousands are without food or shelter, relief
agencies say.
   Last year, there weren't enough workers to pick an early harvest
of strawberries, and 20 percent of the state's crop rotted in the
fields. Growers complained that Mexican pickers were confused over
the Immigration Reform Act of 1986 and refused to cross the border.
   This year, social service agencies are stretching to help an
estimated 18,000 to 25,000 early arrivals.
   ``Word got out that there were a lot of jobs and everybody was
afraid there would be such a rush that when they showed up it would
be too late,'' said Titus Herman of the Salvation Army.
   Marta Garcia, who operates the House of Zion emergency shelter
in Marion County, said she often sees 50 or 60 people living in one
room when they deliver food to migrant camps.
   ``We have people in the backyard in tents. We even have people
staying in the camper of our pickup because there's no place else
to go,'' she said. ``Everywhere you see that. They have no water,
no facilities. Many come here to take baths.''
   A Washington County grower who asked not to be identified said
many workers are asking farmers to sign papers saying they worked
for them at least 90 days each year from 1984 to 1986, as required
by the new law.
   ``A lot of them can't get legalized, but hope people will fill
out the forms for them,'' he said.
   The illegal workers are ``just hoping and praying they won't get
asked for papers, that farmers will be lenient toward them,'' Mrs.
Garcia said. ``We bring it up to them all the time, and they say,
`It's just the chance we're taking.'''
   David Beebe, district director of the U.S. Immigration and
Naturalization Service, said the law allows special agricultural
workers to enter the country this year if they pay a $185
application fee and promise to provide papers from former employers.
   The law offers amnesty to illegal aliens who have been in the
United States since before 1982.
   The amnesty application deadline is May 4, a date that has
confused some migrants, the Washington County grower said. Some
workers arrived early because they believed they could not cross
the border next month.
   ``Right now the (strawberry) crop looks very good, but it's
still too early to say,'' said the grower, who is providing hoeing
work for 15 to 20 people.
   ``I think everyone in Mexico now understands how the rules work.
... They say they're going to stay here: `We're going to wait for
the work.' I think they all realize that this is the last
opportunity to harvest in the Northwest.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
