<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Hijack-Passenger     04-15 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Hijack-Passenger,0503</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Citizen Says Hijackers Missed Driver's License</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN RICE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KUWAIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Arab hijackers of a Kuwait Airways jumbo jet
overlooked the U.S. driver's license of an Egyptian-American, who
said he feared being harmed if his captors knew of his American
citizenship.
   On Thursday, more than 2,000 Kuwaitis attended the funeral of
two countrymen killed by the hijackers. Many of the mourners said
their country should never give in to the sky pirates' demands that
17 convicted terrorists imprisoned in Kuwait be released.
   Ramadan Ali, a consulting engineer who travels widely and holds
both Egyptian and United States citizenship, said he hid his U.S.
passport in his briefcase and showed only his Egyptian documents.
   ``One of them searched my wallet, and there was my (U.S.)
driver's license,'' Ali said during an interview at the home of a
relative in Kuwait. ``I was so lucky. He didn't realize what it
was.''
   He declined to give his American address because ``these guys,
they have long hands.''
   Ali was one of 12 passengers freed Tuesday night shortly before
the hijackers of the Boeing 747 flew from Cyprus to Algeria with
more than 30 passengers and crew still aboard. The Kuwait Airways
plane was seized April 5 on a flight from Bangkok.
   Ali, who displayed bruises on his wrists, said the hijackers put
plastic handcuffs on the passengers while the plane was in Mashhad,
Iran, where it first landed last week.
   His eight days as a hostage left him nervous, emotionally
stunned and wary of flying, Ali said.
   ``It became to me like a phobia,'' he said. ``It could happen
again.''
   Ali said the hijackers asked the branch of Islam he belonged to:
Sunni or Shiite.
   All of Kuwaitis released so far have been Shiites, members of
the branch that predominates in Iran and southern Lebanon, but is a
minority in the Islamic world.
   ``I was reading the Koran all the time. They noticed I'm a
religious person,'' he said, speculating that might have helped his
release.
   On Thursday, a military honor guard escorted the flag-draped
bodies of Khalid Ayyub Bandar, 20, and Abdullah Shibib al-Khalidi,
24, into a graveyard in Kuwait.
   The two men were beaten, shot and their bodies dumped on the
tarmac at the Larnaca, Cyprus airport, where the plane sat for five
days.
   Kuwait's crown prince, Sheik Saad Abdullah Al-Sabah, led the
procession of mourners along a condolence line of more than 60 male
relatives of the slain men.
   ``Even if they kill all the hostages there on the plane, we'll
never, ever release the killers who are here in Kuwait,'' said one
mourner, Faisal al-Marzouk, chief editor of Al-Anbaa newspaper.
   Like him, many of the mourners supported Kuwait's refusal to
free the 17 pro-Iranian terrorists who were convicted in a series
of bombings in December 1983 at the U.S. and French embassies in
Kuwait.
</TEXT>
