<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Japan-Markets     04-15 0329</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0339</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar, Stocks Fall In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Both the U.S. dollar and stock prices closed the
week sharply lower in Tokyo today following the announcement of
worse-than-expected U.S. trade figures for February.
   The dollar closed at 124.13 yen, down 2.02 yen from its close on
Thursday, but up slightly from its 123.95-yen opening level. During
the day, it ranged between 123.90 and 124.22 yen in moderate
trading.
   Dealers attributed the dollar's fall to the $13.8 billion U.S.
trade deficit in February, announced by the Commerce Department in
Washington on Thursday.
   ``The larger-than-expected U.S. trade deficit prompted the
dollar-selling in early trading, but the currency stabilized after
reports of intervention by the Bank of Japan and due to
profit-taking by export-related industries,'' said a trader at a
major commercial bank, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Kazuma Takasugi of the Bank of Tokyo said the dollar had
remained fairly stable during the day because participants were
nervous about possible additional intervention by the Bank of Japan.
   On the Tokyo Stock Exchange, the Nikkei Stock Average of 225
selected issues, which closed at a record 27,111.35 points
Thursday, lost 217.78 points to end the day at 26,893.57. The
decline came after four consecutive days of record highs for the
Nikkei index.
   ``The overnight setback on Wall Street and the weaker dollar,
coupled with profit taking, brought share prices sharply lower
during early trading,'' said Taketomi Kikuchi of Sanyo Securites.
   ``Toward the end of trading, share prices eased mainly because
of a wait-and-see attitude toward the dollar and the coming
weekend,'' he said.
   Kikuchi said trading was calm, with no concern among
participants that the market had risen too far.
   Among the losers were export-related issues, such as electricals
and precision machineries. Some large-capital issues also moved
lower.
   Volume on the market's first section was estimated at 1 billion
shares, down from 1.2 billion shares Thursday. Declining issues
outpaced advancers by 674 to 260, while 127 were unchanged.
</TEXT>
