<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BigToad     04-15 0212</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Big Toad,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>World's Largest Toad Dies of `Biological Accident'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DES MOINES, Iowa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 5-pound, 1{-ounce South American toad
recognized as the world's largest has died apparently of old age,
but zoo officials said they're not sure just how old she was.
   ``She was not obese, just a very healthy specimen,'' Blank Park
Zoo director David Allen said Thursday of Toad A, known as ``Toad''
to her keepers.
   Terming the death a ``biological accident,'' Allen said
pathology tests are being conducted on Toad A to confirm the cause
of her April 8 death.
   Toad A, stretching to 9{ inches, was accepted late last year
into the Guinness Book of World Records as the largest toad on
Earth.
   A Miami animal dealer sold the South American toad to the zoo in
1983. At that time she was estimated to be 2 years old, Allen said,
but zoo keepers believe she may have been older than 8 when she
died.
   ``Toad's notoriety was an attraction for the zoo and we're very
disappointed at the loss,'' Allen said. ``A lot of people planned
on seeing Toad on exhibit at the zoo this summer.''
   Many may still get a chance.
   Toad A might be freeze-dried so she can be displayed, zoo
officials said.
</TEXT>
