<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0608EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Mexico-Drugs     04-15 0565</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Drugs,0581</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mexico Rejects Senate Vote on Drug Certification</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-US-Drugs, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Mexican government rejected as meddling
in its domestic affairs a U.S. Senate vote revoking President
Reagan's certification that Mexico was doing its part to combat
drug trafficking.
   The Senate approved a resolution Thursday that also would slap
trade and economic aid sanctions against Mexico. But the measure
stands little chance of passage in the U.S. House of
Representatives and is almost certain to be vetoed by Reagan.
   In a brief statement Thursday night, Mexico's Foreign Ministry
rejected the U.S. action as ``foreign interference'' in Mexican
affairs.
   ``No power can claim for itself the right to certify the conduct
of other societies or governments. No one has the right to impose
from abroad conduct, ideas, political or economic systems on other
peoples,'' the statement said.
   Under U.S. law, Mexico would stand to lose American support in
international lending institutions for new loans to the country if
the resolution became binding.
   The federal attorney general's office, which is responsible for
overseeing Mexico's narcotics efforts to find and destroy drugs,
issued its own strongly-worded statement late Thursday night
insisting that ``Mexico is undertaking a plain effort of
international cooperation in the campaign against drug
trafficking.''
   It expressed ``profound astonishment and its great displeasure
with the resolution taken by the United States Senate, in that (the
Senate) does not recognize the enormous effort of the Mexican
people to combat a problem whose causes are not, certainly,
attributable to Mexico.''
   The statement cited ``the vast consumer market'' for drugs, in a
clear reference to U.S. demand, as sustaining the illicit narcotics
trade.
   Mexico receives little economic aid from the United States. But
officials here are concerned about a requirement under 1986 law
that U.S. representatives in multilateral lending institutions must
vote against future loans to countries whose certification is
revoked.
   Mexico has a $105 billion foreign debt, and depends heavily on
its relationship with foreign lenders.
   Officials point out that about one-quarter of Mexico's
100,000-member armed forces is permanently assigned to narcotics
interdiction and eradication operations.
   Mexican officials also have insisted they could use more
financial assistance from the United States in fighting drugs. As
recently as 1986, U.S. anti-drug assistance to Mexico was about
half that provided for eliminating the screwworm in Mexican cattle.
   More than 100 army troops and federal judicial policemen have
been killed over the past 10 years during drug operations,
according to Mexican army figures.
   Relations between the two countries have been soured by mutual
accusations surrounding the Feb. 7, 1985 kidnapping of U.S. Drug
Enforcement agent Enrique Camarena Salazar.
   The bodies of Camarena and Alfredo Zavala Avelar, a Mexican
pilot who worked with him in anti-narcotics programs from their
base in Guadalajara, were found on March 5, 1985.
   American officials charged that Mexican authorities were slow in
seeking out and arresting several drug barons who allegedly ordered
the killings.
   Attorney General Sergio Garcia Ramirez has called for an end to
mutual recriminations between Mexico and the United States over
their contributions to the fight against the drug trade.
   ``We find it difficult to accept the opinion held in the United
States of what really goes on in Mexico,'' Garcia Ramirez said.
``The border is not a border between black and white, good and
evil. It is a border between countries.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
