<HEAD>Late Porn Star Confessed To Role In Slayings, Ex-Wife Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pornographic film star John Holmes tearfully
confessed to a role in the bludgeoning deaths of four people,
charges he was acquitted of in 1982, his ex-wife said.
   Holmes, who died last month of complications stemming from AIDS,
told his ex-wife, Sharon Holmes, that he led three killers to a
hillside home and stood by while they murdered four people, the Los
Angeles Times reported in Thursday's editions.
   Ms. Holmes, who divorced the actor in 1984, said in a recent
interview with the newspaper that Holmes confessed his role to her
shortly after the slayings in July 1981.
   However, he said he didn't participate in the murders and never
told her the names of the killers, she said.
   Another woman who had a longtime intimate relationship with
Holmes and asked not to be identified said he made a similar
admission to her, the newspaper said. She reported that admission
to police in 1981.
   Together, the women's stories corroborate the Los Angeles Police
Department's theory of how the killings happened.
   Holmes, who died March 13 at age 43, was tried and acquitted in
a 1982 trial. No one but Holmes has ever been charged in the murder
of Ronald Launius, 37; William DeVerell, 42; Joy Audrey Miller, 46;
and Barbara Richardson, 22.
   The actor appeared in hundreds of sexually explicit films in the
1970s and early '80s, when he was the porn industry's leading male
star.
