<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PRIDEConference     04-15 0260</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-PRIDE Conference,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Nancy Reagan Says Goodbye To Anti-Drug Group</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto AX4</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nancy Reagan made her last appearance as first
lady before an anti-drug group's conference, telling students,
youth leaders and teachers she will be with them ``in spirit''
after her husband leaves office in January.
   ``These past eight years of work against drugs have brought new
meaning to my life, and I will not abandon what we are
accomplishing,'' Mrs. Reagan said Thursday in remarks to the PRIDE
International Conference on Youth and Drugs.
   Mrs. Reagan, making her fifth annual appearence, drew frequent
cheers from the crowd of 3,000 amid a pep-rally atmosphere. The
conference was the 11th sponsored by the Parents' Resource
Institute for Drug Education.
   The first lady told the young people that they pose ``a threat
to the dealers and the traffickers ... a danger to the drug
attitudes that have ruled this country for the past two decades.''
   ``It's the young people who will solve the drug crisis in this
country,'' she said. ``We could have parents following their
children's every move. We could have drug agents on every corner,
treatment centers on every block, jails in every neighborhood, and
still there would be a demand for drugs.
   ``What will win the battle against drugs is a change in
attitudes, and that's exactly what you're accomplishing,'' she
said. ``While I won't be able to come here every year as I have in
the past, I'll be with you in spirit.''
   Attorney General Edwin Meese III also spoke to the group
Thursday.
