<1ST_LINE>r a PM-`Colors'Protest     04-15 0475</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-`Colors' Protest,0488</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Filmmakers: Movie Doesn't Glorify Gang Violence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SUE MANNING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The movie ``Colors'' opens today in 425
theaters across the country amid protests by the Guardian Angels
and others who claim the street-gang drama will incite violence.
   But Dennis Hopper, the film's director, called the protesters
``irresponsible'' and said they were encouraging ``blood to flow in
the streets.''
   The movie stars Sean Penn and Robert Duvall as gang-fighting Los
Angeles policemen. The movie, which used active Los Angeles-area
gang members as extras and advisers, portrays the world of the
Crips and the Bloods, rival gangs, who use the colors blue and red,
respectively, to distinguish themselves.
   Some theaters planned to increase security today as the film
opened.
   In Chicago, police Supt. LeRoy Martin said extra police might be
assigned to patrol near theaters where ``Colors'' is playing. He
said the film might send a message that there is ``something clever
and hip about being a gang member.''
   Six Guardian Angels including Curtis Sliwa, the founder of the
volunteer crime-fighting group, were arrested Thursday on charges
of disorderly conduct when they tried to enter the New York City
office of the film's distributor, Orion Pictures.
   ``The movie ... glorifies street crack youth gangs,'' Sliwa
declared during a rally in front of the midtown Manhattan building.
The group had announced plans to ``take over'' the office.
   Sliwa said the film provides a virtual ``how-to'' of street
violence, including the killing of a police officer, and fosters
negative stereotypes by depicting minority youths as violent toughs.
   But Hopper said the protesters ``are whipping up the probability
and the possibility'' of violence. ``The people who are saying
blood is going to flow in the streets are asking for blood to flow
in the streets.''
   Charles O. Glenn, executive vice president of Orion Pictures,
said the movie is a statement of conscience and could ``shock''
children into avoiding drugs and violence.
   ``If there is anything this picture does not do _ it does not
glorify gangs or gang violence,'' Glenn said. ``We feel that
`Colors' is an honest and socially responsible portrayal of a
problem that obviously exists in Los Angeles and in the streets of
every other American city.''
   However, Wes McBride, president of the California Gang
Investigators Association, said ``Colors'' will ``leave dead bodies
from one end of this town to the other.''
   In Seattle, the local Guardian Angels group threatened to seek a
court injunction if Seattle theaters show ``Colors'' and said a
protest would begin tonight at the UA Cinema 150 in downtown
Seattle.
   ``Each one of us was horrified by what we saw on the screen,''
said Patti Whitehead, Guardian Angels chapter leader, after she and
others previewed the movie Wednesday night. ``The movie as we saw
it was a simple recruitment for gang members.''
</TEXT>
