<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Dollar-Gold     04-15 0337</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0357</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Falls, Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar was mostly lower in thin late-morning
European trading today, even though apprehension about possible
central bank intervention was supporting the currency, traders said.
   Gold prices rose.
   Traders predicted little substantial change in the dollar before
the weekend, but warned that the dollar could come under heavy
pressure early next week.
   Dealers said the U.S. February trade deficit of $13.83 billion,
announced Thursday, had confirmed many traders' worst suspicions
about the long-term trend of the U.S. trade imbalance.
   The markets had expected January's $12.44 billion deficit to
improve.
   ``The only thing that will really cure the U.S. trade gap is a
recession and I don't see that happening in election year,'' said a
trader with a major U.S. commercial bank in Milan.
   Another Milan trader predicted the dollar will face heavy
selling pressure when the markets open on Monday.
   ``Traders had a busy day yesterday and are waiting for the
weekend,'' he said. ``The real war will begin on Monday.''
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 2.02 yen to a closing 124.13. Later, in London, it was
quoted at 124.10 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Thursday:
   _1.6645 West German marks, up from 1.6635
   _1.3743 Swiss francs, down from 1.3745
   _5.6458 French francs, up from 5.6390
   _1.8673 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8680
   _1,234.85 Italian lire, down from 1,244
   _1.2330 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2368
   In London, the British pound was quoted at $1.8817, compared
with $1.8755 Thursday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $452.90 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $451. At midmorning Friday, the
city's five major bullion dealers fixed a recommended price of
$453.85.
   In Zurich, the bid price was also $453.85, up from $450.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $5.45 to close at a bid $454.93.
   Silver was quoted in London today at a bid price of $6.48 a troy
ounce, up from Thursday $6.43.
</TEXT>
