<2ND_LINE>PM-Schnick Trial,0291</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dairy Farmer Convicted In Three Of Seven Slayings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSHFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 37-year-old dairy farmer was convicted
of three counts of first-degree murder in connection with the
slayings of seven members of his family, a rampage he at first
blamed on a 14-year-old victim.
   James E. Schnick of Elkland wept with his face buried in his
hands when the verdicts were read early Thursday night. The jury
deliberated about two hours after hearing 2{ days of testimony.
   The jury was scheduled to return this morning to receive
instructions for the sentencing phase of the trial. The jury must
recommend either the death penalty or life in prison without
probation or parole.
   Schnick was convicted in the deaths of his wife, Julie, and two
nephews, 14-year-old Kirk Buckner and 2-year-old Michael Buckner.
   He also was accused, but not tried, in the deaths of his
brother-in-law, Steve Buckner; Buckner's wife, Jeannette, and the
Buckners' other sons, Dennis, 8, and Timmy, 6. Buckner and Mrs.
Schnick were brother and sister.
   Darlene Beisiegel, the mother of Mrs. Buckner, said one question
remained unanswered for her.
   ``I just wanted to know why he did it,'' she said. ``I think it
was cold-blooded.''
   All the victims were killed Sept. 25 in an early-morning
shooting spree at two dairy farms in nearby Elkland.
   Schnick originally blamed the slayings on his nephew Kirk, a
revelation that shocked members of the community who knew the
teen-ager. Within days, however, Schnick himself was charged in
connection with the seven deaths.
   Investigators discovered, among other inconsistencies, that Kirk
Buckner was left-handed. The .22-caliber revolver used in the
killings was found in Kirk's right hand.
</TEXT>
