<HEAD>Singer Dennis Day Returns Home From Hospital</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 4th graf, `Doctors determined ...,' to insert Day's age.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer Dennis Day has returned home
after spending five weeks at a hospital for treatment of a head
injury following a fall at his home, a spokeswoman said.
   Day, a mainstay on Jack Benny's radio and television shows, was
released from St. John's Hospital and Health Center Wednesday
night, and is ``home with nurses and all the necessary trappings,''
said his publicist, Kitty Davis.
   ``He is alert and conscious but he's having therapy,'' Ms. Davis
said Thursday. ``The main therapy is that he's home with his
family.''
   Doctors determined last summer that Day, 71, was suffering from
amyotropic lateral sclerosis, a progressive nerve disorder also
known as Lou Gehrig's disease.
   On March 9, Day fell at his Bel Air-area home, and complained of
a severe headache immediately afterward. A diagnosis showed
bleeding in the brain and Day underwent emergency surgery.
   Day, born Eugene Denis McNulty in New York City, began his
career with Jack Benny in 1939. In addition to singing, he often
played a dim-witted straight man in comic dialogues with Benny.
