<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0801EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Britain-BirminghamSix     04-15 0386</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Britain-Birmingham Six,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Highest Court Turns Down ``Birmingham Six'' Appeal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Six Irishmen serving life sentences for the worst
terrorist attack in modern British history failed to win permission
to appeal their convictions before Britain's highest court.
   The defendants, known as the Birmingham Six, claimed they were
beaten into confessing and were wrongly convicted on faulty
forensic evidence for two Irish Republican Army pub bombings that
killed 21 people and injured 162 in the central England city of
Birmingham in 1974.
   The three Law Lords of the House of Lords, members of the
unelected upper legislative chamber who have expertise as judges,
rejected the men's bid to challenge their murder convictions
Thursday. They did not give reasons for their decision.
   The men's only option now would be to take their case to the
European Court of Human Rights.
   ``At some stage a future Home Secretary is going to have to deal
with the ongoing injustice to these men,'' said Gareth Pierce, a
lawyer for the six. The Home Secretary is the Cabinet minister
responsible for the administration of law and order.
   ``They simply can't spend the rest of their lives in prison when
they have committed no offense,'' Pierce said.
   The men were not present at the 90-minute preliminary hearing at
which the Law Lords were deciding whether to hear the case in full.
   In January, after a five-week court battle, the Court of Appeal
upheld their convictions and sent them back to prison.
   The Irish government believes the six may have been convicted
wrongly. The failure of the appeal in January contributed to a
severe strain in Anglo-Irish relations.
   The bombs exploded minutes apart at two pubs in Birmingham on
Nov. 21, 1974. Within hours, the six were rounded up among dozens
of suspects.
   Four signed confessions and two were said to have made verbal
admissions.
   In 1975, a court imposed multiple life sentences on Patrick
Hill, Hugh Callaghan, John Walker, Richard McIlkenny, Gerry Hunter
and William Power. Three of the men are in their 50s and three in
their 40s.
   The IRA, fighting British rule in Northern Ireland, claimed
responsibility for the bombings but said none of the six was
involved.
   The almost exclusively Catholic Irish Republican Army wants to
join the Protestant-dominated province and set up an all-Ireland
socialist state.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0070 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0803EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua     04-15 0500</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sandinista, Contra Commissions End Technical Talks, Report
Progress</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandinista and Contra commissions
charged with defining Nicaragua's cease-fire finished talks early
today with both sides reporting progress.
   High-level government and rebel leaders, meanwhile, planned to
meet later today in the capital of Managua for the first time to
further negotiations toward lasting peace.
   The Sandinista and Contra commissions, meeting in Sapoa on the
Costa Rican border, said they achieved ``considerable progress''
and ``reconciled differences of the earlier meeting,'' according to
an official statement issued by both sides.
   They remaining differences were not known, but both sides said
they would take them up in the high-level meeting today.
   The two sides held six technical meetings since March 28 and
managed only to agree on seven zones in which the Contra combatants
are to gather. They failed to define operating conditions within
the areas affecting security and resupply.
   The zones and the technical talks were outlined in the March 23
cease-fire pact signed by the Soviet-supplied Sandinistas and the
U.S.-backed Contras after three days of unprecedented direct
negotiations at the Sapoa border post, 90 miles south of the
capital.
   The goal is to end more than six years of war that have killed
more than 40,000 Nicaraguans.
   The commissions were defining the mechanics of the cease-fire,
which formally went into effect April 1.
   Under the plan, the Contra evacuation into the zones was to have
been completed by today. In return, the Sandinistas were to have
released 700 political prisoners, allowed humanitarian aid for the
rebels and permitted the insurgents to send representatives to take
part in internal political discussions.
   Two points contained in a Contra proposal had been termed
``non-negotiable'' by the Sandinistas. It would allow the
combatants to receive replacements of arms and ammunition inside
the zones while prohibiting the government from accepting military
aid, which comes from the Soviet bloc.
   The cease-fire pact allows only humanitarian aid to be
distributed by a neutral organization to the rebels. It does not
mention government supplies.
   The Contra delegation was to be headed by its Miami-based
directorate, made up of Adolfo Calero, Aristides Sanchez, Alfredo
Cesar, Maria Azucena Ferrey and Pedro Joaquin Chamorro.
   The government's delegation is headed by the nation's highest
military leader, Gen. Humberto Ortega, the brother of President
Daniel Ortega.
   Agreement is needed on a new deadline for the Contras to gather
into zones and for the Sandinistas to make their concessions, such
as the prisoner release. The pact now calls for a 60-day
cease-fire, which ends June 1.
   The Sandinistas and Contras still stand far apart on the issue
of laying down weapons, which is not mentioned in the cease-fire
plan. They do agree the rebel combatants can enter the zones with
their weapons.
   The Contras argue that they will never put down their arms until
Nicaragua is ``on the irreversible road to democracy.'' The
Sandinistas contend that disarmament must occur before
reintegration into civilian life.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0810EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-Lites     04-15 0252</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Lites,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>On The Light Side</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WARWICK, R.I. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tobias F. Schaeffer, known as a colleague
by the National Association of Real Estate Appraisers, is actually
Roy Schaeffer's 8-year-old cat Toby.
   ``I just wanted to prove that this organization doesn't screen
applicants,'' said Schaeffer, a Warwick real estate appraiser.
   But the association, which didn't like the idea of having a cat
for a colleague, has filed a $1 million lawsuit against Schaeffer,
the human, for registering Schaeffer, the feline.
   ``We feel he's hurt our organization by getting out there and
saying, `Hey, they had a cat as a member,''' director E. Kenneth
Twichell said Wednesday. ``Yes, we've had a cat as a member but
somebody defrauded us.''
   When a bank or savings and loan wants to hire an appraiser,
``they'll say, `Maybe it's a cat,''' Twichell said. The
16,000-member association is based in Scottsdale, Ariz. The suit
was filed in federal court in Phoenix.
   Schaeffer, after answering a direct-mail advertisement and
obtaining an application, signed Toby up two years ago to show
others in his office how simple it was to get an appraiser's
certificate from the association.
   He changed his cat's name to Tobias, gave it a middle initial _
F for Feline _ and sent in an $85 check. In return, the cat
received a gold-embossed appraiser's certificate, was listed in the
group's directory for 1986 and received a membership sticker.
   Twichell said certifiates are granted without screening because
the association does not expect experienced professionals to lie.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
