<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Germany-GasExplosion     04-15 0150</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Germany-Gas Explosion,0153</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Blast Rips Through Apartment Building Injuring 17 People</HEAD>
<DATELINE>COLOGNE, West Germany (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A gas explosion ripped through a
five-story apartment building in Cologne today and injured 17
people, three of them seriously, police said.
   The blast was in the Ehrenfeld district of the Rhine River city
shortly before 8 a.m., and there was ``extreme danger'' of the
structure collapsing, a police spokesman said on condition of
anonymity.
   Authorities feared some people may be buried in the rubble.
Rescue work at the site continued in the afternoon, they said.
   According to the spokesman, the blast left residents of at least
20 apartments homeless. The spokesman did not immediately say how
many people lived in the building.
   Police said the explosion may have been touched off by
construction work on a nearby subway system, and a local resident
complained of smelling gas shortly before the blast occurred.
</TEXT>
