<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Ethiopia     04-15 0540</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Ethiopia,0559</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Accuses Famine Relief Agencies Of Helping Rebels</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ADDIS ABABA, Ethiopia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethiopia said international relief
agencies it expelled were helping separatist rebels in the
drought-stricken north and that its own government relief program
could handle the crisis.
   But Western officials said the Soviet-backed government alone
will not be able to feed the millions threatened with starvation.
   In Washington, White House spokesman Marlin Fitzwater said the
United States would consult with the Soviet Union about urging
Ethiopia to allow food aid to resume.
   Last week the Marxist government ordered the expulsion of all
foreign aid workers from the northern provinces of Eritrea and
Tigre and said the situation was too dangerous for foreign relief
personnel.
   But an editorial by the state-run Ethiopia News Agency,
published on the front page of the Ethiopian Herald, said Thursday
that the International Committee of the Red Cross and other
agencies were aiding insurgents.
   The editorial accused unidentified relief agencies of committing
``serious crimes by transmitting false information to the world
about the drought situation ... through sophisticated communication
facilities which they had installed purportedly to ease relief
operations.''
   ``The International Committee of the Red Cross is at the
forefront of these, which have been directly or indirectly
supporting separatist bandits,'' it said.
   Rebels in Eritrea have been battling the government for 27 years
in Africa's longest civil war. In neighboring Tigre, rebels have
been fighting for 14 years.
   A special U.N. envoy arrived in Addis Ababa on Wednesday to
discuss the expulsions with government officials. About 60 Western
relief workers were ordered out of northern Ethiopia last week.
   A spokesman for the Geneva-based organization, Vincent Bernard,
refused comment.
   The United Nations also refused immediate comment. It had been
coordinating the huge northern relief operation that relies on food
from Western donors.
   Western aid officials, speaking on condition of anonymity, have
said they fear the government expelled relief workers to remove
witnesses from the war zone as it prepares for a major offensive
against the rebels.
   On Tuesday, the U.S. State Department accused the Marxist
government of sacrificing the interests of millions of its citizens
in pursuit of military objectives. Ethiopia denied the charge.
   An estimated 3.2 million people are facing starvation in the
northern regions.
   Until peace comes, all relief operations must be handled by the
government Relief and Rehabilitation Commission and other national
organizations, the editorial said.
   ``Refusal to go along with such (an) arrangement is tantamount
to interfering in our domestic affairs,'' it concluded.
   Berhanu Jembere, the chief Ethiopian relief official, has said
Western aid workers would be allowed back in the north only when
the area had been ``cleansed of bandits.''
   The government says it will be able to feed most northern
drought victims with help from Ethiopian organizations. But Berhanu
said the war effort took priority over relief operations and that
there could be a ``temporary stoppage'' of food distribution in
areas outside government control. Rebels now control most of Tigre
and much of Eritrea.
   Western relief officials say that at most 1 million people could
be fed from government-held distribution sites. They fear mass
migration of the hungry and have warned that deaths from starvation
could begin within weeks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
