<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Aquino 1stLd-Writethru a0507 04-15 0511</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Aquino, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0507,0522</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Aquino Receives Official Welcome to China</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with talks with Li Peng,
details; pickup 14th pvs, `Mrs. Aquino ... ADDS LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto BEJ1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JIM ABRAMS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino of the Philippines met
with Premier Li Peng and President Yang Shangkun today after
receiving an official welcome on her first visit to China.
   In two hours of talks in the Great Hall of the People, Mrs.
Aquino and Li discussed Cambodia, Afghanistan, disarmament and
U.S.-Soviet relations, the official Xinhua News Agency said.
   Mrs. Aquino also stressed that ``we stick to the policy of
non-interference in each other's internal affairs.'' China has
assured Manila that it no longer aids communist insurgents in the
Philippines. Mrs. Aquino said that the People's Republic is the
sole legal government representing China.
   It was not known whether the two spoke about trade issues. The
Philippines has sought a reduction in China's surplus in trade
between the two countries.
   Li, who was formally confirmed as premier at the just-concluded
session of China's legislature, the National People's Congress,
greeted Mrs. Aquino in English and said: ``Glad to meet you.
Welcome to Peking.''
   Yang noted that Chinese-Philippine contacts date back for
centuries and that ``the Chinese and Filipinos are relatives as
well as friends. We hope more and more Philippine friends will
visit China,'' Xinhua reported.
   The ancestors of Mrs. Aquino, like those of many Filipinos, came
from China. On her first day in China Thursday, Mrs. Aquino visited
the home of maternal great-grandfather in southern Fujian province.
   Mrs. Aquino said the warm reception she received in the village
of Hongjian ``was a reflection of the friendly feelings of the
Chinese people for the Philippine people.''
   Li and Yang accepted an invitation from Mrs. Aquino to visit the
Philippines, Xinhua said. No date was set.
   Yang presided over welcoming ceremonies earlier outside the hall.
   The new president, an 81-year-old general, accompanied Mrs.
Aquino on a review of a People's Liberation Army honor guard and
300 children dancing and waving bouquets. She received a 21-gun
salute from cannons on Tiananmen Square.
   Mrs. Aquino and Li spoke about Cambodia. Both Asian nations
support the rebels in their 9-year-old war against Vietnamese
troops in Cambodia.
   Mrs. Aquino, accompanied by two of her daughters, planned an
afternoon visit to the Forbidden City, home in the past to the
Chinese imperial family, and the Great Wall.
   Her three-day trip to China is her first abroad since November
1986, and was called risky by opposition leaders because of fears
of a coup following the escape of renegade military officer
Gregorio Honasan, who led an attempted takeover last August.
   The military was put on full alert on the eve of the visit.
   Philippine presidential spokesman Teodoro Benigno said Thursday
that Honasan was not capable of mounting a serious threat to the
government.
   Mrs. Aquino was swept to power in February 1986 after a
civilian-military coup ousted President Ferdinand Marcos. Marcos
lives in exile in Hawaii.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
