<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Spain-Bomb     04-15 0417</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spain-Bomb,0429</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes Near U.S.-Spanish Air Base</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded today at a U.S. Air Force
radio relay station near a U.S.-Spanish air base east of the
Spanish capital and caused slight damage but no injuries, a U.S.
Embassy spokesman said.
   The spokesman, Bob Meade, said the bombing took place about 6
a.m. (midnight Thursday EDT) when a bomb planted near an air
condition unit exploded at Humosa, a radio relay station about six
miles east of the U.S.-Spanish air base at Torrejon.
   Torrejon is 12 miles northeast of Madrid.
   No group immediately claimed responsibility, Meade said, and
police gave no indication of what group could have carried it out.
   The Spanish national news agency EFE cited an unidentified
Defense Ministry source as saying the bomb attack on the U.S.
facility could be related to the second anniversary of the April
15, 1986, U.S. air raids on Libya.
   President Reagan ordered the air attack on Libya in retaliation
for alleged Libyan involvement in the bombing of a nightclub in
West Berlin that killed two U.S. servicemen and a Turkish woman.
   Meade said the explosion caused slight damage to a maintenance
building near the fenced perimeter of the station, but did not
interrupt U.S. Air Force communications at Torrejon, which the
station supports.
   Torrejon air base has served as the site of numerous protest
marches against U.S. bases and the North Atlantic Treaty
Organization in recent years.
   In a March 1986 referendum called by the government of Socialist
Prime Minister Felipe Gonzalez, Spaniards overwhelmingly voted to
keep Spain in NATO on condition Spanish armed forces remain outside
the NATO command structure, that U.S. troops in Spain be
substantially reduced and that Spain remain free of nuclear weapons.
   Last Jan. 15, after 18 months of tough negotiations, the United
States accepted Spanish demands to withdraw within three years a
tactical wing of 72 F-16 fighter bombers from Torrejon to gain a
new eight-year defense accord to replace a five-year pact set to
expire May 14.
   The U.S. armed services currently maintains three air bases and
an important southern Atlantic Ocean naval station as well as
10,000 troops in Spain.
   Last Dec. 26, a bomb blast at a United Service Organizations bar
in the northeastern Mediterranean port of Barcelona killed one U.S.
sailor and injured nine others.
   The Red Army of Catalonian Liberation claimed responsibility for
the attack. The tiny, little-known terrorist group seeks
independence from Spain for the four-province northeastern region
of Catalonia.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
