<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Philippines 2ndLd-Writethru a0541 04-15 0695</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Philippines, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0541,0710</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Military Announces Arrests Of Honasan Allies In Raids</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 8 grafs to UPDATE with 10 arrested and with
officials saying Honasan might be surrounded. PICKS up 7th graf,
``There are ...' EDITS to tighten.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CLARO CORTES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Troops raided a suburban house today
and arrested 10 people, including eight navy guards who helped the
leader of an August coup attempt escape his prison ship this month,
the military said.
   Officials said troops had surrounded at least four other houses
believed to be hideouts of followers of former Lt. Col. Gregorio
``Gringo'' Honasan.
   Brig. Gen. Rodolfo Biazon, commander of the National Capital
Regional Defense Command, said there was a distinct possibility
Honasan might be in one of the houses.
   Honasan led the bloody Aug. 28 coup attempt but escaped April 2
with 14 of his elite navy guards. The charismatic former lieutenant
colonel had been detained on the navy ship since his arrest last
December in a Manila suburb.
   Biazon said three Marine companies and 30 police and soldiers
carried out the raid one day after a tip that renegade troops were
hiding in the Blue Ridge district of suburban Quezon City.
   The raid lasted only 15 minutes, he said, and there was no
resistance. Raiders seized 16 M-14 rifles, four M-16s, one light
machine gun, five Israeli-made Uzis, a grenade launcher and several
grenades.
   Those arrested included Lt. Eraldo Mojica, commander of the
security force aboard the ship from which Honasan escaped. Two of
those arrested were civilians, Biazon said.
   Col. Emiliano Templo, chief of staff of the Capital Regional
Command, said raids were continuing in hopes of capturing Honasan,
who has vowed to continue his struggle against President Corazon
Aquino.
   ``There are other places to be raided,'' Templo said. ``Maybe,
before the night is over, we will know if he (Honasan) is here or
not.''
   The raid took place as the military was on full alert to prevent
a new coup attempt while Mrs. Aquino paid a four-day visit to China
and Hong Kong. She left Thursday.
   Before the raids, the military announced the filing of the first
mutiny charges against officers linked to Honasan's failed coup.
   Military spokesman Lt. Anselmo Cabingan said those who have been
formally charged before a court martial include two lieutenant
colonels, a major and two lieutenants. Their arraignment has been
scheduled for Monday, he added.
   At least 53 people were killed and more than 300 others wounded
during the coup attempt.
   Military lawyers said more charges were to be filed soon against
more than 100 military officers and enlisted men jailed in
connection with the coup attempt, the most serious of half a dozen
bids to unseat Mrs. Aquino since she came to power in February 1986.
   Also today, police clashed with stone-throwing leftists near the
U.S. Embassy and blocked a nearby march by militant Moslems
protesting the U.S. bombing raids on Libya two years ago.
   Two demonstrators and one policeman were injured in the melee,
the second near the embassy in two weeks. The clash broke out when
club-swinging riot police charged a group of about 120 students who
had arrived at a square fronting the embassy, witnesses said.
   They said three of the demonstrators who threw stones at police
were arrested.
   At about the same time 100 yards away, police blocked a march by
about 350 Filipino Moslems who were heading for the embassy on a
march marking the second anniversary of U.S. bombing raids on Libya
in 1986.
   The Moslems dispersed peacefully after a brief rally at an
intersection where they chanted anti-American slogans. They also
burned the U.S., British and Israeli flags as well as an effigy of
President Reagan.
   Leaflets distributed during the rally said the April 15, 1986,
raids on the Libyan cities of Benghazi and Tripoli unmasked the
United States as ``20th century barbarians.''
   The U.S. bombings came 10 days after a terrorist bomb killed two
American soldiers and a Turkish woman and injured more than 200
people at a disco in West Berlin. Libyan officials said 37 people
were killed in the raids.
</TEXT>
