<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DoveAwards     04-15 0377</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dove Awards,0391</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Patti Top Gospel Music Winner</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOE EDWARDS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sandi Patti has been voted the top
female gospel music singer for the seventh straight year and has
earned her fifth award as Christian music's No. 1 artist.
   Miss Patti won three Dove Awards Thursday night from the Gospel
Music Association, sharing honors with Larnelle Harris who was
voted male vocalist of the year and two other accolades.
   Miss Patti, of Anderson, Ind., also won an award for co-writing
``In the Name of the Lord,'' which was voted song of the year. Her
co-writers were Phil McHugh and Gloria Gaither, wife of gospel
music pioneer Bill Gaither.
   Miss Patti, who gave birth to twins in November, had cut back on
her appearances and recording work last year.
   ``I didn't work a whole lot,'' she said after the 19th annual
presentations at the Tennessee Performing Arts Center.
   She also won the award as top artist in 1982, 1984, 1985 and
1987.
   Harris, of Louisville, Ky., earned male vocalist of the year for
the third time, top inspirational album for ``The Father Hath
Provided'' and best songwriter.
   ``It has been a great year,'' said Harris, who won his fourth
Grammy Award in February.
   Harris also was voted top male vocalist in 1983 and 1986.
   Soul music star Aretha Franklin was honored for the best
traditional black album of the year for ``One Lord, One Faith, One
Baptism.'' She was not present at the ceremony.
   Cliff Barrows, veteran music director for the Billy Graham
Crusade, was chosen for induction into the Gospel Music Hall of
Fame. He also was not present.
   The Winans, a brother-and-sister duet from Detroit, were double
winners, earning No. 1 contemporary black gospel album for
``Decisions'' and the Horizon Award as the top rising act.
   First Call, a Nashville trio, was voted group of the year for
the second straight time.
   Gospel superstar Amy Grant, whose music has crossed over into
the pop field, won best short form video of the year for ``Stay For
A While.'' It was the only category in which she was a finalist.
   Winners were chosen by the singers, musicians, songwriters and
others in the Nashville-based gospel association, which has 3,200
members.
</TEXT>
