<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Israel-Soviet 1stLd-Writethru   04-15 0516</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel-Soviet, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0531,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shamir Would Welcome A Shevardnadze Visit, Spokesman Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 2 grafs to UPDATE with comment from Soviet Embassy
in Amman. Pick up 3rd graf pvs: `Speaking in...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOCELYN NOVECK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir is willing to
invite Soviet Foreign Minister Eduard Shevardnadze to Israel if he
can be sure the invitation will be accepted, a Shamir spokesman
said today.
   The statement came after the Jerusalem Post reported
Shevardnadze planned a visit to Jordan, Syria and possibly Egypt
later this month. Officials at the Soviet Embassy in Amman, Jordan,
confirmed that Shevardnadze will visit the Middle East in late
April.
   Speaking in Geneva Thursday after signing accords on Soviet
troop withdrawal from Afghanistan, Shevardnadze expressed optimism
on prospects for Middle East negotiations modeled on the Afghan
talks.
   ``The signing of the Geneva agreements certainly stimulates
positive processes in the settlement of other regional issues,
including the Middle East,'' he told reporters.
   Although he declined to say if he would visit the region, the
Soviet foreign minister seemed upbeat about the possibility of
arranging talks.
   ``Fairly good prospects are now opening for a resolution of this
most difficult problem,'' he said.
   Officials close to Shamir said Israel would welcome a visit by
Shevardnadze, either by himself or in the company of Secretary of
State George P. Shultz, who is reportedly considering a return to
the Middle East.
   ``The prime minister would very much like to welcome the Soviet
foreign minister to Jerusalem for discussions,'' said Yossi
Ahimeir, a Shamir spokesman. ``But Shamir will not just throw out
an invitation. He needs to know the foreign minister will come.''
   Some observers saw the prime ministry's statement, which was
also published in Israeli newspapers, as a trial balloon.
   A visit by Shevardnadze would signify a major thaw in
Israeli-Soviet relations. Diplomatic ties were severed by Moscow to
protest Israel's occupation of Arab lands in 1967.
   The visit could also spur ahead the stagnant Middle East peace
process. Israel and the United States have said the Soviets must
demonstrate a more balanced approach in the region if they want to
play a role in the peace process.
   Among conditions Shamir has set for Soviet participation in
peace talks are a resumption of diplomatic ties and freer
emigration for about 380,000 Jews Israel says want to leave the
Soviet Union.
   Aides to Shamir said a Shevardnadze visit would not be linked to
those conditions.
   The Soviet Union supports the idea of an international
conference on Middle East peace, a key element of Shultz's recent
peace initiative. But Shultz and Shevardnadze have disagreed on the
authority that forum would wield.
   Shultz envisions a conference as a ceremonial opening to direct
talks, whereas the Soviets have visualized an ongoing conference
actively involved in decision-making.
   Shamir, of the right-wing Likud bloc, sharply opposes an
international conference, fearing it would be hostile to Israel and
lead to territorial concessions.
   His coalition rival, Foreign Minister Shimon Peres of the
leftist Labor Party, has advocated the conference as a launching
pad for direct talks.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
