<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1026EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Arias-Panama     04-15 0412</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Arias-Panama,400</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Arias Calls For Election In Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Costa Rican President Oscar Arias proposed
today a new presidential election in Panama and said U.S. military
intervention in the country would be a mistake.
   Arias, responding to questions on ABC-TV's ``Good Morning
America,'' said he believed Panamanian military chief Manuel
Antonio Noriega would agree to an election.
   Arias, who is on a U.S. visit, earlier urged a negotiated
solution rather than increased U.S. pressure to oust Noriega, who
has been indicted on drug trafficking charges by a grand jury in
Florida.
   ``Let us negotiate a new election and let us allow the
Panamanian people to choose the next president through the ballot
box,'' said Arias.
   He said military intervention in the U.S. effort to oust Noriega
would bring a negative reaction across Latin America.
   A Panamanian presidential election is scheduled in May 1989, and
Noriega has said he might be willing to step down as military chief
earlier if the opposition agrees to negotiations over Panama's
political future.
   The United States recognizes Eric Arturo Delvalle as Panama's
president. The Noriega-controlled legislature fired Delvalle and
installed the education minister, Manuel Solis Palma, as president.
Delvalle remains in hiding, apparently in Panama.
   The United States froze Panamanian funds in the United States
and took other steps to cut off the flow of dollars to Noreiga
after he was charged with drug trafficking by the grand jury.
   Members of the Senate Foreign Relations Committee said Thursday
that the Reagan administration is running out of plans to oust
Noriega and is doing little to enlist the help of neighboring
countries.
   Pentagon and State Department officials briefed committee
members on possible further economic sanctions against the country,
along with several top-secret, non-economic options, committee
members said.
   Arias told the American Society of Newspaper Editors that the
Panamanian crisis can be resolved only through negotiations.
   If the United States acts unilaterally in Panama, ``you'll be
isolated,'' he told the editors.
   ``You need to get support from the rest of Central America,'' he
said. ``If you want to punish Noriega, economic sanctions are not
the best answer. You are then punishing the Panamanian people but
not General Noriega.''
   Arias, who won the Nobel Peace Prize for his efforts to bring
peace to Central America, previously urged Panamanian Roman
Catholic Archbishop Marcos G. McGrath to mediate between Noriega
and the opposition parties. But McGrath withdrew as mediator last
week when he couldn't get the two sides together.
</TEXT>
