<1ST_LINE>u w PM-Fetuses-Research 1stLd-Writethru a0476 04-15 0484</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Fetuses-Research, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0476,450</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: New material and editing thruout with administration
confirmation and clarification that ban does not apply to all fetus
research</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JERRY ESTILL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Ethical and legal questions are behind a
decision to prohibit the National Institutes of Health from using
tissue from intentionally aborted fetuses in genetic research,
administration officials said today.
   The decision came last week in a letter from Dr. Robert E.
Windom, assistant secretary of health at the Department of Health
and Human Services, to NIH Director James B. Wyngaarden.
   ``This proposal raises a number of questions _ primarily ethical
and legal _ that have not been satisfactorily addressed, either
within the Public Health Service or within society,'' Windom wrote.
   His letter was in reponse to a proposal from NIH _ which is part
of the Public Health Service headed by Windom _ to implant fetal
tissue into patients with Parkinson's disease.
   PHS spokesman Jim Brown noted today that Windom's letter
instructs Wyngaarden to appoint an outside advisory committee to
examine the ethical, medical and legal implications of using tissue
from intentionally aborted fetuses.
   He also pointed out that the prohibition does not ban research
on tissue from fetuses from miscarriages or stillbirths, but
acknowledged that it generally is not feasible to use that tissue
in the kind of genetic research the NIH proposal contemplated.
   Brown said Windom anticipates that the advisory committee he has
instructed NIH to form will move quickly _ perhaps within a couple
of months _ to make recommendations.
   Windom was out of town and could not be reached for elaboration.
   His decision was reported initially by The Washington Post.
   ``The morality and science are all mixed together,'' the paper
quoted Windom as saying. ``They need to be evaluated before we rush
ahead. We just can't afford to move too hastily on this.''
   Thousands of aborted fetuses are used each year in research on
Parkinson's disease, juvenile diabetes and leukemia. Researchers
say the special composition of fresh tissue that is obtained
quickly from inducted abortions holds promise for treatment of the
diseases.
   Researchers contacted by the Post expressed dismay at the
decision.
   ``NIH sets the pace, and this will cripple fetal research in the
United States,'' said Dr. Bernard Liebel, professor of medicine at
the University of Toronto.
   ``It is an extraordinarily valuable research tool with immense
potential. Depriving research scientists of this material is a
great disservice to humanity,'' he said.
   Abortion opponents praised the decision.
   ``If the parents were a part to the killing, they have no right
to assign organs to another person,'' said Dr. John C. Willke,
president of the National Right-to-life Committee. ``That is
desecration of a corpse.''
   Researchers told the Post, however, that proper planning is
necessary to retrieve the tissue while it is useful and that it is
rarely possible to use fetuses that have been aborted spontaneously.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
