<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BillyCarter     04-15 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Billy Carter,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former President's Brother Says He Won't Give Up In Fight With
Cancer</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PLAINS, Ga. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Billy Carter says he's continuing to receive
weekly treatments for pancreatic cancer and will continue to fight
the disease even though he's been told it's fatal.
   ``I haven't given up yet,'' the brother of former President
Jimmy Carter said in an interview broadcast today on ABC-TV's
``Good Morning America.''
   ``I still think I'm going to beat it, you know. I'm going to try
everything. ... I'm going to my seventh treatment next week, and if
he doesn't do any good I'm going to another one, and then I'm going
to try a voodoo doctor, you know, and a snake doctor. I'm going to
fight it as long as I can.''
   In the interview, conducted Thursday in Plains, Carter said he
and his brother have grown closer since both moved back to their
south Georgia hometown.
   ``He lives right around the corner, and we've become extremely
close since I found out (about the cancer),'' he said.
   Billy Carter became known for his wise-cracking and
beer-drinking during his brother's 1976 campaign, but quit drinking
nine years ago after undergoing treatment at a California
alcoholism center.
   Carter, 51, was told by doctors last fall that he had inoperable
pancreatic cancer, the same disease which killed his father and his
sister.
   He has credited a new treatment involving injections of a
compound containing platinum with prolonging his life beyond the
short spans lived by his father, James Earl Carter, and sister,
Ruth Carter Stapleton, after they were stricken.
   He said his brother's election in 1976 completely changed his
own life, propelling him from the simple life of a peanut farmer in
Plains to the problems of national celebrity.
   ``I've been asked a thousand times, I guess, what would I do if
I had to do it over again, and I said I'd probably do the same
thing because if I had it to do over I'd probably screw it up
worse,'' Carter said.
   He said he was sorry for his drinking, but had no other regrets
about his life.
</TEXT>
