<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Libya-Bombing     04-15 0558</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Libya-Bombing,0574</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Libyans Mark Second Anniversary of U.S. Bombing</HEAD>
<HEAD>RETRANSMITTING a0574 to fix cycle designator</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Libya today marked the second anniversary
of the U.S. bombing of Tripoli and led foreign dignitaries on a
tour of the ruins of Col. Moammar Gadhafi's former home.
   About 40 delegates to an international terrorism conference and
a few journalists were ushered into the Libyan leader's two-story
concrete house shortly before 2 a.m. to coincide with the time of
the American raid on April 15, 1986.
   Libyan officials promised that the Libyan leader would make an
appearance, but Gadhafi didn't show up.
   In Italy, a man claiming to speak for the Organization of Jihad
Brigades claimed that the bombing of a U.S. military club Thursday
was in retaliation for the U.S. raid on Libya. The bombing in
Naples killed an American servicewoman and four Italian civilians.
   Another bomb exploded today in at a U.S. Air Force radio relay
station near Madrid. There were no injuries. The Spanish national
news agency EFE cited an unidentified Defense Ministry source as
saying the attack could be related to the Libyan anniversary.
   Also today, police clashed with stone-throwing protesters near
the U.S. Embassy in Manila, Philippines, and blocked a nearby march
by Moslems protesting the U.S. bombing raids.
   In downtown Tripoli, all was quiet. Libya said 37 people,
including Gadhafi's baby daughter, were killed in the American
attack, which was in retaliation for alleged Libyan involvement in
the bombing of a West German nightclub. That blast killed two U.S.
soldiers and a Turkish woman.
   ``Even if they were able to kill me on that day _ the day of the
U.S.-NATO barbarous aggression _ even if they were able to do that
in the future, that does not mean that they have succeeded in
accomplishing what they wanted,'' the official JANA news agency
quoted Gadhafi as saying Wednesday during a speech to the terrorism
conference.
   There was no explanation for Gadhafi's absence from today's
tour. Since the bombing, countless visitors to Libya have been
taken to tour the house. Blown out windows have been covered with
plastic sheeting.
   ``This is one of the two bedrooms where the children slept,'' a
Libyan official said, pointing to an unlit room littered with
glass. Several schoolbooks and notebooks, including a coloring book
with pictures of animals, were strewn on one bed.
   Hotel gift shops sell postcards of Gadhafi's adopted daughter
Hana, who reportedly died in the raid.
   The interior walls, including those of two bedrooms, bear chalk
inscriptions in Arabic that Libyan guides said were written by
students visiting the house.
   They said the inscriptions praise Gadhafi and denounce President
Reagan and British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher. The U.S.
bombers that participated in the raid took off from a base in
Britain.
   In front of the entrance hall, the Libyans have erected a
12-foot high tin hand with its fingers gripped around a splintered
silver jet representing the U.S. bombers.
   Those on the tour included delegates from Italy, Greece, Togo,
Tunisia and Canada.
   Gadhafi told them that Mediterranean nations should ``start the
struggle to rid the waterway from the fleets of terrorism, from
nuclear arms and from military exercises.``
   He said he endorsed Soviet leader Mikhail Gorbachev's proposal
to withdraw both the U.S. and Soviet fleets from the Mediterranean.
</TEXT>
