<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1122EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Tibet     04-15 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Tibet,0390</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. State Department Official Visits Tibet</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A senior U.S. State Department official in Tibet
is investigating human rights issues in the remote mountain region,
authorities said today.
   The U.S. Embassy in Beijing said J. Stapleton Roy, deputy
assistant secretary of state, is visiting several cities in Tibet
with an officer from the American consulate in Chengdu, southwest
China.
   ``The main reason he's going is to see the situation for
himself,'' said press officer Andew C. Koss.
   A report on Tibet regional radio said Roy had met with Mao
Rubai, deputy secretary of the Communist Party in Tibet. The report
said Roy raised human rights questions, among other issues.
   Mao told Roy that the ``leftist errors'' of the past, when
Tibetan religion and customs were oppressed, had been rectified and
defended China's human rights record in Tibet, the radio said.
   Tibet has erupted in violence twice in the past six months, with
Buddhist monks leading anti-Chinese, pro-independence riots last
fall and again on March 5.
   The disturbances last September and October in the capital of
Lhasa, which left an estimated 14 dead. They caused a rift in
U.S.-Chinese relations, with Congress accusing China of human
rights violations and China charging the United States with
interference in China's internal affairs.
   The U.S. government backs Beijing's contention that Tibet is
part of China, but members of Congress have expressed support for
Tibetan spiritual leader, the Dalai Lama, who has been living in
exile in India since 1959.
   After last fall's riots, Tibetan authorities closed the area to
foreign journalists and diplomats and all but a few well-watched
tourist groups.
   Since late February the restrictions on foreign visitors have
been eased somewhat, although the March 5 riots, in which as many
as 24 people were killed and hundreds arrested, prompted another
clampdown on visits.
   Chinese officials continue to insist that Tibet, which has
promoted tourism as a major source of revenue, is open. But they
say the region can handle only a limited number of people at any
one time.
   Roy leads the second U.S. government delegation to Tibet this
spring, following a group led by U.S. Rep. Sonny Montgomery,
D-Miss., a member of the House Armed Services Committee.
   Roy is to return to Beijing Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
