<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Panama 1stLd-Writethru   04-15 0592</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Panama, 1st Ld-Writethru,a0513,0610</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Says No Evidence, But Sticking By Marine Shooting Story</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 15 grafs to UPDATE with Panamanian protest, other
details. Pick up 12th graf pvs: ``The United...''</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The government today filed a formal
diplomatic protest with the United States over what it called
``violations of Panama's sovereignty'' by American troops.
   The note said U.S. troops closed a Panamanian highway during a
two-hour firefight Tuesday night ``between soldiers of the United
States and an unknown group.''
   Foreign Minister Jorge Abadia called the act a ``flagrant
violation of Panama's sovereignty'' by U.S. soldiers who ``violated
Panamanian territory in a visible form.''
   The highway was closed for three hours Tuesday night, when U.S.
officials said about 100 Marines exchanged fire with 40 to 50
uniformed intruders at a fuel dump near Howard Air Force Base
outside Panama City.
   The U.S. Southern Command said it consulted with the Panama
Defense Forces before closing the highway for ``security reasons.''
The highway runs past the air base and connects the capital with
the western part of the country.
   Copies of the protest note were sent to Javier Perez de Cuellar,
secretary general of the United Nations.
   Marines scouring rugged jungle at a fuel depot have found no
evidence to back sentrys' claims that uniformed intruders engaged
them in a nighttime firefight, the U.S. military says.
   Still, and despite Panamanian ridicule, the Americans stood by
their story.
   The Southern Command said a Marine was accidentally shot to
death by another Marine on Monday night as they investigated what
was described as a break-in by six to eight ``uniformed,
camouflaged intruders'' at the depot.
   The next night, the Southern Command said, about 100 Marines and
40 to 50 intruders ``wearing dark uniforms'' engaged in a two-hour
firefight. No injuries were reported.
   Bill Ormsby, a civilian spokesman for the U.S. Southern Command,
said Thursday that it would take at least another day for soldiers
to complete their inspection of the 807-acre Arraijan Tank Farm.
   Asked if the Southern Command was still sticking to its accounts
in the absence of concrete evidence, Ormsby replied: ``Yes, sir, we
are.''
   On Thursday, state-run news media and Panama's Defense Forces
heaped scorn on the American story.
   ``Marines Made Fools Of,'' a headline in red ink said in the
morning tabloid Critica, which is controlled by the government.
   The story said the Marines had shouted ``cries of fear,
desperation and terror'' during the reported skirmishes. A cartoon
showed a Marine smoking marijuana against a backdrop of swaying
palms.
   The United States maintains about 10,000 troops in Panama as a
permanent force to defend the Panama Canal. About 1,300 more U.S.
servicemen were sent to Panama last week to increase security for
the canal and U.S. citizens there.
   On Tuesday, a Pentagon spokesman suggested Monday night's
intrusion had been made by members of the Defense Forces, an
assertion angrily denied by the Panamanian government.
   In describing the Tuesday night incident, Southern Command
officials carefully avoided implicating the Panamanian military,
saying the reported intruders could not be identified ``with any
particular organization.''
   The Defense Forces are headed by Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega,
the power behind Panama's civilian government.
   Noriega is under indictment in the United States on charges of
drug trafficking, and the Reagan Administration has been seeking
his ouster for months.
   Last month, in an attempt to force out Noriega, the Reagan
administration began freezing Panamanian funds in the United
States, creating a cash shortage in the country.
</TEXT>
