<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Gulf-Frigate     04-15 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Gulf-Frigate,490</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With PM-Gulf Rdp</HEAD>
<HEAD>Pentagon Says Frigate Encountered Field with Numerous Mines</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NORMAN BLACK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Military Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The guided-missile frigate Samuel B. Roberts
encountered a mine field with numerous mines Thursday morning
before its hull was ripped open by one of the underwater
explosives, Pentagon officials said today.
   The frigate had come to an almost complete stop in the water at
the time of the explosion after successfully maneuvering away from
several mines spotted by lookouts, the officials said.
   The effort to maneuver out of the mine field was hampered by
rough seas, however, and the mine the Roberts eventually hit was
probably moored to the bottom, the officials said.
   The defense officials, who agreed to discuss the matter only if
not identified, said at least two mines had been spotted today by a
reconnaissance helicopter dispatched by other Navy ships in the
area.
   The sources said the Navy now had four mine-sweeping ships
closing in on the patch of water in the central gulf where the
Roberts was hit to begin a search.
   ``Ideally, we'd like to recover one of these mines,'' said one
source. ``But we also want to do it safely. The seas out there are
still heavy. It may take a while.
   ``We might end up just blowing them (the mines) up. But we're
pretty much convinced this is a new field that was just laid. And
we certainly suspect the Iranians are behind it.''
   The sources also said today the frigate had suffered extensive
damage.
   ``At one point, there was 12 feet of water inside the engine
room,'' said one official. ``The crew just did a hell of a job. She
(the ship) took a really bad hit.''
   Ten sailors were injured _ two of them critically with
second-degree burns _ when the Roberts was ripped by the underwater
explosion at 10:10 a.m. EDT. There were no fatalities.
   The Pentagon said it had been decided to tow the Roberts to
Dubai instead of Bahrain as earlier announced, and a commercial
tugboat, the Hunter, was now en route with it. The Pentagon
declined to estimate when the ship might arrive.
   One source said that by towing the Roberts to Dubai, the Navy
could move the ship immediately into a dry dock there for repairs.
While the Navy uses Bahrain as a base for its Persian Gulf forces,
there are no large dry dock facilities on that island.
   The sources said the Navy would not be able to tell the full
extent of the damage or make any decisions about repairs until the
ship was out of the water.
   ``We know the damage is bad, though,'' said one. ``They're
towing her only at about five knots because they don't think she
can take any more.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
