<2ND_LINE>PM-Turnpike Explosives, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0555,0576</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyer Appointed to Represent Japanese Man Arrested With Three
Bombs in Car</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 4 grafs to UPDATE with today's hearing recessed,
lawyer appointed to represesnt Kikumura. Picks up in 3rd graf,
`Kikumura, 35 ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By BOB McMAHON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal magistrate assigned a lawyer today
to meet with a Japanese man who has refused to speak to officials
trying to find out why he carried three powerful bombs in his car
on the New Jersey Turnpike.
   U.S. Magistrate Ronald Hedges said the lawyer, Thomas Higgins,
would explain to Yu Kikumura the charges pending against him.
Hedges then recessed a hearing, called to consider bail for
Kikumura, while Kikumura met with Higgins.
   Kikumura is being held on federal charges of possessing a
fraudulent visa and illegally possessing unregistered firearms, the
explosives. If convicted, he faces up to $260,000 in fines and up
to 15 years in prison.
   In addition to the explosives, authorities revealed in court
today that Kikumura was carrying $3,600.
   Kikumura, 35, entered the country March 8 and was arrested by a
state trooper Tuesday at the Vince Lombardi rest area in
Ridgefield, authorities said.
   U.S. officials have been unable to confirm reports by the
Japanese Foreign Ministry that Kikumura is a suspected member of
the terrorist group Red Army, said John C. McGlinley, special agent
in charge of the FBI's Newark office.
   Officials have yet to link Kikumura with any group and were
exploring any international ties he might have, McGlinley said.
   ``We have a lot of unanswered questions that we have to
answer,'' he said.
   The Red Army is suspected of involvement in a bombing which
killed five people, including a U.S. servicewoman, in Naples,
Italy, on Thursday. Italian police said a known member of the Red
Army is believed to have rented the car that exploded outside an
American military club.
   A spokesman for the FBI here, James J. Knights, refused to
comment on the Italian bombing and any connection to Kikumura's
activities.
   ``We're not saying anything about that,'' he said today. ``We're
not making any linkage between the two.''
   Kikumura, who was identified by officials in Japan through
fingerprints, faced a bail hearing under heavy guard Thursday
before Superior Court Judge Charles DiGisi, who released him to
federal agents without setting bail.
   Kikumura told DiGisi he would not talk to federal authorities
until a lawyer was appointed for him.
   Meanwhile, Japanese police refused to comment on Kyodo news
service reports Kikumura was believed to have established links to
the leftist Red Army, a Japanese terrorist group, in 1974 when he
ran a bookshop in Athens, Greece.
   The news service said Kikumura's arrest had raised suspicions
the Red Army might be planning attacks during the summit of leaders
of advanced industrial nations June 19 in Toronto, Canada.
   The Red Army advocates ``simultaneous world revolution'' and is
believed to have members allied with pro-Palestinian groups in
Lebanon.
   State Police Superintendent Col. Clinton Pagano said a terrorist
task force is investigating the case because of the sophisticated
nature of the bombs, which police said were made from three 18-inch
steel cylinders. Authorities said they found 15 pounds of black
powder in the car.
   Federal officials estimated that the explosives in the car were
capable of destroying the car and a ``substantial part of a normal
dwelling.''
</TEXT>
