<HEAD>Heating Oil Pollutes Drinking Water in Czech Mountains</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRAGUE, Czechoslovakia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Spilled heating oil fouled the
drinking water for a town of more than 30,000 people in
northeastern Bohemia, it was reported Friday.
   More than 1,000 gallons of oil spilled into the Upa River at Pec
pod Snezkou, and water supplies had to be brought in for the town
of Trutnov, according to Prague television and the Communist Party
daily Rude Pravo reported.
   The heating oil got into the river's water purification system
when automatic pumping equipment failed to halt pumping into a tank.
   The accident occurred in a mountain recreation center belonging
to the Sigma factory, Czechoslovakia's largest producer of pumping
systems.
</TEXT>
