<HEAD>Imprisoned Opposition Party Leader To Be Tried</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DAKAR, Senegal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An opposition leader and 11 colleagues
will go on trial Monday on charges of inciting riots after losing
Feb. 28 national elections.
   Abdoulaye Wade and 11 members of his Senegalese Democratic Party
will be tried for compromising state security and inciting violence
in the three days following the elections, said a court official
who declined to be identified.
   A state of emergency was imposed in the Dakar area as gangs of
youths fought police, damaged buildings and burned cars. President
Abdou Diouf later defended Wade's arrest, saying he had tried to
``sow disorder and violence.''
   Diouf was re-elected to a second, elected term with 73.5 percent
of the vote. Wade, his closest challenger, took 25 percent of the
vote.
   Wade and other opposition leaders claimed the voting was rigged.
   The Dakar region remains under state of emergency laws, and a
nighttime curfew remains in effect.
