<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--Cyprus-Passports     04-15 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Cyprus-Passports,0207</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Passports Required for Crossing Green Line</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NICOSIA, Cyprus (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Turkish Cypriot administration said
Friday it has started requiring Cypriots to carry passports if they
cross the Green Line that divides this Mediterranean island.
   The new requirement became known when opposition Republican
Turkish Party leader Ozker Ozgur was turned back from the
checkpoint Thursday by Turkish Cypriot officials for not carrying a
passport.
   Rauf Denktash, the Turkish Cypriot leader, said the decision was
in response to Greek Cypriot President George Vassiliou's statement
that there are no borders in Cyprus.
   The decision is mainly symbolic since few people make the
crossing through the checkpoint near the Ledra Palace Hotel.
Diplomats and United Nations peacekeeping forces will be able to
cross as in the past, they said.
   In the past, Cypriots making the crossing required only
permission from both administrations.
   Greek Cypriots carry passports issued by the Republic of Cyprus,
the only internationally recognized government on the island.
Turkish Cypriots have been issued Turkish Republic of Northern
Cyprus passports by the Turkish Cypriot administration.
   The Turkish Cypriots make up about 18 percent of the 650,000
population of the island, divided since the Turkish invasion of
1974 into two zones.
</TEXT>
