<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Chambers 1stLd-Writethru a0518 04-15 0554</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Chambers, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0518,0565</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Chambers Sentenced to 5-to-15 Years</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with sentencing today.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SAMUEL MAULL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Robert Chambers, apologizing for the first time
to the family of Jennifer Levin, was sentenced today to five to 15
years in jail for strangling the 18-year-old in Central Park.
   The sentence was agreed to three weeks earlier when Chambers
pleaded guilty to first-degree manslaughter, abruptly ending the
celebrated ``preppie murder'' trial in the ninth day of jury
deliberations after a three-month trial.
   ``The Levin family has gone through hell because of my
actions,'' Chambers said in his first public apology for killing
Miss Levin. ``Whoever said time heals all wounds is all wrong.''
   Chambers stood silently while state Supreme Court Justice Howard
E. Bell handed down the predetermined sentence in a crowded
Manhattan courtroom. As he did while pleading guilty, the defendant
shook his head ``no'' several times during the session, including
once when Bell repeated his guilty plea to manslaughter.
   ``Jennifer's looking down, looking and wondering why this all
happened. I don't know,'' Chambers said later during his brief
statement. ``I never wanted any of this to happen. I wish to
apologize to her family and all her friends.''
   Chambers also apologized to his family and friends, and thanked
more than 150 supporters for letters he has received since being
jailed after his guilty plea.
   The Chambers case spotlighted the world of wealthy Upper East
Side youths and the underaged drinking, drugs and sex of their
lifestyles.
   Among those in the courtroom for the sentencing were several
Chambers trial jurors and several members of the Levin family.
Steven Levin, the slain girl's father, was not permitted to speak
at the hearing as he had requested.
   At the time of the plea, the jury was divided after several
votes on the charge of second-degree murder, the stiffest Chambers
faced, and sent notes to the judge saying they were at an impasse.
   The sentence followed a hearing before Bell in which Chambers'
attorney, Jack Litman, complained that the probation report on his
client was ``slanted'' and asked for an opportunity to answer
charges made by the prosecution in the report.
   Bell granted Litman's request, telling the attorney to put his
comments in writing. The sentencing was delayed for about an hour
while Bell read Litman's response to the probation report.
   Chambers, 21, agreed to the first-degree manslaughter plea in a
deal with the district attorney as a jury deliberated second-degree
murder charges against him, abandoning his story of an accidental
death during ``rough sex'' in the park.
   The agreement was reached after two days of deliberations
between prosecutors and Chambers' attorneys, and approved by the
Levin family. A manslaughter conviction carries a maximum term of
eight and one-third to 25 years.
   By pleading guilty to first-degree manslaughter in Miss Levin's
strangulation, Chambers admitted he intended to hurt the teen
during an encounter in Central Park on Aug. 26, 1986, and ended up
killing her.
   Miss Levin's bruised and nearly naked body was found beneath a
tree behind the Metropolitan Museum of Art early on the morning of
Aug. 26. The couple had run into each other earlier at a popular
Upper East Side ``preppie'' bar.
   Chambers' plea bargain also took care of three burglary charges
against him.
</TEXT>
