<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1230EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-BRF--China-Military     04-15 0175</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--China-Military,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deng Xiaoping Urges Return of Military Ranks</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Deng Xiaoping has urged the People's Liberation
Army to reinstate the use of military ranks abolished by Mao
Tse-tung more than 20 years ago, it was reported Friday.
   The official China Daily said Deng, who heads the state and
party central military commissions, made the proposal Wednesday at
the first meeting of the newly formed Standing Committee of the 7th
National People's Congress.
   Deng also proposed awarding medals of honor to retired veterans
of the PLA and confirming military ranks conferred between 1955 and
1965.
   The reintroduction of ranks has been discussed for several
years, but it was believed to be the first time Deng has stated his
support for the idea.
   Mao abolished ranks and medals in the early 1960s to further his
concept of an egalitarian, proletariat military force.
   Deng has worked to create a leaner, more efficient and
modernized fighting force. In 1985 he began a two-year program to
reduce the army from 4 million to 3 million members.
</TEXT>
