<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Hijack-Scene     04-15 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hijack-Scene,0530</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Everything Normal, Except for Life-and-Death Hijack Drama</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Hijack, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHARLES CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALGIERS, Algeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sun shines on rustling palms, the
airport bustles with the world's business, and on the isolated
``plane of martyrdom'' three dozen people wait for their captors to
kill them or set them free.
   The blue-and-white Kuwait Airlines Boeing 747, hijacked April 5,
faces north toward the main terminal and control tower about 400
yards away.
   From the cockpit, crew members talk with the tower about air
conditioner maintenance, delivery of food and other routine matters.
   Police presence is discreet. Four small armored cars encircle
the plane, but no soldiers are in sight.
   Algerian officials, proud of their country's ability to deal
with both revolutionaries and conservative governments, note
repeatedly that the gunmen have promised to refrain from violence
while here and say an assault on the plane is out of the question.
   The hijackers killed two passengers during five days spent on
the ground at Larnaca, Cyprus.
   At least 200 reporters and photographers patrol the sunbaked
lawn between the terminal and the VIP lounge and fight for the
scarce, unreliable telephones that were installed after the plane
arrived early Wednesday.
   From the lawn, shaded by tents erected Wednesday night by
blue-uniformed soldiers, journalists peer at the plane through
binoculars and telephoto lenses.
   Now and then, Algerian officials climb the stairway and are
allowed to enter the jumbo jet for 15 to 30 minutes of continuing,
but episodic, negotiations with the hijackers.
   Talks between Algerian mediators and a Kuwaiti delegation take
place elsewhere, presumably in government offices downtown.
   Passenger jets land every 10 or 20 minutes and taxi past the
hijacked plane to discharge passengers into the crowded terminal,
which is dusty from construction that has closed its self-service
restaurant.
   Airport workers and taxi drivers show intense interest and press
journalists for information about the standoff with the hijackers,
who demand freedom for 17 pro-Iran extremists convicted of bombing
the U.S. and French embassies in Kuwait in 1983.
   On Wednesdy night the drama heightened.
   Two buses pulled up to the plane, official cars raced across the
tarmac, the Kuwaiti delegation stood expectantly in what looked
like a receiving line and the moving stairway approached the
plane's front door.
   The control tower radioed the cockpit to say an official was
ready to enter. The response: ``We are praying.''
   An Algerian official entered. Rumors flew. He left. The Kuwaiti
receiving line disbanded, reformed, then disappeared. Hours ticked
away toward midnight, and it seemed that whatever had been on was
off. There was no official explanation.
   Suddenly a hijacker was helping a hostage hobble down the
stairs. Less than a minute later the Kuwaiti businessman was being
guided into a portion of the VIP lounge barred to reporters. His
10-day ordeal was over.
   Soon afterward, radio scanners recorded a statement from the
hijackers describing themselves as ``men of principle'' and
restating their demand for the release of the 17 prisoners in
Kuwait ``even if the price we have to pay is very high.''
</TEXT>
