<DOCNO> AP880415-0114 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1302EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Firms Bjt   04-15 0750</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Firms, Bjt,0777</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>American Companies Say Law May Force Some to Close</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHRIS ANGELO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   American companies here say they're
caught in the middle of President Reagan's new economic sanctions
and may have to close if they're not allowed to resume payments to
Panama's government.
   Eastman Kodak Co. gave its workforce in Panama a 15-day paid
furlough because of the problems in doing business, a company
spokesman said Friday.
   Another company has given its employees ``collective vacations''
since Reagan froze all U.S. payments to the Panamian government on
April 8, in an attempt to force Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega to
relinquish power.
   A source familiar with the company's situation said it would not
reopen until conditions are such that it can pay taxes in Panama.
   The U.S. order prohibits direct or indirect payments, including
income taxes, by Americans and U.S. corporations to the Panamanian
government. It also applies to Panamanian corporations owned or
directed by Americans. Violators can be sentenced to up to 10 years
in prison and fined $50,000.
   Companies have been told that until any exemptions are
announced, the order is being enforced to its fullest extent _
right down to the $30 departure tax charged at the airport to
people leaving the country.
   ``You can't move, you can't do anything without breaking the
law,'' the head of one company said.
   ``The executive order puts a gun against my head and the
(Panamanian) government has a gun against my head, and I'm just
ducking,'' he said.
   All the executives spoke on condition of anonymity.
   Several company representatives said they were complying with
the order and continued to operate, but they noted they did not yet
have tax or other payments due the government.
   Commerce and Industries Minister Mario Rognoni has said the
government will be flexible with U.S. firms. But if electricity,
water and telephone bills are not paid, the utilities services run
by the government will be cut off.
   ``We weren't ordered to close, but it just doesn't make sense to
stay open,'' said Kodak spokesman Henry Kaska in Rochester, N.Y.
``We are not permitted to pay our utility bill. We can't pay the
phone bill.''
   One executive said the ability of American manufacturers to
continue operating also would depend on whether they have enough
raw materials in stock, since importing also requires payments to
the government.
   ``We're hoping there will exceptions for essential items,'' a
food company executive said.
   ``We have tax payments to the government but cannot pay them,''
he added. ``We're caught in the middle.''
   ``Sooner or later, the executive order is going to shut
everybody down. The executive order will totally kill U.S. business
in Panama,'' he said.
   He said some companies paid high taxes the first three quarters,
but owed less for the year because of the economic crisis and now
have credits, allowing them to postpone a payment decision.
   An American trade association representative said the law was
hurting U.S. companies more than its target, Noriega.
   ``In essence it's closing down U.S. companies and sending
Americans home and not affecting Mr. Noriega at all. I expect some
leeway will have to be allowed,'' he said.
   ``Really you're a hostage here in Panama,'' he said, referring
to the airport tax.
   Panamanian residents also may not leave the country without
showing what amounts to an income tax receipt.
   American businesses are worried about the progressive penalties
the Panamanian government may charge if it decides to let the
companies pay taxes late.
   Most executives said they would comply with the sanctions, but a
number were said to be looking for ways to get around it.
   Nicolas Psychoyos said he and his father, both American
citizens, have taken leaves of absence from the Panamanian-owned
supermarket chain they headed.
   ``Non-Americans will run the company for a while. From all they
said, this is all we can do,'' he said. ``I think most companies
are evaluating now whether they want to be thrown in jail in Panama
or in the United States.''
   Psychoyos said the supermarket chain will continue payments to
the government.
   ``We've got to abide by the laws. We've been here 80 years and
we hope to be another 80,'' he said.
   Under the order, companies are to make their normal payments to
an escrow account at the Federal Reserve Bank of New York
established for Eric Arturo Delvalle, who was ousted from the
presidency by Noriega on Feb. 26 after trying to fire the general.
</TEXT>
