<1ST_LINE>r w AM-FTC-MailOrder     04-15 0164</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-FTC-Mail Order,160</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mail Order Head To Pay $300,000 Penalty</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The head of two mail-order firms has agreed to
pay a $300,000 civil penalty to settle charges that he violated
federal rules, the Federal Trade Commission announced Friday.
   The payment settled charges against Philip Goutell, president of
Frank E. Bush Inc. and Conceptual Trends Inc. of New York, the FTC
said.
   The Trade Commission had charged that Goutell's companies, and
others, misrepresented products they offered for sale, failed to
deliver merchandise on time, failed to notify consumers of their
right to cancel delayed orders and failed to cancel orders or make
refunds to consumers.
   Under terms of the settlement the companies also agreed not to
make misleading claims about products offered for sale, including
cookware, kitchen products, binoculars, kerosene lamps and pills
claimed to remedy male impotence.
   Seven other firms and three individuals also were named in the
original FTC suit. The others settled the charges against them last
August.
