<1ST_LINE>r w AM-BRF--SubmarineLaunch     04-15 0143</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Submarine Launch,140</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy to Launch USS Pennsylvania April 23</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Navy's newest Trident nuclear submarine
will be launched later this month in Groton, Conn., the service
said Friday.
   The ballistic missile submarine Pennsylvania will slide into the
water during ceremonies April 23 at the General Dynamic Corp.'s
Electric Boat Division shipyards, the Navy said.
   Rep. Joseph McDade, R-Pa., will be principal speaker during the
ceremonies. The nuclear-powered sub will be the fourth U.S. Navy
warship to be named for the state of Pennsylvania.
   The Pennsylvania is 560 feet long, 42 feet wide and will
displace about 18,700 tons when submerged. The first such
submarine, the Ohio, was commissioned in 1981.
   The Pennsylvania will be the second sub in the line built to
accommodate a new, more accurate version of the Trident
intercontinental nuclear missile known as the D-5.
</TEXT>
