<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MummyTests     04-15 0292</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mummy Tests,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scientists Find Probable Cause Of Death Of 2,300-Year-Old Mummy</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WOODY BAIRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEMPHIS, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An ancient mummy found in a pawnshop is
likely the body of a man who died at the age of 35 and would have
had a longer and more comfortable life in the age of antibiotics,
university scientists say.
   Memphis State University paid a Detroit pawnbroker $40,000 for
the 2,300-year-old mummy two years ago and asked the University of
Tennessee, Memphis, to run a battery of tests.
   The medical school set up a ``mummy team'' in 1985 to conduct
similar tests on an ancient head acquired by Memphis State's
Institute of Egyptian Art and Archaeology.
   The team tested tissue and hair samples and took hundreds of
X-rays, and announced Thursday that the Egyptian apparently died of
a brain abscess caused by an ear infection.
   Hugh Berryman, a forensic anthropologist, said the man was 5
feet tall, probably right-handed and had thinning brown hair, and
also suffered from serious tooth infections.
   James Langston, a radiologist with the medical school, said the
Egyptian had an infection that ate through a bone near his left
inner ear and may have led to a fatal brain abscess.
   ``That's a reasonable cause of death,'' he said. ``We only have
the bone for speculation because we don't have the brain.''
   Rita Freed, an Egyptologist from Memphis State, said the mummy
was named Iret-Irew, according to inscriptions on its coffin.
   The mummy was brought to the United States in the 1920s. It was
kept at a museum in Chicago until 1976, when it was sold to an
antique dealer. It eventually was bought by the pawnbroker who
later sold it to Memphis State, Ms. Freed said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
