<HEAD>Government Donates Seized Fish to Needy</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some 78,000 pounds of illegally imported fish
is being donated to food banks in California, the National Marine
Fisheries Service reported Friday.
   The frozen salmon was seized last year after being imported from
Japan and then relabeled as a product of the United States, the
agency said.
   After inspecting the salmon and clearing it for human
consumption, the agency decided to donate it for use in shelters,
day-care centers, soup kitchens and senior centers.
   About 26,000 pounds of salmon will go to the Los Angeles
Regional Food Bank and 52,000 pounds will be divided by the San
Francisco and Santa Clara County food banks.
   The salmon was seized at cold storage plants in Oakland,
Riverside and Watsonville.
   About 200,000 pounds of fish confiscated in Bellingham, Wash.,
was sold earlier under a court order, officials said.
