<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Moon-VenusShow     04-15 0228</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Moon-Venus Show,210</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Look: Up in the Sky, It's Venus and the Moon</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The queen of the sky will nestle near a
sparkling crescent Moon in the next few days, offering skywatchers
a special sight.
   The dazzling white point of light that marks the planet Venus
will shine near the emerging Moon, astronomers report.
   ``It'll be a particularly nice scene, and folks will notice
it,'' said Gail Cleere of the U.S. Naval Observatory here.
   The peak will come on Tuesday night just after twilight, but the
celestial couple will also shine together on Sunday and Monday
nights, reports Sky & Telescope magazine.
   The Moon will be just three days old on Tuesday, so it will be a
pretty crescent, Cleere said. ``We gets hundreds of calls'' when
instances like this occur.
   The New Moon occurs on Saturday, meaning that the Earth's
natural satellite will be invisible. But on the following days
light will begin to brighten the edge, creating the familier
crescent Moon.
   Venus, meanwhile, will be located in almost the same part of the
sky and will be the brightest object visible other than the Moon.
   While Venus and the Moon will appear close together in the sky,
that's only because they are located along the same line of sight.
Venus is about 54 million miles away, 225 times farther than the
Moon.
</TEXT>
