<1ST_LINE>u p PM-PoliticalRdp 3rdLd-Writethru a0623 04-15 0971</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Rdp, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0623,980</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Criticizes Administration on Anti-Drug Spending</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs 2 grafs for 7th graf pvs, Massachusetts Gov., with
Dukakis speaking informally rather than delivering speech quoted in
story</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis blasted President
Reagan and Vice President George Bush today for having supported a
``dope-peddling'' dictator in Panama. Republican Bush said one
reason Panamanian strongman Manuel Antonio Noriega has lasted so
long is that he has been getting money from Libya.
   All three Democratic candidates campaigned in New York today,
four days before the state's primary, with Jesse Jackson ridiculing
his rivals as latecomers in the fight against illegal drugs and
Albert Gore Jr. saying troubles at Eastern Airlines reflected
hands-off, greed-promoting values encouraged by the Reagan
administration.
   New polls confirmed Dukakis' lead among New York Democrats, with
Jackson running second and Gore a poor third.
   Bush, speaking in Washington to the American Society of
Newspaper Editors, said, ``Noriega should go and Noriega will go.''
   He said he did not know about Noriega's alleged involvement in
drug trafficking until the Panamanian leader was indicted in this
country. Citing ``several reliable sources,'' he said Noriega has
been able to stay in power despite U.S. sanctions at least partly
because he has been receiving millions of dollars from Libya.
   Speaking before the same forum, former television evangelist Pat
Robertson said he still hoped his supporters could play a key role
in the Republican convention in August. But he ackowledged,
``George Bush will probably have things his own way.''
   Massachusetts Gov. Dukakis made strong anti-drug remarks to
students today at a junior high school in Brooklyn.
   He spoke informally rather than giving the prepared remarks that
aides had distributed to reporters. In those remarks, he asked
rhetorically, ``Mr. President and Mr. Vice President, what is going
on?
   ``Why do we have the money for Star Wars but not for the war
against drugs? And why did you pay $200,000 a year to a
dope-peddling, gun-running Panamanian dictator?'' _ a reference to
former U.S. support of Noriega.
   Gore spoke to about two dozen members of pilots, mechanics and
flight attendants unions at Eastern Airlines early today, saying
``mismanagement of Eastern and Continental, et cetera, stands as a
symbol of the kind of approach Ronald Reagan and George Bush
encourage with their policies of hands off, let 'em have whatever
kind of labor relations they want, promote greed as the principal
guiding value for corporate America.''
   Cuomo has refused to endorse any of the three Democratic
contenders, saying he will wait until after the last primaries on
June 7.
   Earlier in the week, Jackson met with Cuomo and the governor was
generous in his praise of the former civil rights activist.
   On Thursday, however, Cuomo said Jackson's lack of experience in
elective office could hurt him if he won the nomination.
   ``I could make a better case for him if he had been a public
official,'' Cuomo said.
   Before Cuomo decided to hold off any endorsement, Dukakis had
been considered the odds-on favorite to win the governor's backing.
   The Massachusetts governor also had hoped to get the support of
Koch, but the New York City mayor surprised many observers by
announcing his backing of Gore, whom he described as ``a man of
intellect, courage and integrity.''
   Koch said that on the issue of support of Israel, Gore was
``head and shoulders'' above the other two Democrats.
   The mayor said Jackson was never in contention for his
endorsement, but that he would back him if he became the party
nominee.
   He added however that his support of Jackson would be based
``not because of his positions but because he would be less
destructive of the country than George Bush.''
   Gore needed all the help he could get in New York, which holds
its primary next Tuesday with 255 delegates at stake.
   Dukakis led Jackson by 45 percent to 28 percent in a CBS News
poll, 46 percent to 34 percent in a Marist College poll and 49
percent to 34 percent in an ABC News-Washington Post poll. Gore had
only 8 percent support in two polls and 7 percent in the third.
   ``Gore's numbers are flat across the board,'' said Marist
pollster Lee Miringoff. While things can change before Tuesday's
vote, ``certainly nothing much moved this week except for solidity
to the front-runners.''
   ``I only believe polls that show me way in front,'' Gore
commented after the debate.
   The latest confrontation offered no sign of a breakthrough.
   Gore pressed Dukakis once again on his statement to the New York
Daily News that he would consider use of nuclear weapons in the
event of a Soviet invasion of Europe.
   ``This is a serious mistake'' said Gore, referring to the
Dukakis statement.
   When Gore raised the issue again later in the debate, Dukakis
said: ``Don't pick up the morning newspaper and then have a press
conference. Give me a buzz and I'll tell you exactly what I said
and there'll be much less confusion.''
   When Gore first took Dukakis to task, Dukakis said Gore
misrepresented what Dukakis had told the newspaper. Dukakis said he
was simply restating longstanding U.S. and NATO policy.
   Jackson, however, said there was ``a real danger in those of us
who may very well lead our country to get trapped into a
hypothetical situation on who will shoot your gun first and destroy
the whole world to prove that you got macho.''
   Dukakis widened his delegate lead over Jackson to 112, when 26
House members supporting him were nominated to be among the
so-called super delegates to the Democratic National Convention.
   Jackson picked up 15 delegates in Congress, while Gore got 11. A
total of 251 members of the House and Senate will be delegates to
the convention.
</TEXT>
