<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1327EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel-Palestinians Bjt   04-15 0790</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel-Palestinians, Bjt,0813</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Signs of Cracks In Palestinian Leadership</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cracks are appearing in the underground
Palestinian leadership over how to wage a campaign of resistance
against Israel's occupation of the West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The divisions are emerging at a time when the frequency and size
of street clashes is diminishing, and the nature of the
confrontation is changing into more of an economic test of wills.
   There are two basic splits in Palestinian ranks:
   _ The Islamic Resistance Movement is at odds with the mainstream
Palestine Liberation Organization factions on the issue of
convening an international conference to negotiate peace.
   _ The Communists, in a dispute over tactics, have pulled out of
the PLO-affiliated underground command, the United National
Leadership of the Uprising.
   The underground has announced weekly action programs in a series
of leaflets. But starting in early March, there have been multiple
versions, some making conflicting demands on the 1.5 million
residents of the occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   In the latest handbill, No. 13, one version calls for three days
of general strikes to mark ``Prisoners' Day'' while another
version, apparently Communist, called for sit-ins at the Red Cross
offices and other locations.
   ``There are differences on how to act, on tactics, '' conceded
Mohammed Manasra, a journalist with the daily Communist newspaper
Al Taalia.
   As an example, Manasra cited the repeated calls for general
strikes, which he said kept workers away from jobs at a time when
Israel was using economic measures in an effort to put an end to
the uprising.
   ``If Israel is putting economic pressure on people, and we also
put pressure on people, then we are doing what Israel wants,'' said
Manasra, who added workers would ignore strike calls if they became
excessive.
   Instead of general strikes that hurt low-income Palestinians,
Manasra said the Communists supported a boycott of Israeli products.
   According to the Ministry of Labor's government Employment
Service, about half the 110,000 Arabs who hold jobs in Israel went
to work in February and March. Oficials claim the on-the-job figure
has risen recently, although statistics were not available.
   After Palestinians stopped paying taxes, Israeli authorities
imposed financial and trade restrictions and put the West Bank's
8,000 teachers on half-pay for three weeks. The army has also
ordered stores closed when PLO leaflets said they should be open.
   ``Food is very expensive. People are feeling the seriousness of
the economic strikes,'' Farah El-Araj, the pro-Jordanian mayor of
Beit Jallah, said on Israel Radio.
   A second split is between the PLO factions and the Islamic
Resistance Movement, a coalition of fundamentalist groups that has
a large following in the Gaza Strip.
   To counter the increasing Islamic influence, the PLO-affiliated
factions, the Communist Party and the Islamic Jihad formed a
coalition in early January. Called the United National Leadership
of the Uprising, it has followed the policies of PLO Chairman
Yasser Arafat in seeking an international peace conference and in
not escalating clashes by using guns and knives.
   The fundmentalists, however, oppose negotiations with Israel and
seek creation of a pan-Islamic, rather than Palestinian, state.
   ``The first phase of the uprising is winding down, and they
(Palestinians) disagree about the second phase, about where to go
from here,'' said Col. Renaan Gissin, deputy army spokesman.
   ``There are feelings of fatigue. The people want to see some
results,'' he added.
   Gissin said another split threatening the unity of the
underground was Islamic Jihad's desire to wage armed struggle, a
policy opposed by PLO groups.
   Despite the disputes, Manasra said the resistance would continue
because local committees rather than the leaflet writers had the
final say on whether to observe calls for strikes and protests.
   For example, he said he doubted whether local committees would
heed the call in the latest leaflet to throw firebombs on April 21,
the so-called ``Day of the Palestinian Molotov.''
   The army spokesman said the overall level of violence had
dropped markedly in recent weeks even though the bloodshed had not
ceased altogether.
   ``The intensity of the clashes is still high, but there are
fewer confrontations and the size of demonstrations is smaller, a
hundred or so instead of thousands,'' said Gissin.
   There have been 7,000 clashes between soldiers and demonstrators
since Dec. 8, killing 146 Arabs and two Israelis. More than 1,000
Arabs have been wounded by gunfire.
   ``I think we are now in an ebbing phase of the uprising. We've
already reached the peak. But when it finally subsides, I don't
think it will go back to the same level it started at four months
ago,'' said Sari Nusseibah, a philosophy professor at the Bir Zeit
University in the West Bank.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
