<DOCNO> AP880415-0126 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1331EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Thatcher Bjt   04-15 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Thatcher, Bjt,0727</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Welfare and Property Tax Laws Stir Thatcher Rebellion</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MAUREEN JOHNSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's controversial
social welfare legislation is stirring the fiercest opposition she
has encountered since her re-election last June.
   The resistance is coming not just from the opposition, but from
rank-and-file lawmakers within her own Conservative Party, who on
Thursday night staged their biggest back-bench revolt since June.
   Twenty-eight of the 376 Tories in Parliament voted against the
government's decision to end free dental checkups and eye
examinations.
   The sums involved _ $5.60 for the dental checkup _ are small,
but they matter to the poor and they come in the same month as the
top income tax rate is being slashed from 60 to 40 percent.
   And while the number of rebels looks relatively small, any
revolt is significant, given Mrs. Thatcher's strong-willed style of
leadership. Customarily, a lawmaker voting against his government
almost automatiucally destroys his chances of winning government
office.
   The social welfare moves and a controversial reform of property
taxes, another Thatcher brainchild, have combined to arouse deep
unease among sections of the Parliamentary rank-and-file about her
radical third term program.
   ``At the heart of the debate is a fear that the very well-off
make substantial gains which are wholly financed by the less
well-off,'' said Conservative legislator Sir George Young, a
leading rebel.
   ``Playing around with rebates for the poor in no way tackles
that fundamental inequity.''
   Mrs. Thatcher remains determined to wean Britons off what she
calls the ``dependency culture'' and encourage private enterprise.
She points to the economic revival her rigorous policies have
wrought, including the fastest growth rate in Western Europe and
the country's first budget surplus in nearly two decades.
   But there are signs of defensiveness. On Thursday night, the
62-year-old prime minister made a comparatively rare foray into the
House of Commons tea room to rally support for the new property
tax, popularly called the poll tax.
   And the government announced an extension of rebates, costing
about $245 million and affecting 1 million people, in a move to
blunt another rebellion when the poll tax comes up for a key vote
Monday.
   That concession appeared aimed at heading off a major revolt
Monday in the 650-member Commons, where the Conservatives' hefty
102-seat majority was whittled to 81 and 74 in Thursday's votes.
   Under the poll tax, families will be rated according to how many
adults are living in the home. Estimates are that the tax on some
homes will more than double, hitting modest earners hardest.
   ``It will manifestly be perceived to be unfair,'' complained
another Tory legislator, Michael Mates, who hopes to get about 50
colleagues to back an amendment that would base the tax on income
instead of a flat charge.
   Like changes in housing subsidies which force everyone,
including public housing tenants, to pay at least one-fifth of the
property taxes on their homes, the poll tax is fundamental to a
Thatcher onslaught on local councils.
   The local councils, which run local government, are dominated by
Britain's left-wing.
   They levy and spend property taxes and most of the bigger
councils are run by the socialist Labor Party.
   The Guardian newspaper, the nation's foremost liberal daily,
argued that Tory legislators with narrowly held seats are
frightened by Mrs. Thatcher's measures.
   ``Where damaging policy changes were unable to provoke a revolt,
political survival has succeeded,'' it said.
   A straw poll among 100 rank-and-file Tory legislators by another
daily, The Independent, found nearly two-thirds expressing alarm at
the social security changes.
   The government says it is merely refocusing the $86 billion
welfare budget on the most needy. But opposition and welfare groups
estimate that two-thirds of the 8.6 million welfare claimants will
lose funds. The government acknowledges 43 percent will receive
less.
   Polls show the Conservative government is losing support.
Gallup's March poll showed the Conservatives 5.5 points ahead of
Labor, down from 10 the previous month. Two-thirds of the 1,094
voters questioned said they thought the tax-cutting budget
announced March 15 was ``not fair.''
   The Conservatives received 42 percent support _ enough for
another victory _with Labor getting 36.5 percent and the rest split
among two center parties and minority regional parties.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0127 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1340EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-IndustrialProduction     04-15 0445</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Industrial Production,440</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Industrial Production Posts Tiny Gain</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Production at the nation's factories, mines
and utilities edged up a sluggish 0.1 percent in March, the
government said Friday, somewhat counterbalancing signs that
inflation is reheating.
   The Federal Reserve Board said gains in production of autos and
business equipment offset declines in construction supplies and
consumer goods other than cars.
   The slight March advance followed no change in February and,
according to economists, is an indication that the pickup in
wholesale prices may not be sustainable.
   ``It isn't the type of boom production environment that would
support rapid gains in inflation,'' said Maury Harris, chief
economist at PaineWebber in New York.
   The Labor Department, in a separate report Friday, said
wholesale inflation was running at a 7 percent annual rate in
March. That news sent jitters through the financial markets and
pushed interest rates higher.
   ``Ironically, a fairly low growth rate in industrial production
is good in one sense ... It may actually allay suspicions that the
economy may be on the verge of overheating,'' said Gordon Richards,
an economist with the National Association of Manufacturers.
   Before February, production had been increasing at a steady
pace: 0.5 percent in November and December and 0.4 percent in
January. The last decline was in September, when production fell
0.2 percent. Production had shot up 1.1 percent in October.
   Despite two months of lackluster growth, production levels in
March were a strong 5.6 percent above levels a year ago.
   The March rise included a 0.2 percent jump in production at
manufacturing plants after a flat performance in February. That
included a 2.6 percent increase in auto production, which followed
a 0.8 percent drop in February, and a 0.6 percent boost in
production of equipment used by businesses, the fourth consecutive
gain.
   Factories making durable goods, items expected to last three or
more years, saw output rise 0.3 percent last month; output at
plants making non-durable goods was unchanged for the second month
in a row.
   Mining output increased 0.4 percent after a 1.0 percent drop in
February. Output at utilities dropped 1.2 percent after a 0.5
percent increase.
   David Wyss, an economist with Data Resources Inc., a Lexington,
Mass., forecasting firm, said the drop at utility companies was
caused by warmer-than-usual weather in March.
   He predicted that industrial production overall would pick up in
coming months.
   ``We ought to see auto production coming up ... Inventories are
now down to near-normal levels. The drop in utilities should be
over,'' Wyss said.
   The various changes left industrial production at 134.6 percent
of its 1977 base of 100.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
