<DOCNO> AP880415-0129 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1342EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ConstitutionExhibit Bjt   04-15 0579</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Constitution Exhibit, Bjt,0597</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Horse Around Bar in Tiny Town Houses Constitution Exhibit</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB IMRIE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>AMIDON, N.D. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawrence Buzalsky stopped at the Horse
Around Bar to buy a frozen pizza, but he got a taste of history and
a gander at the U.S. Constitution before heading home with his
dinner.
   ``Who built that?'' Buzalsky asked, circling a traveling exhibit
the state put together to celebrate the 200th birthday of the U.S.
Constitution. ``There's a lot of reading.''
   The Horse Around Bar, one of two businesses in this prairie
ranching town, is playing host to the four-sided display through
Monday, because there is no other place for it in the county.
   The wooden exhibit was too large to fit through the doors of
either the nearby Slope County Courthouse or the school, and a
church that could accommodate it was already booked.
   Galan Hanson, who moved to Amidon from Wisconsin four years ago
to open the Horse Around Bar, said he gladly volunteered a large
garage and storage room attached to his saloon for the exhibit.
   Nine people had signed a guest book ``ratifying'' the
Constitution by Thursday afternoon.
   ``Some spend quite a lot of time back there reading the stuff
and some just look it over, in and out,'' Hanson said, sitting near
rows of liquor bottles, sipping coffee. ``In a lot of ways, it is
the conversation piece of the bar. (But) I really don't think it
will bring me any extra business.''
   The North Dakota Constitution Celebration Committee, headed by a
state Supreme Court justice, and the state Department of Public
Instruction created the exhibit and intend to display it in each of
the state's 53 counties.
   It's a mini-museum featuring old pictures, newspaper stories and
brief narratives about segments of North Dakota's history that
relate to individual freedoms and government powers.
   Amidon is in the southwest corner of North Dakota about 125
miles west of Bismarck and boasts that it's the smallest county
seat in the country.
   ``You can say 25 to 30 people live here,'' Slope County Sheriff
Pat Lorge said. ``It depends on what day it is.''
   Judy Bender, one of two teachers at the elementary school, said
all 20 students would go see the historical display Friday.
   It didn't make any difference that the field trip essentially
meant visiting a saloon, she said. ``The kids are used to it. They
frequent it quite often with their parents for supper,'' she said.
   The sheriff, whose office just is across U.S. Highway 85,
examined the exhibit Wednesday night.
   ``They have an old Slope County homestead on it,'' said Lorge,
whose grandfather was sheriff for 18 years. ``I'm not so sure it's
not the old Day place.''
   Hanson moved his pickup from the garage, which used to be a
repair shop for a farm supply store, to make way for the display.
   An old horse harness hangs on pegs on one wall, not far from a
saddle. A wooden-wheeled wagon that Hanson hitches to his
Clydesdales sits nearby. Hanson claims the wagon is at least 75
years old.
   Buzalsky, a rancher, circled the constitutional exhibit with its
red, white and blue ribbons a couple of times before leaning into a
chest freezer to pick out a pizza.
   He didn't have time to read all the history on the display.
   ``I have to get the pizza going,'' he said. ``The women folks
sent me to town to get it.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
