<1ST_LINE>r a AM-LostComputer     04-15 0458</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lost Computer,0473</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Computer Potato'' Has His Way of Life Back</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Teen-ager Charles Patterson has his way of
life back _ in a bigger and better way.
   The 17-year-old, who was born with gross motor impairment that
limits his physical activity, couldn't afford to replace his
Commodore 64 computer and disk drive when they were stolen from his
home, but got several replacement offers after a story appeared in
a local newspaper.
   On Thursday, Patterson's computer equipment was replaced by a
Ridgeland computer dealer.
   ``Thank you a lot,'' Patterson said repeatedly after the
computer was installed atop the family television set where his old
computer sat.
   ``It's overwhelming,'' said his mother, Florence Weeks, who
earns $700 a month at a taxi company. ``It's marvelous. I don't
have the words to say how I feel. To think of the total strangers
that were willing to help. I didn't know that there were that many
caring people out there.''
   Weeks said their home telephone rang constantly with people who
offered to give Patterson a computer or money.
   After talking with several people, Patterson, a senior at Murrah
High School, accepted a new IBM PC XT computer offered by John P.
Robinson, a 1974 Murrah graduate. Patterson also got a color
display, a modem and assorted software.
   Patterson's stolen computer and disk drive were worth $400;
Robinson's gift was valued at $3,000.
   ``It makes us feel good to help. I hope whoever got your
computer the first time won't come back,'' Robinson said.
   Patterson saved four years' allowance and lunch money to
purchase a computer. Earlier this month, a burglar broke into the
Patterson home and took the computer, a disk drive, $28 in cash and
a small television.
   Weeks said the computer was the first thing her son sought after
getting home from school.
   ``Every available moment he was sitting there,'' said Weeks, who
calls her son a ``computer potato.''
   ``It was his way of communicating with others. He cannot get out
and ride a bicycle or play baseball,'' she said.
   Patterson, a student in the Advanced Performing Arts Complex at
Murrah High School, said he used the computer to do homework and a
science fair project, write short stories and invent games.
   He had planned to use his computer to teach computer basics
during a camp this summer at Mississippi State University. He said
the theft occurred ``just as I was going to really need it the
most.''
   The incident taught him several lessons.
   ``I'm overwhelmed,'' he said. ``I think this was a dual lesson.
That computer was a favorite item in my life. I learned that you
don't get heavily attached to a thing like this. I learned about
the giving of people.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
