<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CDC-Suicides     04-15 0444</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CDC-Suicides,0455</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Extraordinary' Community Response To Suicides Can Be Appropriate,
CDC Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT BYRD</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The tragedies of multiple suicides by young
people can provide lessons for other communities to follow in the
future, according to a new report by the national Centers for
Disease Control.
   On March 11, 1987, in Bergenfield, N.J., two young men, 18 and
19, and two young women, 16 and 17, committed suicide by locking
themselves in a garage and sitting inside a car with the motor
running.
   Within days, school officials identified other students they
felt might be at risk, counseling was provided to young people and
a local suicide hotline and a walk-in counseling center were
started.
   The CDC report, as is the agency's custom, did not name the New
Jersey town where the four young people died on that date. But
Bergenfield has been identified in numerous news reports about the
deaths.
   After an investigation, the CDC noted in its weekly report
Thursday that ``when a suicide cluster does occur, an extraordinary
amount of community effort and resources is temporarily devoted to
suicide prevention.''
   ``Such a response ... is appropriate,'' the Atlanta-based health
agency said. ``It is prudent for a community faced with a suicide
cluster to make every effort to anticipate and prevent additional
suicides among susceptible individuals.''
   The CDC said communities should consider contingency plans for
suicide clusters, and ``may want to consider implementing a suicide
response plan before a cluster has begun.'' Many suicide clusters,
the agency said, have followed one or more deaths due to injuries
among young people.
   Planning ahead can keep communities from ``reinventing the
wheel'' during their own tragedies, said Dr. Patrick O'Carroll of
the CDC.
   ``There's no reason for every single community that runs into
this to try to start from scratch. There's experience they can try
to take advantage of,'' O'Carroll said.
   Bergenfield, a suburban community six miles west of New York,
had an annual suicide rate of seven per 100,000 during 1980-84,
significantly lower than the national rate of 12 per 100,000, CDC
researchers found.
   But in that town and in others where people have died in
apparent suicide pacts, there have been similarities, the CDC said:
other young people had died unnaturally before the suicides, and
the suicides may have had a ``contagious'' effect, prompting others
to try to kill themselves.
   The young Bergenfield men had both been friends of an
18-year-old who died in a fall from a cliff six months earlier. And
after the four teen-agers killed themselves, two other young people
_ a 20-year-old and a 17-year-old _ attempted suicide together in
the same garage.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0132 </DOCNO>
