<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Trade     04-15 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Trade,550</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fitzwater Says Plant Closing Provision Would Harm Workers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MERRILL HARTSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Presidential spokesman Marlin Fitzwater denied
Friday that the Reagan administration's resistance to a
labor-backed plant-closing provision in a new trade bill
constitutes an anti-worker stance.
   While renewing President Reagan's threat to veto the legislation
if the plant shutdown notification requirement remained intact,
Fitzwater said, ``We're trying to keep people's jobs.''
   ``We want a trade bill that doesn't eliminate jobs through
foreign competition,'' he said.
   ``We want a bill that maximizes the opportunities for companies
to stay in business and people can keep their jobs,'' Fitzwater
told reporters. ``And that's what you're going to hear from us if
we have to veto this bill.''
   But during his daily White House news briefing, the spokesman
acknowledged that administration negotiators on the sweeping trade
bill are stymied in attempts to talk lawmakers into discarding the
plant notification provision.
   ``I think there's still some opportunity for talk,'' he said.
But he said Reagan would not accept any version of the trade bill
that contained provisions which are ``injurious to a dynamic
economy.''
   Fitzwater reiterated Reagan's veto intentions in the wake of a
further deterioration of America's trade deficit and as House and
Senate members wrangled over the language to be kept in the final
version of the 1,000-page trade bill.
   Conferees are trying to iron out differences between competing
House and Senate versions of the bill. The plant-closings
provision, which was approved by the Senate but not the House,
would require companies with at least 100 employees to give 60-day
notice of plant closings or layoffs involving at least 150
positions if that represented one-third of the work force.
   All layoffs of 500 or more would have to be accompanied by
notice, regardless of whether they represented a third of the work
force.
   Business groups oppose the provision, arguing that it could lead
to other steps to strip away the prerogatives of company managers.
The AFL-CIO and other organizations in the labor movement maintain
the measure is necessary to prepare workers for the need to find
new employment.
   ``The Congress made good progress in moving toward such a
bill,'' Fitzwater said Friday. But he said the White House is
displeased that the plant-closing provision remains in the bill.
   ``Our negotiators ... were encouraged to believe the plant
closing provision would be eliminated,'' Fitzwater said. ``Later,
however, we were told that after certain consultations took place,
they could not remove that provision. The labor unions apparently
would sacrifice the entire trade bill for this provision.''
   ``While the administration would be willing to accept a positive
trade bill, we cannot accept one that includes seriously flawed
elements that will hurt America's competitiveness,'' the spokesman
said.
   ``If the bill reaches the president in its present form, the
president will veto it,'' Fitzwater said.
   The Democratic leadership had seemed close to dropping the
plant-closings plan on Wednesday. But overnight lobbying by
organized labor led to a chorus of protests Thursday in the House
Democratic caucus, said sources who spoke only if not quoted by
name.
   Top Democrats announced their support for the plan at
midafternoon Thursday. They said new figures from the Commerce
Department showing a widening U.S. trade deficit and an
accompanying 101-point drop in the stock market called for a strong
legislative response.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
