<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VitalSigns     04-15 0486</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Vital Signs,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Star Trek-style Monitor Could Be On Market in 18 Months</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID SIMPSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The idea is something out of ``Star Trek,'' a
hand-held device that a doctor or nurse can point at a patient to
register heart and respiration rates.
   But the vital signs monitor which a new company hopes to put on
the market in 18 months is expected to look more like a pocket
calculator than the sleek cylinders used by Dr. Leonard ``Bones''
McCoy on the Enterpirse.
   And the device was inspired not by science fiction, but by a
military need to help medics in the battlefield.
   A prototype somewhat bigger than a briefcase has been delivered
to the military by Georgia Tech researchers. The university has
licensed Health Techniques of Georgia Inc., a company formed last
August, to sell the technology to civilian health care providers.
   ``We think it has particular application for patients who are
severely burned, where no contact (with the skin) is possible or
looked for, and also with patients who may have a contagious
disease or patients who have compromised immune systems and have to
be isolated from contact with other people,'' said Doug Robinson,
chief operating officer of Health Techniques.
   Robinson said the device would weigh 1{ to 2 pounds and would
have a top range of six feet to 10 feet. He said the comparison to
the chirping medical scanners on ``Star Trek'' is inevitable.
   ``I've heard that more times than you can imagine. It's really
very close to that,'' he said.
   Stephen Bonasera, a research engineer on the Tech team which is
developing the monitor, said the device depends on microwave
transmissions bounced off the patient's body. ``Phase changes'' in
the waves show the heart's movements, he said.
   In addition to the heart and respiratory rate functions, Health
Techniques hopes the device can be refined to also measure body
temperature.
   Bonasera said the monitor also can reveal information about the
mechanical workings of the heart, something an electrocardiogram,
or EKG, cannot do. The researcher said more work is needed on
interpreting the returning microwave signals to do that.
   Tech's work began in 1984 with Navy funding. The Air Force later
contributed funding, and Bonasera said the Army also is interested.
   ``They're imagining, say, a chemical battlefield in Europe, that
you have medics going around and picking up patients for trage and
you want to limit the exposure of the medics. They want a device
you could point at a patient to find out yes or no, is he alive?''
he said.
   Dr. David Erwin of the Air Force School of Aerospace Medicine at
Brooks Air Force Base, Texas, said other battlefield casualties
also would benefit.
   ``In the military, we have situations where people are in all
types of clothing; it makes it very difficult to put on a
stethoscope or blood pressure test,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0134 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1359EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Billig-Ruling 3rdLd-Writethru a0650 04-15 0740</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Billig-Ruling, 3rd Ld-Writethru, a0650,730</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs grafs 4-5 pvs, Billig automatically, to restore initial
identification of spokeswoman.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A day after his conviction on charges of
killing three patients was overturned, Navy heart surgeon Donal M.
Billig was allowed today to leave Fort Leavenworth, Kan., where he
had been held prisoner for two years.
   The U.S. Navy-Marine Corps Court of Military Review on Thursday
overturned Billig's conviction because, the court said, ``the
evidence was simply not sufficient.''
   Billig, held at the fort since 1986, was released from the
prison itself Thursday, but was held overnite in the base's
bachelor officers quarters while administrative paperwork was
completed.
   Billig automatically returns to active duty with his previous
rank of commander and is eligible for $120,000 in back pay, but he
cannot practice medicine, said Navy spokeswoman, Lt. Janet Mescus.
   She said Billig would probably be assigned to a Navy-Marine
Corps reserve center in Kansas City while the Navy makes a decision
on appealing the verdict. The service has 20 days to make that
decision.
   The court's 20-page opinion said prosecutors had failed to
establish Billig's guilt ``beyond a reasonable doubt.''
   The appeals court said the prosecutors at Billig's 1986 court
martial ``lost sight of the fact that coronary artery bypass
surgery is an inherently risky business.''
   The prosecutors argued that Billig used questionable surgical
techniques, the court said, but never really produced the evidence
or testimony to demonstrate that Billig's work in the operating
room was so out of line as to constitute criminal conduct.
   ``We shall set aside all findings of guilty based on this
factual insufficiency of the evidence,'' the court said.
   The Navy has 20 days to file a formal motion with the appeals
court asking it to reconsider the matter. The service said Thursday
it had made no decision yet on pursuing an appeal.
   Billig, 57, was the former chief heart surgeon at the Navy's
flagship Bethesda, Md., Naval Hospital, and held the military rank
of commander.
   He was convicted in early 1986 of two counts of involuntary
manslaughter and one count of negligent homicide in the deaths of
three patients. He also was convicted on 18 of 24 counts of
dereliction of duty stemming from other operations. He was
sentenced on March 3, 1986, to four years in prison. Last summer,
he was rebuffed in his first bid for parole.
   Billig's case attracted great public attention, in part because
of the sensational nature of some of the charges. It also prompted
congressional reviews of military health care in general and
several large monetary settlements between the government and
relatives of Billig's patients.
   Prosecutors described Billig as an egocentric man, nearly blind
in one eye, who hid his visual handicap and continued performing
complex heart operations despite numerous warnings that he was
killing patients.
   The appeals court, in its opinion, said it was troubled by
Billig's conviction because his court-martial had involved criminal
charges as opposed to civil claims for damages based on negligence.
   The court quoted from a New Jersey Supreme Court ruling that
stated: ``The question is not whether a defendant should absorb the
dollar loss of his victim, but whether his conduct justifies
stamping him a criminal and sending him to state prison.''
   In Billig's case, the military court said it appeared the
prosecutors ``lost sight of the fact that coronary artery bypass
surgery is an inherently risky business ... and that those patients
who agree to this elective surgery are quite ill in the first place
...''
   ``Given the critical nature of the work and its complexity,
these surgeons face a difficult enough task without having to worry
about the spectre of the criminal prosecutor, waiting to reduce to
a `charge sheet' honest mistakes which fall far short of the gross,
wanton and deliberate misconduct ... that truly deserves punishment.
   ``We are not convinced beyond a reasonable doubt that the deaths
that formed the basis of the appellant's conviction were due to any
negligence, simple or otherwise, on his part.''
   The court also faulted the presiding military judge at the
court-martial for allowing the prosecution to conduct ``a smear
campaign'' against Billig.
   ``The appellant was forced not only to defend against the
charges, but also to explain and account for virtually all of his
mistakes, professional setbacks or surgical misadventures during
the previous 20 years. This `bad surgeon' theory permeated the
trial proceedings and undoubtedly influenced the court members'
decisions.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
