<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Israel Bjt   04-15 0751</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, Bjt,0770</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Heavily Guarded Settlers Hike Near Site of Fatal Clash</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto TLV1</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Dozens of Israeli settlers, guarded by as many
soldiers, marched Friday near the Arab town where 15-year-old
settler Tirza Porat and two Palestinians were killed in an exchange
of gunfire and rocks last week.
   Their purpose was to demonstrate that Jews could walk freely in
the occupied West Bank. Army radio said they objected to the large
army guard for the mass re-enactment of the hike by Miss Porat and
a group of friends.
   Israeli troops wounded two Palestinians in scattered violence
Friday after midday prayers on the Moslem sabbath, hospital
officials reported. The army deployed hundreds of soldiers and
surrounded major mosques to keep order in the occupied West Bank
and Gaza Strip.
   Violence after Friday prayers has become a ritual since violence
began Dec. 8 in the occupied West Bank and Gaza, which Israel
captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war. At
least 146 Palestinians have been killed in the 18 weeks, along with
Miss Porat and an Israeli soldier.
   Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir said he was ready to invite Eduard
A. Shevardnadze to Israel if he could be certain the invitation
would be accepted, a spokesman said. The Soviet foreign minister is
to visit Jordan, Syria and possibly Egypt later this month.
   Israeli soldiers surrounded mosques in the West Bank cities of
Hebron and Qalqilya and imposed a curfew Friday in the downtown
district of Khan Yunis in the Gaza Strip, Arab reports said.
   Soldiers and Palestinians clashed at several mosques in Gaza and
two Palestinians were reported wounded. Officials at Shifa Hospital
said a 13-year-old boy from nearby Beit Hanoun in critical
condition with a bullet wound in the stomach.
   They said an 18-year-old in Jabaliya was was shot in the leg,
the officials said.
   The army confirmed clashes at Jabaliya but said soldiers used
only rubber bullets, and said the Beit Hanoun incident was being
investigated.
   An army helicopter flew surveillance over Jerusalem's two main
mosques as thousands of Moslem worshipers gathered to pray.
   After prayers, 250 youths circled Al Aqsa mosque waving a
Palestinian flag. They shouted ``Allahu Akbar! (God is Great!)''
and threw rocks and empty bottles at police.
   Associated Press photographer Max Nash saw police detain five
boys aged 7 to 9. They had been throwing rocks near Flower Gate, a
northern entrance to the walled Old City that borders a main
shopping street used by Jews and Arabs.
   Romam Aldubi, a 26-year-old settler who guarded Tirza Porat and
the other hikers April 6, was beaten on the head in clash with Arab
residents of Beita and has not regained conciousness. Investigative
reports indicate the girl may have been killed by Aldubi's gun but
the bullet has not been found.
   Maj. Gen Amram Mitzna, military commander of the West Bank,
visited Aldubi on Friday at Jerusalem's Hadassah Hospital, brushing
past members of the man's family who angrily asked him to go away.
   ``I don't welcome the visit,'' said Aldubi's brother Yanir, 29.
``Romam is lying here because of the way Mitzna reacted to the Arab
violence. A strong army should be feared not only when it's in the
area, but also when it is not there.''
   Yossi Ahimeir, a spokesman for Shamir, said the prime minister
``would very much like to welcome the Soviet foreign minister to
Jerusalem for discussions, but Shamir will not just throw out an
invitation. He needs to know the foreign minister will come.''
   Shevardnadze said Thursday after signing an accord on withdrawal
of Soviet troops from Afghanistan that it could open the way for a
Middle East peace settlement.
   ``The signing of the Geneva agreements certainly stimulates
positive processes in the settlement of other regional issues,
including the Middle East,'' he told reporters in Geneva.
   Shamir opposes the Kremlin proposal for an international
conference including the Palestine Liberation Organization and the
five permanent members of the U.N. Security Council: the United
States, Soviet Union, China, Britain and France.
   Under the Soviet plan, participants in the conference would play
active roles in peace talks.
   The prime minister suggests that the United States and Soviet
Union invite Israel and Jordan to a meeting and then leave the two
adversaries to negotiate directly.
   He also says Moscow must allow Soviet Jews to emigrate and must
renew diplomatic relations severed during the 1967 war before it
can have a part in Middle East negotiations.
</TEXT>
