<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1412EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     04-15 0527</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0546</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unions Strike For Raises</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About half of Lebanon's businesses closed
Friday in the first day of a national strike called by a union
demanding a 300 percent wage increase.
   The government of this chaos-ridden nation, which faces a severe
economic crisis, has offered an increase of about 75 percent.
   Police said 50 percent of both Moslem and Christian areas were
closed in response to the strike call issued Thursday by the
General Confederation of Labor Unions, or GCLU.
   Some banks, schools, restaurants, movie theaters, gas stations
and other businesses closed in Beirut's Moslem and Christian
sectors as well as in other major cities and towns, a police
statement said.
   However, a variety of businesses defied the 300,000-member union
and maintained normal activity.
   The union called for the two-day strike after rejecting as
insufficient the 75 percent increase in private- and public-sector
wages announced by acting Prime Minister Salim Hoss.
   ``Some employers are clearly defying the GCLU's decision. They
called their employees to work, and strangely these employees
reported to duty,'' a police spokesman said.
   ``GCLU teams are touring Beirut and other cities in an effort to
convince violators to abide by the strike,'' said the spokesman.
   A government source, speaking on condition of anonymity, said
the 75 percent increase ``is the highest the state treasury and
private businesses can afford.''
   ``The employees realize this. That's why they are hesitant in
abiding by the strike,'' he said.
   Ahmed Srouji, who runs a ready-made clothes factory in Moslem
west Beirut, said even a 75 percent raise would be ``difficult to
meet.''
   ``We will have to raise our prices. In this case, the unions
will start nagging again and demand another pay raise,'' Srouji
said at his factory, which stayed open Friday.
   ``If the unions insist on a 300 percent raise, I will close,''
he threatened. ``Closing will strip my 70 employees from their
income. Is this what the GCLU wants?''
   Some of his employees also appeared convinced that the size of
the raise demand was not in their interest.
   ``The boss will definitely fire most of us if the 300 percent
increase was decided,'' said Elie Abu Issa, who works at a
hairdressing salon in Christian east Beirut.
   ``There would be less clients if the raise was decided because
the fees would be brought up sharply. In such a case, the boss and
an assistant will be enough to handle the job, and most of us will
be fired,'' Abu Issa said.
   ``I don't want to be unemployed, especially when prices are
soaring,'' he added.
   The Lebanese pound slipped against foreign currencies following
Hoss' 75 percent pay increase announcement Thursday and closed at
400 to the dollar. It opened at 380 to the dollar early in the day.
   Lebanon's economy, once the most flourishing in the Middle East,
has been hit hard by 13 years of violence.
   The pound, which rated 2.5 to the dollar before the outbreak of
the civil war in 1975, has declined sharply against foreign
currencies, pushing prices sky high in a nation that imports more
than 85 percent of its needs.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
