<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1414EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Denmark     04-15 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Denmark,260</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Distressed over Danish Anti-Nuclear Vote</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department said Friday it was
``deeply distressed'' over a resolution approved by the Danish
parliament which closes a loophole in a government ban on ships
carrying nuclear weapons into Danish ports.
   The resolution, approved Thursday by a 75-58 vote, requires the
government to inform visiting naval vessels of Denmark's
anti-nuclear policy. Denmark has a nuclear ban policy but has not
been asking such vessels if they are carrying nuclear weapons.
   State Department spokesman Charles Redman said implementation of
the Danish resolution in a way which is inconsistent with the U.S.
policy of not discussing which ships carry nuclear weapons would
undercut NATO security. The United States has a long-standing
policy of neither confirming nor denying the presence of nuclear
weapons aboard its ships.
   ``This policy is central to the U.S. ability to fulfill its NATO
commitments,'' Redman said. ``We are not going to change it.''
   ``It would have extremely serious consequences for U.S.-Danish
defense cooperation,'' he said, adding that the impact of this
issue extends beyond bilateral relations.
   ``It goes to the very heart of the meaning and interlocking
nature of our mutual commitments within the NATO alliance,'' he
said.
   Redman said the policy of withholding information about the
presence of nuclear weapons is aimed at keeping ``terrorists and
saboteurs'' in the dark and makes effective attacks on U.S. forces
more difficult.
   Redman added that the United States will review together with
the Danish government and other NATO allies the implications of the
resolution for the NATO alliance and continued defense cooperation
with Denmark.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
