<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Japan-US,0199</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Military Reverses Decision To Fire Japanese Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The U.S. military on Friday reversed an earlier
decision to lay off 271 Japanese employees at its bases on Okinawa.
   Hiroo Takakura, head of the labor division of Japan's Defense
Facilities Administration Agency, said the U.S. decision followed
talks since last year between Japanese and U.S. officials.
   The U.S. Military Forces in Japan had planned the layoffs
because the yen's recent rise against the dollar made it more
expensive to maintain employees.
   U.S. officials notified the Japanese government of the decision
Friday, Takakura said.
   Japan agreed last month to assume a larger share of the costs of
running U.S. military bases in Japan. Under the agreement, Japan's
share of allowances for Japanese base workers will be boosted from
the current 50 percent to 100 percent, or about $162 million in
1991.
   The United States pays the salaries of the Japanese workers, but
all other benefits and allowances, including transportation,
housing and retirement expenses, will be covered by Japan.
   There are about 21,000 Japanese employees at U.S. military
facilities across Japan, where more than 60,000 U.S. military
personnel are stationed.
</TEXT>
