<1ST_LINE>u p AM-NewYorkPolls     04-15 0683</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-New York Polls,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Stalled, Dukakis Leading Jackson in New York Polls</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Albert Gore Jr.'s attacks on his rivals
have brought him more animosity than votes in New York, leaving his
campaign seemingly stalled in the last days before Tuesday's
primary, poll analysts say.
   Gore's Democratic opponents have solidified their support,
surveys this week indicate, with Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
retaining a comfortable lead over Jesse Jackson. Gore is a poor
third.
   One poll indicated Dukakis may have overcome the weakness of
support that plagued him in early contests. It said 67 percent of
his support was strong, 9 points better than Walter Mondale's in
1984, when Mondale won the state.
   Jackson maintained his powerful support among blacks, who make
up about one-quarter of the Democratic primary vote, but was
drawing only about 17 percent of the white vote and was splitting
the Hispanic vote with Dukakis.
   ``I think it's a two-person race. I don't believe to date that
Gore has made a mark,'' said Meyer S. Frucher, a leading state
political strategist. ``A lot of people feel turned off'' by Gore's
campaign style, he said.
   Two New York polls by the Marist College Institute for Public
Opinion appeared to support that view. One done April 5-6 said Gore
was viewed unfavorably by 29 percent. One week of campaigning
later, that was up to 36.
   ``Part of Gore's problem is an overwhelmingly negative reaction
on the part of the black community,'' said Lee Miringoff, the
Marist pollster. Nine percent of blacks rated Gore favorably, 50
percent unfavorably, he said.
   The Marist poll also indicated Gore was not drawing Jews from
Dukakis, despite his aggressive effort to portray himself as more
staunchly pro-Israel.
   ``The problem with the Gore strategy among the Jews is that he
was appealing to conservative Jewish Democrats. And those are
called Republicans in New York,'' Miringoff said. Dukakis had 70
percent of the Jewish vote in the Marist poll, Gore 12 percent _
unchanged from the week before. Dukakis's favorable-unfavorable
rating among Jews was 87-7; Gore's, 49-23.
   The Marist poll was conducted Monday and Tuesday, before Gore
launched a sharp midweek attack on Dukakis' nuclear policy.
   Frucher, a close adviser to Gov. Mario Cuomo, said he expected
Gore's newer moves to miss the mark. ``Negative works, don't get me
wrong. But it only works if you have a positive image,'' he said.
``And that just hasn't been created.''
   For Jackson, widespread support among whites remained elusive. A
New York Post poll Friday put his white support at 17 percent;
Marist said 16 percent.
   Voters who are supporting Jackson are doing so solidly; 82
percent in the Marist poll said they backed him strongly. That
would help him in a light turnout, when only the most committed
voters show up at the polls.
   The Marist poll found 67 percent of Dukakis' supporters were
strongly behind him. A survey by ABC News and The Washington Post
found less strength for both Dukakis and Jackson. It said half
Dukakis' supporters were strong, compared to two-thirds of
Jackson's.
   The ABC News-Post poll was done Wednesday night among 176 likely
Democratic voters and had a margin of error of 8 points. The Marist
poll was done Monday and Tuesday among 359 Democrats and had a
5-point error margin.
   The strength of Gore's support was flat _ 40 percent in the
April 5-6 Marist poll, 41 percent in this week's survey.
   The Marist poll said 13 percent of likely Democratic voters were
undecided or uncommitted; a CBS News poll said 19 percent were
uncommitted or undecided.
   The CBS poll, which was done Monday through Wednesday and had a
4-point error margin, had Dukakis with 45 percent support, Jackson
28 and Gore 8. ABC had it as Dukakis 49, Jackson, 34, Gore 8. The
Marist poll said Dukakis had 46 percent, Jackson 34 and Gore 7. The
New York Post poll, done Monday and Tuesday and with a 4-point
error margin, had Dukakis at 50 percent, Jackson 33, Gore 9.
</TEXT>
