<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Afghan     04-15 0555</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Afghan,0573</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soviets Blast U.S. Position on Geneva Accords</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Less than 24 hours after the signing of the Geneva
accords on Afghanistan, Tass accused the United States on Friday of
trying to ruin the agreement by continuing to supply weapons to the
Moslem insurgents.
   ``Washington is confirming its policy of neoglobalism, a course
of export of counter-revolution,'' the news agency said in the
first official Soviet press commentary issued since the signing of
the pact in the Swiss city.
   Tass said private and public figures from various countries had
hailed the agreement, which paves the way for the May 15 start of
the withdrawal of the estimated 115,000 Soviet troops now in
Afghanistan.
   But, Tass said, the U.S. government has been reacting ``in a
typical Washington manner.''
   It said the U.S. government was interfering in Afghan-Soviet
relations by insisting the Soviet Union stop its military aid to
Afghanistan's Marxist government in Kabul.
   U.S. officials have said they will continue aiding the
guerrillas as long as Soviet military supplies to the regime of
President Najib continue.
   Similar American interference continues in other regional
conflicts in the Middle East, Central America and Africa, where the
United States is using ``illegal, unclean practices'' to bring
about a situation favorable to itself, Tass said.
   The Soviet Union and United States signed agreements in Geneva
on Thursday pledging to guarantee Pakistani and Afghan observance
of the settlement of the 10-year-old Afghan conflict.
   It said that if Pakistan and Afghanistan strictly observe the
Geneva agreement's prohibition against interference in each other's
affairs, Washington's military support of the guerrillas, funneled
through Pakistan, ``will not have a decisive influence.''
   However, a separate Tass commentary expressed concern about
Pakistan's position as stated by President Mohammed Zia Ul-Haq.
   ``The ink hadn't dried on the Geneva agreements, in which the
sides obliged not to offer their territory for hostile actions
against other countries, when the Pakistani president undertook to
aid the mujahadeen in the struggle for the armed overthrow of the
Kabul administration.'' Tass said.
   It called the Pakistani position ``irresponsible.''
   The mujahadeen guerrillas, based in Pakistan, have rejected the
Geneva agreements and vowed to drive the Kabul government from
power.
   The Soviets sent troops into Afghanistan in December 1979 to
preside over the replacement of one Marxist leader by another. They
stayed to help combat a nationwide insurgency.
   Also Friday, a Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman said the number
of Soviet soldiers killed and injured in Afghanistan will be
disclosed during the troop withdrawal.
   Spokesman Vadim Perfiliev told reporters at a regular news
briefing that Foreign Minister Eduard A. Shevardnadze had promised
disclosure of the figures while in Geneva for the signing of the
Afghan agreement.
   Perfiliev was asked at the briefing whether he believes Soviet
citizens, who have never been informed of casualties during the
Soviet involvement in Afghanistan, have the right to know the full
costs of the war.
   ``Of course,'' he replied. ``As far as concrete figures are
concerned, as the foreign minister mentioned yesterday in Geneva,
the number of Soviet troops in Afghanistan and other figures on
that score, casualties, will be published simultaneously with the
process of withdrawal of Soviet troops from Afghanistan.''
   Western officials estimate that at least 10,000 Soviets have
been killed in the war, and about 25,000 wounded.
</TEXT>
