<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Bush-GOP     04-15 0691</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bush-GOP,700</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bush: Noriega Getting Libyan Support</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush said Friday that
``millions of dollars'' from Libya is helping Panamanian strongman
Antonio Manuel Noriega resist U.S. efforts to force him out of the
country.
   Still, Bush told the American Society of Newspaper Editors,
``Noriega should go and Noriega will go.''
   Bush cited ``several reliable sources'' for his information but
did not elaborate. State Department spokesman Charles Redman
indicated he had no further information on Bush's allegation.
   The vice president labeled Democratic charges that the
administration had propped up Noriega as ``demagogic statements''
and declared: ``It is this administration that has brought Noriega
to justice, or at least taken the first step.''
   Meanwhile, Pat Robertson, Bush's only remaining rival for the
Republican presidential nomination, told the same audience that
Bush's popularity stemmed almost entirely from his association with
President Reagan.
   ``George Bush was regarded as `Reagan the Second,''' Robertson
said. He acknowledged there was no way to deny Bush the GOP
nomination.
   ``It is obvious from the delegate count that has come out that
George Bush is going to be the nominee of the Republican Party
absent any unexpected eventuality,'' the former television minister
said.
   About his own camapign, Robertson said, ``I really don't think
looking now at the results that anything made any difference.
George Bush ran a superb campaign. And I had no conception that he
had adopted the Reagan mantle in so total a way.''
   Still, Robertson indicated he was not ready to abandon his
effort, saying he hoped to ``energize the people who support me''
to play a role in the GOP convention in August. However, he said he
would support the party nominee in November.
   Meanwhile, Sen. Bob Dole, who withdrew from the race earlier
this month, said he was ready to help Bush before the convention.
   Bush and Dole had lunch in the Capitol Friday with Republican
senators and former senators, including White House Chief of Staff
Howard Baker.
   In a unity meeting staged for television cameras and reporters,
Dole and Bush stood side-by-side behind Dole's desk and said they
were ready to work together.
   ``Yes, we had differences, some would say shades of
differences,'' Dole said. But ``we're ready to go to work for
George Bush.''
   Bush, in turn, said ``Nobody possibly could have been more
gracious than Bob Dole.''
   Bush also planned a private meeting later in the day at his
residence with former President Richard Nixon.
   The vice president opened his speech by greeting ``the editors
of the nation's finest newspapers _ and also those who publish
Doonesbury,'' a lighthearted reference to the syndicated comic
strip by G.B. Trudeau that frequently has poked fun at Bush.
   In a speech that focused on foreign policy, Bush cited the
administration's efforts to ``protect civilian rule in Panama
against Noriega.''
   ``So far he has stood up to the considerable economic pressures
we have applied, and I can tell you one reason why,'' Bush said.
``Several reliable sources indicate that he is receiving millions
of dollars in support from Libya.''
   Later, at a State Department briefing, spokesman Redman was
asked about Bush's allegations. He shrugged his shoulders,
indicating that he had no information on the matter.
   However, last month it was reported that a Panamanian defense
force major who defected told U.S. officials that he had been sent
to Cuba in early March to pick up a $50 million payment for Noriega
from Libya, but that the funds were never transferred.
   Bush also reiterated his contention that he did not know about
Noriega's involvement in drugs until the Panamanian leader's
indictment in the United States in March. ``In terms of Noriega,
those are the facts,'' he said.
   In response to a question, Bush also said that the
administration is ``purusing every lead, going down every rabbit
trail, running into dead ends'' in efforts to free hostages being
held in Lebanon, including Terry Anderson, the Associated Press'
Middle East correspondent.
   ``There aren't any easy answers,'' he said, suggesting that poor
intelligence-gathering in the Middle East is making it difficult
``even to find where these people are.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
