<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nicaragua-Contras     04-15 0656</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nicaragua-Contras,0678</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Returning Rebel Leaders Will Find More Misery in Managua</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Nicaragua Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BRYNA BRENNAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Contra rebel leaders returning to
Managua on Friday, some after years in exile, can expect to find
considerably more misery but not many tangible changes in their
capital.
   The trip by the directorate of the Miami-based Nicaraguan
Resistance was to further work started last month to reach a
lasting cease-fire and end more than six years of civil war.
   Just a few months back such a visit seemed impossible.
   But haggling and compromise on both sides, coupled with a need
to end the grueling war, made the trip a necessity.
   The Contras 45-member delegation will find that the leftist
Sandinistas still maintain a firm control on the day-to-day
workings of the government, although their popularity has slipped.
   The capital still is dusty and hot this time of year, though
increased poverty and population are evident.
   Vast open lots left barren since the 1972 earthquake have not
been filled. The walls of homes and buildings bear pro-Sandinista
and Marxist grafitti. A steep hillside bears the initials of the
Sandinista party.
   A large black iron statue in a downtown plaza shows a fighter
with one fist in the air, the other arm raised and holding a
Soviet-designed AK-47 rifle. Red-and-black Sandinista flags fly
everywhere.
   Thousands of people, most from the rural north, flooded into the
capital and its environs to escape the ravages of war. Managua is
home to about a third of the nation's population of 3 million.
Wooden shacks sit in dusty lots.
   Water has been rationed for the past few years. Some
neighborhoods do without for as little as two days a week, while
others receive water only a few hours per week.
   There are shortages of everything from spare parts for cars to
the basics of rice and beans.
   Discontent was on the rise earlier this year because of the
economic conditions, the scarcities and the mandatory draft. But
attitudes changed last month when the cease-fire talks made it seem
that peace could be a reality.
   The mood in the capital has been one of guarded hope, with most
residents acknowledging there never has been a point so close to
ending the war.
   The Contra delegation was headed by the Resistance's board, made
up of Adolfo Calero, Aristides Sanchez, Alfredo Cesar, Pedro
Joaquin Chamorro and Maria Azucena Ferrey.
   All of the directorate members, except for Ms. Ferrey, come from
upper crust Nicaraguan families.
   Calero went into exile in 1982 and was the political head of the
largest Contra group, the Nicaraguan Democratic Force, based in
Honduras. He holds a law degree and headed the Coca-Cola Co. of
Nicaragua.
   He opposed the former government of dictator Anastasio Somoza,
ousted by the Sandinistas in 1979. But he later called the ruling
Sandinista National Liberation Front a group of Marxists.
   Sanchez left Nicaragua for Honduras, where he was responsible
for Contra logistics. He is considered a stauch nationalist and a
pragmatic and sensible negotiator.
   Cesar joined the Sandinistas in 1978 and after the revolution
became executive director of the International Construction Fund.
He also served as head of the Central Bank.
   He left Nicaragua in 1982, saying the Sandinistas were Marxists,
and moved to Costa Rica. He worked with the government there and
later joined the Contras operating on the southern front.
   Chamorro, whose family owns the opposition newspaper La Prensa,
went into exile in 1984. His brother, Carlos Fernando, is editor of
the Sandinista newspaper Barricada. One of his sisters is the
ambassador to Costa Rica.
   Ms. Ferrey was the latest to join the directorate, having stayed
in Nicaragua until last year. She was staunchly opposed to Somoza
and reportedly aided some of the Sandinistas during their guerrilla
campaign against him.
   A member of the Social Christian Party, she comes from a
middle-class family and became a vocal internal Sandinista critic.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
