<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1530EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-CubanBonds     04-15 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Cuban Bonds,0584</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Widow Wins Early Round In Battle To Cash In 50-Year-Old Cuban
Bonds</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An elderly widow has won the first round in her
legal battle against a bank and the government to cash in $127,000
worth of half-century-old bonds issued by the Republic of Cuba.
   The ruling led the woman's lawyer to wonder what happened to the
millions of dollars that should have been in a bank account to back
the $1,000-face-value bonds. It also has fueled speculation in the
bonds.
   The 1937 $85 million bond issue matured in 1977.
   Manufacturers Hanover Trust of New York was an indentured
trustee for part of the bond issue, meaning the Cuban government
contracted to pay a set amount to Manufacturers Hanover, which
would pay the bondholders. The government of Fidel Castro stopped
making payments in 1960.
   When Margarita Rosa De Cuellar, 77, of Virginia Gardens in Dade
County, applied to Manufacturers Hanover in early 1987 to redeem
the bonds, which she inherited from her mother, the bank refused.
   The federal Office of Foreign Assets Control told her the bank
was correct in refusing to redeem the bonds, because they were
considered frozen under the Trading with the Enemy Act.
   Mrs. De Cuellar filed suit in September, and U.S. District Judge
C. Clyde Atkins ruled March 13 that she was entitled to the money
because the United States unreasonably considered all the bonds,
even those held by U.S. residents, as frozen assets.
   An American resident shouldn't be stopped from seeking payment
from an American institution, the judge decreed.
   ``This court recognizes the importance of providing the
president with flexibility in his negotiations with the Cuban
government. However, the United States may only use those assets
that are not property of American residents,'' he wrote in his
order.
   Attorneys for the government and Manufacturers Hanover Trust
asked to delay payment to Mrs. De Cuellar pending a decision on
whether to appeal. Her lawyer, Alex Arandia, filed a counter motion
asking that they pay immediately. No court date has been set on the
motions.
   ``There's many unidentified holders of these bonds. ... We don't
know who they are,'' Julian Kroeger, an attorney for the bank, told
the judge.
   Estimating there are $44 million in bonds in circulation in this
country, the bank says there is only about $1.5 million in the fund
to pay off bondholders.
   Arandia, Mrs. De Cuellar's lawyer, said he wants a full
accounting of the bond fund, arguing that according to the payment
schedule, the bank should have received $40 million by 1960.
   Although the bond issue was to mature in 1977, Arandia said that
as far as he can determine his client appears to be the first to
ever try to redeem any of the bonds, meaning the question of
whether they could be redeemed had never been asked before.
   ``It's very strange,'' he said Friday of the entire case.
   The federal Office of Foreign Assets Control was not happy with
the judge's ruling. ``The court's decision could become a vehicle
enabling Cuba to obtain U.S. dollars,'' said agency spokesman R.
Richard Newcombe.
   In the meantime, speculators have been snapping up the old bonds
and trading them on the New York Stock Exchange, with hopes of a
thaw in relations between Cuba and the United States.
   Before Atkins' ruling, the bonds traded for $200, but a week
later they traded for $450.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0157 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Soviet-Dali     04-15 0469</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soviet-Dali,0481</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>First Soviet Exhibition of Salvador Dali's Drawings</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANDREW KATELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The artistic freedom fostered by Mikhail S.
Gorbachev brought the work of Spanish surrealist Salvador Dali out
of a ``zone of silence'' to Soviets for the first time Friday, the
head of the host museum said.
   Irina A. Antonova, the director of the Pushkin Museum of Fine
Arts, said Dali's nightmarish style in sculpture, painting and
graphics had been off limits in the Soviet Union.
   ``The creative work of the surrealists, including Dali to some
extent, belonged to a zone of silence of such themes of art that
were closed until recent times,'' said Antonova.
   Gorbachev's ``glasnost'' policy of more openness has encouraged
intellectuals and artists to explore previously forbidden themes in
their work, and Antonova said the display of Dali's work represents
a break from conservative policies of Soviet museums.
   ``Very many blank spots in literature, art and cinematography
are being opened for our audiences,'' she said. ``And I would
assume that the work of Dali now should be placed in that context.''
   Before Gorbachev, Soviet media blasted Dali as decadent and
degenerate and did not publish any reproductions of his work.
   The Pushkin Museum kicked off its display of 160 Dali graphics
and a few sculptures from the collection of Frenchman Pierre
Argillet with private showings for Soviet and foreign journalists
and for invited dignitaries such as government officials.
   The one-month exhibition opens to the public Saturday, but
people began lining up Friday during a snowstorm in hopes of
getting into the museum, a few blocks from the Kremlin. They were
told tickets won't go on sale until Saturday.
   Long lines are common at most cultural events involving foreign
artists. Antonova bristled when asked if it would be difficult for
people to get tickets.
   ``They will get tickets just like everywhere, as in Paris, New
York or Munich, people will stand at the cashier's booth, buy
tickets and go to the exhibit,'' she said, declining to say how
many people would be allowed to view the exhibit daily.
   Argillet, 78, said Soviet officials became interested in his
collection of Dali's sketches after musicians from the Soviet
Conservatory and dancers from the Kirov and Bolshoi ballets saw the
works in the Frenchman's home, the Chateau de Vaux le Penil in
Melun, 24 miles southeast of Paris. He signed a contract for the
Pushkin exhibition in October with the Soviet Culture Ministry.
   Argillet, a publisher of Dali's works, said the 84-year-old
artist is in poor health in Spain and couldn't attend the Moscow
showing, but would be pleased it was taking place.
   Some Soviets said they regretted that the exhibition was limited
to Dali's etchings and drawings from the 1960s and did not include
his better-known and more colorful paintings.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0158 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1541EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Majorette-Walkout     04-15 0364</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Majorette-Walkout,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Students Walk Out When Squad Drops Black Majorette</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MACCLENNY, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   High school administrators have promised
to review the way drum majorettes are chosen after 25 to 30
students staged a walkout when the squad's first and only black
member was dropped.
   The students chanted ``We want Mazy'' as they left classes at
Baker County High School for about an hour Thursday in the school
and were joined at a schoolyard fence by 10 to 15 parents.
   Mazy Ruise, 15, a sophomore, has been a majorette for the past
two years, but did not make the squad for the 1988-89 school year.
She is the 10-member squad's first and only black member.
   ``All of the kids in the band felt Mazy was highly qualified to
return to the majorette group,'' said Gail Moore, a parent.
   ``I feel I've been treated unfairly,'' said Miss Ruise, the only
black to try out for the 1988-89 squad. She said she was touched
when she saw that parents and students gathered at the fence to
protest the decision.
   The school's enrollment of 1,000 students is 17 percent black.
   Gail Brown, a guidance counselor who is serving as acting
principal, met with students and parents at the Thursday protest.
   After complaints that Miss Ruise had been unfairly treated, Ms.
Brown agreed to review ``the whole situation concerning Mazy'' and
the school's policies for majorette selection.
   The walkout ``did not totally disrupt the school,'' Ms. Brown
said. Students returned to school after missing just one class
Thursday, and the school day went on normally on Friday, she said.
   Students who tried out for the majorette squad last month did
dance and twirling routines and then were ranked by scores tallied
by four judges, all white. Two of the judges were from dance
studios and two were former majorettes.
   Mazy was ranked 11th of the 14 students who tried out. Ten were
chosen.
   ``I've been twirling since I was 6. ... I'm not bragging, but
I'm better than all of them,'' Miss Ruise said.
   Tajuana Spencer, 16, who participated in the protest, agreed
that Miss Ruise had been treated unfairly. ``They knew she was
good,'' she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
