<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Nigeria     04-15 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Nigeria,0293</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Die in Rioting to Protest Higher Gasoline Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOS, Nigeria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said six people died during a violent
demonstration against increases in gasoline prices, the News Agency
of Nigeria reported Friday.
   Police said they used force to quell a riot that had degenerated
into ``complete lawlessness.''
   Nigerian newspapers had reported Thursday that police shot four
people to death in the northern city of Jos. Authorities closed
half a dozen colleges and universities, including the University of
Lagos, to halt the spread of protests.
   The Plateau state police command said the dead included a police
constable and a retired police inspector, the news agency said.
   ``The command unequivocally believes that it will not allow a
situation where there is a complete breakdown of law and order,
resulting in a state of anarchy,'' according to the police
statement.
   The statement also confirmed that rioters burned down two court
buildings, a metropolitan development board building, police
station, local government secretariat and the state fire office.
   Police blocked rioters from burning down the city's main market,
a bank and divisional police headquarters, the statement said.
   The news agency said businesses had reopened in Jos and life was
returning to normal Friday.
   Gasoline prices were raised 3 percent last weekend by the
military government, which is under pressure from Western creditors
to raise money to meet a $1.5 billion budget deficit.
   Although the price increases appear small, transport companies
subsequently raised bus prices from 50 percent to 100 percent in
some areas.
   Since the oil boom days of the mid-1970s, Nigerians have come to
regard cheap gasoline as a fundamental right. Even with the
increases, gasoline costs about 40 cents a gallon.
</TEXT>
