<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ASNE-Officers     04-15 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-ASNE-Officers,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USA Today Official Named President of Editors Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   John Seigenthaler, editorial director of USA
Today, was elected president of the 1,000-member American Society
of Newspaper Editors on Friday, stepping in for a Wall Street
Journal editor who was unable to take the job because of health
reasons.
   Seigenthaler, who also is editor and publisher of the Nashville
Tennessean, had been ASNE treasurer.
   Edward R. Cony, associate editor of the Wall Street Journal, who
for the past year served as vice president of the ASNE, was elected
to the presidency, but an ASNE statement said he was resigning the
post.
   By tradition, the vice president usually succeeds to the
presidency. But, the statement said, Cony discovered in early March
that he was suffering from Alzheimer's disease, a progressive brain
cell degeneration that leads to senility. There is no cure for the
disease.
   Katherine Fanning, editor of the Christian Science Monitor and
outgoing ASNE president, announced Cony's election and his decision
to resign at a luncheon on the final day of the ASNE's annual
convention. Cony received a standing ovation.
   Cony, who has been a member of ASNE since 1971, previously
served as the group's secretary and treasurer.
   Other new officers are Loren Ghiglione, editor and publisher of
the Southbridge (Mass.) News, vice president; Burl Osborne, editor
and publisher of The Dallas Morning News, secretary; and David
Lawrence, publisher of The Detroit Free Press, treasurer.
</TEXT>
