<DOCNO> AP880415-0168 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1717EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Australia-Military     04-15 0250</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Australia-Military,0258</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Australia Scales Down its Only Overseas Air Base</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By PETER O'LOUGHLIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SYDNEY, Australia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Australia will scale down its only
overseas military base Saturday when it begins withdrawing an air
force fighter squadron from Malaysia.
   The withdrawal is part of a redeployment of Australia's front
line fighter force to air bases in northern Australia, which are
being developed at a cost of $75 million.
   The redeployment is the first step in a new program that will
include a new submarine and missile destroyer fleet, half of which
will be based permanently on its west coast.
   Australian Defense Minister Kim Beazley will officiate at
ceremonies at Butterworth air base in Malaysia marking the return
to Australia of the French-designed Mirage fighters.
   Australia is playing down the withdrawal of the fighters,
arguing that its new northern Australia-based U.S. built FA-18
Hornet fighters will be only two hours' flying time from Malaysian
airspace in the event of emergency.
   The FA-18s are to be rotated through Butterworth 16 times a year
under a new agreement with the Malaysian govenrment.
   They will fly from Tindal, a new base south of Darwin in
Australia's Northern Territory.
   Beazley has said Australia also will rotate U.S.-built F-111
strike aircraft through Butterworth, built on Malaysia's west coast
as a Royal Air Force base in 1941, a year before Pearl Harbor.
   It was destroyed by the Japanese in World War II, rebuilt and
later expanded by Australia with a 6,000-foot runway in 1958.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
