<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Czechoslovakia     04-15 0365</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Czechoslovakia,0376</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Critics Want Human Rights Attached to Creation of `Zone of Trust'</HEAD>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Czechoslovak human rights group has
called on its government to release all political prisoners and
allow free travel abroad before a government-proposed ``zone of
trust'' is created in central Europe.
   ``If trust is not to remain a mere propagandistic slogan,
certain basic preconditions must be fulfilled for it to emerge,''
said the appeal from the Charter 77 group. A text was released
Friday through the London-based Palach Press newsletter.
   The document was signed by three Charter 77 spokesmen and issued
in Prague on April 11. It welcomed a Czechoslovak government
proposal to set up a ``zone of trust and good neighborly relations
along the dividing lines of the Warsaw Pact and NATO countries'' in
central Europe.
   Czechoslovak Communist Party leader Milos Jakes made the
proposal in February, but no details have been made public.
   Prague officials said the buffer zone, to include such countries
as West and East Germany, Czechoslovakia and Austria, would cover
cultural, military, ecological and human relations issues.
   The Charter 77 appeal calls on the Czechoslovak government to
prove its ``trustworthiness and credibility by respecting the
fundamental rights and liberties of its citizens while submitting
itself to open and public scrutiny.''
   A copy was sent to Jakes and to the Helsinki follow-up
Conference on Security and Cooperation in Europe in Vienna,
   As reported by Palach Press, signatories Milos Hajek, Stanislav
Devaty and Bohumir Janat specifically demanded the immediate
release of Jiri Wolf, who is serving a six-year sentence for
publishing information on conditions in Czechoslovak prisons. He
was jailed in 1983.
   They also demanded that priest Stefan Javorsky, sentenced to
eight months in jail last year for celebrating Mass without
official permission, be set free.
   The appeal also demanded freedom to travel abroad, in particular
to the couuntries included in the proposed trust zone; an end to
discrimination against nonconformist citizens; and a halt to
persecuting human rights groups.
   ``If the government does not take decisive steps in the spirit
of the above-mentioned points, its peace proposal will remain a
mere empty gesture,'' the signatories of the appeal said, according
to Palach Press.
</TEXT>
