<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Brites     04-15 0706</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Brites,0728</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cosmetic surgery is as common as palm trees in
movieland, but one blemished star on the Walk of Fame took 28 years
to fix.
   Mauritz Stiller, the late Swedish director whose main claim to
fame was bringing Greta Garbo to Hollywood, suffered the indignity
of having not just one name misspelled on the famed star-walk, but
both.
   City officials corrected the error Thursday, replacing a star
plaque reading Maurice Diller with one honoring Mauritz Stiller.
   In 1960, when the first 1,550 bronze plaques were implanted in
the sidewalks of Hollywood's shopping and theater district to
create the hallowed Walk of Fame, someone taking the name over the
telephone misheard the caller, said Bill Welsh, president of the
Hollywood Chamber of Commerce.
   ``Well, we got 1,549 stars out of 1,550 correct,'' Welsh said.
``I just hope our Swedish friends will forgive us for taking so
long to correct the error.''
   The local Swedish consulate had asked Hollywood to correct the
misspelling because King Carl XVI Gustav and Queen Silvia, who are
touring the United States, will be visiting California soon, said
spokesman Claes Jernaeus.
   Stiller was lured to Hollywood in 1925 by MGM's Louis B. Mayer,
and came only on condition that he could bring Miss Garbo. She went
on to become a star, but Stiller contracted pleurisy and returned
to Sweden, where he died in 1928.
   He directed such films as ``Sir Arne's Treasure'' and ``The
Atonement of Gosta Berling,'' which starred Miss Garbo.
   Attending the ceremonies were Swedish notables Lasse Hallstrom,
the Oscar-nominated director of ``My Life As A Dog,'' and actress
Signe Hasso. Miss Garbo had been invited to attend, but ``she's
very private, as you know. And she's over 80 now,'' said Ake
Sandler, a local Swedish-born professor.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>INAVALE, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   It looks like someone drove a car into a
tree and left it there, but nature is responsible for a hybrid 1928
Ford Coupe and a Chinese elm tree in Ermal and James Wilson's field.
   Mrs. Wilson, of Inavale, bought the used Ford in 1944 for $125.
She was working as a waitress for $4 a week. She married Wilson in
1945 and three years later he gave her a 1948 Studebaker. That's
when the Ford got the shaft.
   ``We built a new garage for the Studebaker to go in and I drove
it (the Ford) out there (in the field),'' she said. ``It wasn't
long before a tree grew up in the middle of it. The transmission is
in the tree.
   ``The roof was still on it but of course the tree pushed it
off,'' Mrs. Wilson said. Nature's hold was final when another tree
grew behind the car's rear axle.
   ``It was in perfect shape when I parked it there,'' she said.
``If I had any brains, as they say now, I should have parked it in
the garage and parked the new Studebaker outside.''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>CLARK, Wyo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Greta knocks on the back door with her horns
and plays with the family dogs, but she isn't a billy goat. She's a
bison fast closing in on 700 pounds who likes being petted, fed and
talked to.
   ``She thinks she's a person,'' said Martin Kimmet, a rancher who
raises buffalo for slaughter. ``She still wants to come in the
house every time she sees the door opened.''
   Greta entered the Kimmet household several years ago after her
mother deserted the calf shortly after birth.
   ``The difficult labor apparently caused her to abandon her
calf,'' Kimmet said. ``After we had given her about two hours to
`mother up,' we brought her into our house.''
   At first Greta was no trouble. Weighing only about 50 pounds,
she was the size of a large dog. The family later blocked off a
section of the house for her because she woke earlier than the
family and demanded to be fed. She eventually was moved out to the
yard, where the family continues to treat her like a pet.
   Kimmet is not yet sure of Greta's future, although he is
thinking of using her for public relations. However, he has ruled
out one possibility:
   ``We wouldn't want to eat this one,'' said Kimmet.
</TEXT>
