<1ST_LINE>u p AM-House-Delegates     04-15 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-House-Delegates,520</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dukakis Lengthens Delegate Lead With `Super Delegates' Help</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Political Rdp Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD L. VERNACI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis has expanded his delegate lead
to 112 over Jesse Jackson with the help of support from members of
Congress elected as delegates to the Democratic National Convention.
   Most of the 237 senators and representatives picked so far to
have votes at the convention have not announced their choices.
However, Dukakis was the early leader Friday in the battle for
support from congressional ``super delegates.''
   In Congress so far:
   _Twenty-six of the House Democrats nominated to be delegates are
backing the Massachusetts governor, while 15 are supporting
Jackson, according to a survey by The Associated Press. Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. of Tennessee has 12 in his corner and Illinois Sen. Paul
Simon, who has suspended active campaigning, has 10.
   _Nine of the 32 senators picked so far as delegates have
endorsed Dukakis. Gore has 5 senator-delegates and Simon 2,
including themselves. Jackson has none.
   Dukakis, whose campaign strategy is pegged on putting at least
250 delegates between himself and second-place Jackson in the next
few weeks, already has gained 100 toward that goal during the past
week.
   On Wednesday, he won the endorsement of Puerto Rico's governor,
who delivered himself and 51 other previously uncommitted delegates
as a bloc.
   For sheer size, the congressional caucuses rank behind only
California and New York in terms of the number of delegates being
sent to the convention. The two houses next week complete the
selection of 251 senators and representatives as delegates.
   In both houses, the delegate nominations are supervised by the
Democratic leadership, and next week's party caucuses are expected
to be little more than ceremonial. But the delegates' choices are
still generally unknown.
   Overall, Dukakis has 842.15 delegates, some 100 of whom are
``super delegates,'' the party leaders and politicians _ including
members of Congress _ who are being sent as delegates to the
convention because of offices they hold or held. In all, 644 of
these delegates, who are free to make or dissolve their commitments
to presidential candidates as they see fit, are to attend the
convention.
   Dukakis, Gore and Simon are super delegates, as is Missouri Rep.
Richard Gephardt, who dropped out of the presidental race last
month.
   The remaining 85 percent of the delegates to the convention,
3,518, are getting there through the primaries or caucuses, in
which they are required to pledge themselves to support a
presidential candidate or declare that they are uncommitted.
   Although, Dukakis' delegate lead is becoming formidable, his
total represents just 40 percent of the 2,082 delegates needed to
win the party's presidential nomination.
   Jackson, whose landslide victory in Michigan on March 26
momentarily pushed him into the lead in delegates, now has 730.1
delegates in the AP count. That includes 45 super delegates.
   Gore has 411.55 delegates, including 41 super delegates, and
Simon has 183.5 delegates overall, including 28.5 super delegates.
   More than 600 delegates are uncommitted, including about 400
from the ranks of the party's political professionals.
</TEXT>
