<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2027EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-SharpevilleSix     04-15 0414</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Sharpeville Six,0424</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lawyers Request Reopening Trial For Six Blacks On Death Row</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PRETORIA, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers on Friday filed an
application seeking to reopen the trial of six blacks who were
sentenced to hang in a case that drew worldwide protests.
   The court action came a day after six other blacks were hung at
Pretoria Central Prison, raising to 50 the number of executions in
South Africa this year.
   The application on behalf of the so-called Sharpeville Six was
filed in Pretoria Supreme Court. It is not known how soon a
decision on the request will be made.
   The five men and one women were convicted of complicity in the
mob killing of a black town councilor during anti-apartheid riots
that broke out in Sharpeville, south of Johannesburg, in September
1984. The violence touched off two years of nationwide unrest.
   The six were scheduled to die on March 18, but a stay of
execution was granted to allow time for defense lawyers to request
the case be reopened.
   The stay was decreed because of evidence that a state witness
committed perjury during the original trial.
   President P.W. Botha had previously rejected international
appeals to grant clemency to the six, saying he did not want to
interfere in the judicial process.
   The six were not accused of contributing physically to the death
of Sharpeville councilor Kuzwayo Dhlamini. They were convicted
under the doctrine of ``common purpose,'' which held them
responsible because they were part of the mob that killed the man.
   The government has argued that the Sharpville Six are being
falsely portrayed abroad as innocent victims of an unjust law.
Authorities say evidence in the trial showed that each played an
active part in the killing, through such alleged actions as making
firebombs to burn Dhlamini's house or slapping a woman who pleaded
for the councilor's life.
   The six men hung Thursday included two blacks in their 20s
described by authorities as ``comrades,'' a term commonly used to
describe anti-apartheid militants. They were convicted of killing
two other black men by setting fire to oil-soaked tires placed
around the victims' necks.
   One of the executed men was convicted of killing a mixed-race
man, while the other three were hung for murdering elderly whites.
   By law and custom, apartheid establishes a racially segregated
society in which the 26 million blacks have no vote in national
affairs. The 5 million whites control the economy and maintain
separate districts, schools and health services.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
