<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Egypt-Tanks     04-15 0213</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Egypt-Tanks,200</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pentagon Asks Congressional Approval For $2 Billion Egypt Tank
Deal</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Pentagon formally requested congressional
approval Friday for a $2 billion co-production deal that would
allow Egypt to build M-1A1 Abrams tanks.
   The arms transaction, disclosed several months ago by
administration officials, calls for the sale of 555 M-1A1 tanks. As
many as 540 of them could be built on a new assembly line to be
constructed in Egypt.
   Congress will now have 30 days to veto the deal should it wish
to do so.
   The Pentagon, in notifying Congress it had approved the
transaction, argued Egypt ``needs an advanced tank to ensure the
stability of the existing regional military balance, especially
vis-a-vis Libya.''
   ``The sale of this equipment and support will not adversely
affect the basic military balance in the region,'' the Pentagon
said.
   ``This sale will contribute to the foreign policy and national
security of the United States by helping to improve the security of
a friendly country which has been and continues to be an important
force for stability and peace in the Middle East.''
   The Pentagon said the U.S. Army would be responsible for
overseeing the transaction and that the prime contractor would be
the General Dynamics Land Services Corp. of Warren, Mich.
</TEXT>
