<1ST_LINE>r w AM-JournalistExhibit     04-15 0237</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Journalist Exhibit,230</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gannett to Finance Library of Congress Exhibit on U.S. Journalists</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Library of Congress will open a major
exhibition in April 1990 on American journalists and their role in
society, featuring historic news stories, letters, diaries, movies
and political cartoons from the library's collections.
   The exhibition, titled ``The American Journalist,'' will be
co-sponsored by the American Society of Newspaper Editors and
financed by a $250,000 grant from the Gannett Foundation of
Rochester, N.Y. The show will tour several other cities after it
leaves the Library of Congress.
   ``The exhibition will offer a critical look at news gatherers
and their place in American society and thought, including their
characterization in fiction and art,'' said Loren Ghiglione,
publisher and editor of the Southbridge (Mass.) News, who will be
guest curator of the show.
   Ghiglione is the new ASNE vice president and a fellow at the
foundation's Gannett Center for Media Studies at Columbia
University.
   ``We see this exhibit as an instructive way to examine and
highlight the sometimes troubled relationship between journalists
and the institutions they cover, as well as their audiences,'' said
Eugene C. Dorsey, president of the Gannett Foundation.
   The Library of Congress, largest in the world, has 86 million
items in its collections. Among them are some of the first
newspapers printed in the United States as well as copies of the
1,200 current U.S. daily and weekly newspapers.
</TEXT>
