<1ST_LINE>r a AM-TVSeason     04-15 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-TV Season,0692</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>End of Season Ratings: Bad News and Confusion for Networks</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHRYN BAKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Television Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   CBS says it came in second in the television
ratings for the season according to the ratings company AGB,
although Nielsen results used by all three networks have CBS
finishing third for the first time ever.
   No matter whose figures are used, the end of season ratings
released by CBS Friday show that viewers are no longer enchanted by
its new shows and are turning instead to VCRs, cable and
independent stations, and perhaps even books, conversation or
exercise.
   CBS apparently suffered most. Except for ``Beauty and the
Beast,'' it could count no new shows as successes, even though
``Frank's Place,'' ``Wiseguy'' and ``Tour of Duty'' received
critical praise.
   ``We are not, as some people would expect, going to fall on our
swords in defeat,'' said David Poltrack, CBS vice president for
marketing, who briefed reporters on the end-of-season results. ``We
are not defeatists.''
   The networks' prime-time season doesn't officially end until
Sunday, but the last week's results aren't expected to change the
picture.
   ABC Entertainment President Brandon Stoddard is to have a
session with reporters Monday, and NBC, which will win its third
season in a row, is holding an end-of-season briefing Tuesday.
   CBS held its briefing early perhaps because it is already
conceding it will come in third for the first time in the network's
history _ according to the A.C. Nielsen Co., the ratings service of
record since the 1950s.
   Last year, CBS signed up with Nielsen competitor AGB Media
Research, a British company. Although AGB numbers are not bought by
the other networks, nor are they used in the real business of
television ratings _ negotiating advertising rates _ CBS uses AGB
to back its contention that Nielsen's new people-meter audience
measurement system is inaccurate.
   Poltrack estimates that the networks will lose a combined $50
million in advertising revenues because of the lower numbers
produced by people meters.
   NBC and ABC agree that Nielsen's new system is not accurate
enough, but they haven't been hurt as much as CBS. In fact, ABC has
prospered.
   Poltrack wouldn't say how much of the $50 million loss was CBS'.
   According to Nielsen, the network averages after 29 weeks of the
30-week season were: NBC 16.1, ABC 13.7 and CBS 13.5. The rating is
a percentage of an estimated 88.6 million U.S. homes equipped with
television.
   CBS said AGB figures gave NBC 16.2, CBS 13.9 and ABC 13.2.
Poltrack conceded that CBS has little hope of getting advertisers
and the other networks to switch to AGB in lieu of Nielsen.
   Despite the ratings system squabble, a general erosion in
network audiences is uncontested, Poltrack said, although the
extent of it is unknown.
   According to Nielsen, the three-network average rating dropped 9
percent from 1986-87 to 1987-88. The previous year there was a 3
percent drop.
   Poltrack estimates that roughly half of the percentage drop is
real and half is a function of the people meter, a more complex
measurement device that requires particiants to actively punch in
and punch out when they watch television. The old system was a
hands-off attachment on the set.
   Historically, networks have lost audiences to increasing cable
availability, but this season the numbers show all cable channels
combined gaining only 1.2 percent in the ratings.
   The biggest drop in network audiences was in the realm of
theatrical movies, indicating increased use of cable or
videocassettes. However, audiences are also rejecting new network
programming.
   The highest-rated new show of the season was NBC's ``A Different
World,'' which, with an average rating of 25.1, is the only new
show to qualify as a bona fide hit. But it has never been tested
away from its timeslot that follows the No. 1-rated ``The Cosby
Show,'' of which it is a spinoff.
   Otherwise, new shows performed miserably. Of the 47 this season,
only eight exceeded the a 14.4 rating, the average for all network
prime-time programming.
</TEXT>
