<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Libya-Bombing     04-15 0557</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Libya-Bombing,0575</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dignitaries Shown Gadhafi's House on Anniversary of U.S. Bombing</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FRANCES D'EMILIO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TRIPOLI, Libya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stepping over splintered glass and twisted
metal, Libyan officials led foreign visitors through Col. Moammar
Gadhafi's former home Friday to mark the second anniversary of the
U.S. bombing of Tripoli.
   The tour began at 2 a.m., the time that F-111 fighter bombers
attacked the Libyan capital and the coastal city of Benghazi on
April 15, 1986.
   President Reagan said he ordered the raid in retaliation for
alleged Libyan involvement in the bombing of a West German
nightclub which left two U.S. soldiers and a Turkish woman dead.
   Two bomb explosions in the last two days _ one near Madrid and
one in Naples, Italy, which killed a U.S. Navy woman _ may have
been linked to the anniversary.
   Libyan officials promised Gadhafi would appear early Friday at
the house, which was hit in the U.S. raid. But after an hour, the
visitors were escorted back from the fortified barracks compound on
the outskirts of the city to their hotel downtown.
   No explanation was given for Gadhafi's absence.
   Most of the 40-odd visitors were delegates to a three-day
conference on terrorism that ended Friday. The group included
people from Italy, Greece, Cyprus, Syria, Canada, Tunisia and
Spain. Journalists also were invited on the tour.
   Some of the convention delegates signed a green guest book in
the rubble-strewn entrance hall of the two-story tile-decorated
structure. The Libyans have turned the ruins into a memorial.
   The walls of Gadhafi's two master bedrooms are covered with
chalk graffiti, which guides said were the work of students
denouncing Reagan and British Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher.
U.S. bombers used in the raid took off from a British base.
   Gadhafi, addressing the convention delegates on Wednesday night,
spoke about the 1986 raid that Libyans said killed 37 people,
including his adopted baby daughter.
   ``Even if they were able to kill me on that day _ the day of the
U.S.-NATO barbarous aggression _ even if they were able to do that
in the future, that does not mean that they have succeeded in
accomplishing what they wanted,'' Gadhafi was quoted as saying in a
translation of his speech from Arabic by the official Libyan news
agency JANA.
   ``I am carrying the banner of peace in the Mediterranean and
would like peace for my country as much as for the other countries
of the world,'' JANA quoted him as telling the delegates.
   ``But at one time I thought of leaving this country to form an
internationalist secret army to effectively terrorize the
imperialists who savagely killed my children in Tripoli and
Benghazi.''
   Friday, the Moslem holy day, found Tripoli quiet. Two soldiers
with assault rifles guarded one of the entrances to Gadhafi's
compound, where he lives and works.
   In Italy, a man claiming to speak for the Organization of Jihad
Brigades claimed that the bombing of a U.S. military club Thursday
was in retaliation for the U.S. raid on Libya. The bombing in
Naples killed an American servicewoman and four Italian civilians.
   In Madrid, the national news agency EFE cited an unidentified
Defense Ministry source as saying a bombing at a U.S. Air Force
radio relay station east of the capital Friday could be linked to
the Tripoli anniversary. No injuries were reported.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
