<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Gore-Loans     04-15 0288</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gore-Loans,290</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gore Increases Campaign Debt To $1.6 Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NASHVILLE, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr. has taken
out $100,000 in new loans from banks in his home state, plunging
his campaign for the Democratic presidential nomination $1.6
million into debt.
   Gore was able to obtain the loans even though his prospects for
winning his party's nomination appear to be dimming.
   Polls indicate that his support in next Tuesday's New York
primary, and the contest a week later in Pennsylvania, is mired in
the single digits. He has not won an event since finishing first in
six of the 21 Super Tuesday contests on March 8.
   Gore has spent at least $700,000 on New York television
advertising. Of his two rivals, Jesse Jackson has purchased
$550,000 worth of ads and Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis
reportedly will spend as much as $1.5 million.
   Campaign officials said the most recent loans, for $50,000 each,
were from the Volunteer State Bank of Portland, Tenn., on April 11
and the Bank of Putnam County in Cookeville, Tenn., the following
day.
   Campaign manager Fred Martin said the campaign has no plans to
take out any more loans before the New York primary, but he would
not rule out additional loans after that.
   The campaign had acknowledged a $50,000 loan from Union Planters
Bank in Memphis, Tenn., on April 5.
   One problem Gore might face in repaying the loans is that the
federal matching funds he has been receiving may soon be dwindling.
   Federal assistance to campaigns is diminished if a candidate
fails to receive 10 percent of the vote in two successive primaries
_ which Gore has already done _ and then fails to achieve 20
percent support thereafter.
</TEXT>
