<HEAD>Jewish Newspaper Says ``Stop Jackson''</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Jewish Press, New York City's largest
circulation Jewish weekly, endorsed Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr.
on Friday, calling on all Jews to vote in Tuesday's New York
Democratic presidential primary as ``the only way to stop (Jesse)
Jackson.''
   The newspaper also praised New York City Mayor Edward Koch who
has said Jews would have to be crazy to vote for Jackson.
   ``In the face of much opposition, he sticks to his guns
maintaining that the election of Jesse Jackson would be a tragedy
for American Jewry as well as for Israel, and for all of America,''
the 175,000-circulation newspaper said of Koch.
   In addition to its endorsement of Gore, the newspaper's lead
story ran the headline ``Campaign to Stop Jackson'' and outlined
the efforts of Jewish leaders to do just that.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Two Northern Virginians Back North for Senate Campaign</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REAT FALLS, Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Virginia men have begun a campaign
trying to draft Oliver North to run for the U.S. Senate.
   Jamey R. Wheeler and David L. Sobba of Arlington said they would
have a ``Draft North'' rally at the Iwo Jima Memorial next
Wednesday and have sent out letters urging a North candidacy for
the seat being vacated by Republican Sen. Paul Trible.
   Their letter, addressed to ``Dear Friend of Oliver North,''
accuses liberals of ``trying to put Ollie North in jail for
standing up for our freedom. That's why we need to show Col. North
that he has friends not only in the great Commonwealth of Virginia,
but all across America.''
   ``I think Oliver North would be the best and strongest candidate
with the right kind of charisma to beat someone like a Chuck
Robb,'' said Wheeler, referring to former Gov. Charles Robb, who is
seeking the Democratic nomination for the seat.
   But Alexandria GOP chief Jane Ring expressed skepticism about
the campaign. ``I don't think that's going to gather a lot of
steam,'' she said.
   Wheeler said he had not contacted North about the draft movement
and does not plan to. ``We're trying to help him make his
decision,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>Florida Senator Endorses Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sen. Bob Graham of Florida has endorsed
Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis' bid for the Democratic
presidential nomination, praising the candidate's experience and
capabilities.
   ``I am endorsing Mike Dukakis because I know him. ... I've known
him as governor and as senator ... and he has my complete
confidence,'' said Graham, who earlier served two terms as governor.
   ``Governor Dukakis is the kind of proven problem solver America
needs, and his outstanding record as chief executive of
Massachusetts shows what he can do as chief executive of the United
States,'' Graham, who hopes to attend the Democratic National
Convention in July, said Thursday.
