<1ST_LINE>r w AM-SoilVolunteers     04-15 0227</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Soil Volunteers,220</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>USDA Looking for Volunteers to Aid Conservation Efforts</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department's conservation
chief said Friday that more volunteers are needed to help carry out
a massive program aimed at protecting the nation's soil and water
resources.
   Last year some 2,200 volunteers provided more than $1 million
worth of assistance to agency field offices, said Wilson Scaling,
head of the Soil Conservation Service.
   This ``Earth Team,'' he said, put in more than 132,000 hours in
helping with tree planting, inventorying wetlands, conservation
education, telephoning land owners to inform them of the
Conservation Reserve Program and providing clerical and other
office help.
   Many of the volunteers have expertise in geology, biology,
botony, surveying, mapping, and soil and erodibility
determinations, Scaling said.
   Under the 1985 farm law, farmers with highly erodible cropland
must have a conservation plan approved by Dec. 31, 1989, and have
it implemented by Dec. 31, 1994, or loss USDA benefits such as
price support loans, payments and insurance.
   Scaling said the agency estimates that 800,000 conservation
plans still need to be developed nationwide.
   Anyone interested in volunteering for the Earth Team, he said,
can call 1-800-THE SOIL for the location of the local SCS office.
Volunteers receive coverage for injury claims, are compensated for
travel expenses, and have their contributions made part of a
permanent work record, Scaling said.
</TEXT>
