<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2107EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-AlternativeFuels     04-15 0577</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Alternative Fuels,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Senate Bill Encourages Alternative Fuels Such as Coal, Gas, Grain</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID GOELLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Senate on Friday passed legislation
designed to foster use of alternative motor fuels in order to
reduce U.S. dependency on foreign petroleum and tap vast U.S.
supplies of coal, natural gas and grain.
   The bill passed on a voice vote over warnings by Republicans on
the Environment Committee that it could lead to increased emissions
of the ``greenhouse'' gases that some scientists say are
overheating the Earth's atmosphere.
   The Senate action all but ensures that Congress will enact
alternative fuels legislation in 1988. A similar proposal was
passed overwhelmingly by the House earlier this year. The bills'
differences will have to be resolved by negotiators from both
chambers.
   Both proposals are geared toward encouraging the automobile
industry to mass-produce vehicles that can operate on fuels such as
methanol, ethanol and compressed natural gas.
   Methanol, which powers Indianapolis 500-type race cars at 200
miles an hour, can be manufactured from coal or natural gas.
Ethanol is made from grains like corn. The legislation has broad
support from coal and agricultural state lawmakers.
   The proposals would break an impasse that now prevents any
widespread switchover from gasoline to alternative fuels, according
to Sen. John Danforth, R-Mo., a principal sponsor along with Sen.
Jay Rockefeller, D-W.Va.
   ``Automakers are unwilling to produce (alternative fuel) cars
for which there is no current demand,'' Danforth said. ``Consumers
are unwilling to purchase cars for which there is no readily
available fuel supply, and service stations are unwilling to
provide fuel for cars that are not on the road.''
   Rockefeller said that besides lessening the growing U.S. need
for imported oil, a conversion of just 10 percent of the U.S.
vehicle fleet to coal-based methanol would mean jobs for 20,000
miners in the depressed coal industry.
   The sponsors said automakers would be encouraged to mass-produce
vehicles using alternative fuels because the legislation would make
it easier to meet the federal requirement that their fleets have an
average fuel economy of at least 26 miles per gallon.
   Under the bill's formula, a 25 mpg vehicle that uses a blend of
85 percent methanol and 15 percent gasoline would get a fuel
economy rating of 165 mpg, according to Danforth. A 25 mpg vehicle
using a 50-50 blend would be rated at 40 mpg, he said.
   The higher credits for alternative fuels would begin with the
vehicle 1993 model year.
   Danforth and Rockefeller's argument that methanol and ethanol
would cause fewer environmental and health problems than gasoline
was disputed by Environment Committee members Robert Stafford,
R-Vt., and John Chafee, R-R.I.
   Stafford said coal-derived methanol would double emissions of
carbon dioxide, a major contributor to the greenhouse effect, and
bring a tenfold increase in tailpipe emissions of formaldehyde, a
cancer-causing chemical.
   He urged the Senate to proceed cautiously because many
scientists warn that the production of greenhouse gases is
overloading the atmosphere, trapping heat around the Earth and
threatening major climate changes.
   ``Once we commit to a program like this, it will be too late,''
said Stafford, who unsuccessfully tried to add amendments to
require alternative vehicles to meet the same emissions standards
as gasoline vehicles.
   Chafee succeeded in adding language putting the Senate on record
as saying that coal-based methanol would boost carbon dioxide
levels, contribute to global overheating and should not be used
until emissions controls are developed to control carbon dioxide.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0188 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2108EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PiedmontLanding     04-15 0568</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Piedmont Landing,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Piedmont Starts Repairs After NTSB Completes First Part of Probe</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KELLY P. KISSEL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHARLESTON, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Piedmont airlines maintenance crews
Friday began making temporary repairs to a crippled jetliner,
replacing an engine that exploded in midair and patching holes that
ripped through both sides of the cabin.
   The Fokker F-28 4000, a Dutch-made jet carrying 56 passengers
and a crew of four, was forced to land at Charleston on Thursday
after it lost cabin pressure and plunged partway toward the ground
as passengers screamed and fainted.
   After the workers replace the engine and cover the holes, the
plane is to be flown Saturday to a Piedmont maintenance facility at
Greensboro, N.C., for further study and repair, said Jeff Bubar,
manager of Yeager Airport.
   The engine mounted on the right side of the fuselage exploded
Thursday morning as the plane was at 31,000 feet en route from
Charlotte, N.C., to Columbus, Ohio. It was a half-hour out of
Columbus, and about 40 miles south of Charleston, when the
explosion occurred.
   A turbine blade and other engine parts cut through the plane's
right rear bathroom and a flight attendant work area. No one was
hit by the debris, but two flight attendants suffered bumps and
bruises as the plane plunged.
   The explosion was the first significant trouble reported with
the engines of a Fokker F-28, National Transportation Safety Board
statistics show. Rolls-Royce manufactured the engine that exploded
Thursday.
   Piedmont flies 25 Fokker F-28 4000s, which carry 72 people, and
20 Fokker F-28 1000s, which carry 62. They've used the Fokker
planes for about four years, but the model has been in use
elsewhere for about 20 years.
   The NTSB said it was too early to tell whether safety checks
will be required for the F-28s in Piedmont's fleet.
   ``The damage that took place is very apparent,'' said Dennis
Jones, who handled the NTSB's initial investigation of the
incident. ``What we have is engine failure ... and the side of the
airplane was breached.
   ``There was only limited work we could to there (in
Charleston),'' he said from his Washington, D.C., office. ``Our
work doesn't really begin until we can get the engine and the plane
elsewhere.''
   Jones said that despite the relatively safe history of the
Fokker model, the investigation would be needed to check whether
the problem could be found in other Fokker planes.
   ``Right now, were going to look at that particular aircraft and
that model of aircraft,'' Jones said. ``During the course of the
investigation, that will all be looked at, but we can't make that
determination now.
   ``We want to look at the problem it poses for the future. The
NTSB, in general, is set up to investigate accidents and prevent
similar occurrences.''
   The NTSB's Office of Safety Programs has only two injury
accidents involving Fokker F-28s in the U.S. since the early 1980s,
one when there was a minor collision on an airport taxiway and the
other when a person fell off the boarding stairs when a guardrail
gave way, said spokesman Ted Lopatkiewicz.
   Piedmont spokesman Don McGuire contended that with such a
record, grounding the airline's other Fokkers would not be
necessary.
   ``We'll take a judicious approach to what the next step will
be,'' McGuire said.
   The airline, based in Winston-Salem, N.C., owns 25 Fokker F-28
4000 planes and 20 of the F-28 1,000 series.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
