<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2109EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-WritersStrike     04-15 0519</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Writers Strike,0531</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Smothers Brothers Producer Lauds Exemption; 3-D `Moonlighting'
Scrapped</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The producer of the ``New Smothers Brothers
Comedy Hour'' said Friday that approval of an independent contract
with striking scriptwriters came in the nick of time for the show
and its stars.
   ``We made the point that it would be financially and,
careerwise, disastrous for Tom and Dick'' if the show ended,
producer Ken Kragen said in a telephone interview.
   The Writers Guild of America, whose members are concluding the
fifth week of their strike against producers and studios, voted
Thursday to reject independent contracts that would have allowed
work to resume at selected companies, with two exceptions: the
Smothers' show and Ivan Reitman Productions, which has produced
such movies as ``Ghostbusters'' and ``Animal House.''
   Guild leaders had recommended against allowing the separate
contracts because ``it could lead to divisiveness and destruction
of morale among members,'' said Cheryl Rhoden, a WGA spokeswoman.
She added, however, that the exceptions were granted because of
unspecified legal considerations and because negotiations with the
two producers ``were more advanced.''
   While the contract agreement with the 9,000-member union forbids
discussion of terms, Kragen said he believed the Smothers' support
of the strike on their show, as well as their reputation among
writers, won the day.
   ``There are a lot of writers who got their start in the business
with the Smothers, and went on to win Emmys. And now some of them
are on the Writers Guild board of directors,'' said Kragen.
   He also said the three union-written scripts for the show, which
ran out with Wednesday night's 8 p.m. broadcast on CBS-TV, were
kept untainted by non-union revisions.
   ``They laid out guidelines for us. We strained mightily, but we
stayed within those guidelines, and I think that impressed them,''
Kragen said.
   Also Friday, ABC-TV made official what ``Moonlighting'' producer
Glenn Caron announced four weeks ago: The much-publicized 3-D
version of the popular program for the May ratings sweeps period
has been scrubbed.
   ``After exhausting all of our options, we have concluded that to
go forward without an original script would not be in the best
interests of `Moonlighting,' our viewers or Coca-Cola,'' a promoter
of the episode, Ted Harbert, ABC's vice president for prime-time
entertainment, said in New York.
   Meanwhile, federal mediator Leonard Farrell scheduled a meeting
Monday morning between the WGA and representatives from The
Alliance of Motion Picture and Television Producers.
   Writers on both coasts went on strike March 7. The walkout
shortened the season for some prime-time TV shows and stalled the
start of a few new series. There have been no formal negotiations
since mediated talks broke off March 10.
   Producers spokesman Herb Steinberg said he had little hope for
the Monday session, adding that alliance negotiators will attend
because the law requires them to. He declined comment on the
contract waiver deals.
   Disputed issues include how much writers are paid for foreign
broadcasts of their material and for reruns on domestic television.
How much creative input they have over their work is also an issue.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
