<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Afghanistan     04-15 0551</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghanistan,0563</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>No Accord in Afghanistan Day After Agreement</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SCHEHEREZADE FARAMARZI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet withdrawal agreement
brought no accord to Afghanistan on Friday: President Najib asked
the guerrillas to join a coalition government and they demanded he
be tried by a Moslem religious court.
   In Moscow, the official news agency Tass accused the United
States of trying to ruin the agreement by continuing to supply arms
to the Moslem insurgents. ``Washington is confirming its policy of
neoglobalism, a course of export of counter-revolution,'' it said.
   The guerrillas were not invited to the Geneva negotiations and
have said they will continue fighting.
   Najib, who uses only one name, also sent a message to President
Reagan thanking him for his efforts leading to the agreement signed
Thursday, under which the Red Army will begin May 15 to withdraw
the 115,000 soldiers in Afghanistan.
   In a statement broadcast by by Kabul radio, Najib invited the
guerrillas to accept his policy of national reconcilittion. ``We
are prepared to cooperate with those who are still fighting this
honorable policy,'' he said.
   ``We stress our willingness to meet the leaders of the
opposition in order to reach a decision on peace, for the happiness
of afflicted people ... for the future of the country's children.
We are waiting for the (naming) of your candidates for the National
Assembly and the Senate.''
   Elections for the Parliament ended Thursday. The guerrillas, who
have been fighting since a Communist coup in April 1978, were
offered seats but dismissed the election as a farce.
   Najib said 1.5 million people voted, showing their ``confidence,
needs and views.'' About 5 million Afghans _ one-third of the
population _ have left the country since Soviet soldiers arrived in
December 1979.
   ``Another step has been taken toward ending war and
brother-killing ... deepening political dialogue, the expansion of
democracy, the establishment of a coalition government with the
participation of all forces which represent the Afghan society,''
Najib declared.
   Gulbaddin Hekmatyar, chairman of the seven-party guerrilla
alliance based in Peshawar, a border city in Pakistan, said Najib
and all members of the ruling Communist Party must be tried in
absentia by religious courts.
   He said Soviet soldiers held by the guerrillas would be
exchanged for Afghan army soldiers, and ``all those POWs will be
kept until the Najib regime is toppled and is replaced by an
Islamic government so all those criminals who flee with the Red
Army could be brought back ... for trial'' in exchange for the
prisoners.
   ``In my view, all members of the Central Committee ... including
Najib the puppet must be tried in absentia ... so that after the
withdrawal of the Russian forces such criminals be dealt with in
accordance with Islamic laws, and those who have been misled and
played off against their nation by these criminals be pardoned,''
Hekmatyar said.
   The insurgents have said they will not share power with
Communists in a future government, but had not called for trials.
They have predicted that Najib would follow the Soviet soldiers to
Moscow.
   Guerrilla leaders have not said how many Soviet prisoners they
have, but last month Hekmatyar's Hezb-i-Islami party said an
agreement had been reached to exchange a Soviet soldier for 25
guerrilla prisoners. The exchange has not occurred.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
