<DOCNO> AP880415-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1806EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u w AM-SpeakesProfile     04-15 0752</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Speakes Profile,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speakes Liked To Boast He Never Lied to Press</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Speakes Resigns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Speakes, the former Mississippi weekly
newspaper editor who rose to be a presidential spokesman and Wall
Street executive, often boasted that he never lied to the press
during his years at the White House.
   But in his new book, Speakes admitted that he fabricated quotes
and attributed them to President Reagan. He resigned Friday as vice
president for communications of Merrill Lynch and Co., saying it
was ``the best course of action'' in the wake of that admission.
   At the White House, Speakes' successor, Marlin Fitzwater, would
say only, ``I'm sorry for him, personally.'' Earlier, he had called
Speakes' practice an outrage, said it reflected on the integrity of
the White House press office. He promised that he would never do
anything similar.
   Speakes, 48, became the chief White House spokesman after
Reagan's press secretary, James Brady, was wounded during an
assassination attempt on the president on March 30, 1981. Brady has
continued to hold the title of press secretary although he has been
unable to return to his duties.
   Fitzwater, who served two years as a deputy to Speakes and then
became press secretary to Vice President George Bush, has been the
chief White House spokesman since Speakes left the post 14 months
ago.
   Speakes grew up in Merigold, Miss., which he describes in his
book, ``Speaking Out,'' as ``Middle America, the heartland, Norman
Rockwell's America.''
   The words are similar to those Reagan has often used in speaking
of his own home town, Dixon, Ill.
   In fact, Speakes said that when he told Reagan of his decision
to leave the White House and accept the offer from Merrill Lynch,
he told him, ``As a kid growing up in a town in Mississippi of 700,
I never expected to meet a president, much less work with one.''
   He said Reagan replied, ``Well, what do you think of a kid
growing up in a small town in Illinois?''
   Speakes attended the University of Mississipi for four years,
but did not receive a degree because he had not completed his
second year of French. While in summer school trying to complete
the work, he accepted an offer to be editor of the Oxford, Miss.,
Eagle, a weekly with a circulation of about 4,000.
   For a young married man whose wife was expecting their first
child, the salary of $85 a week was too good in 1961 to turn down.
Later he held editorial posts at other Mississippi weeklies and
became co-owner of four such newspapers.
   In 1968, he came to Washington as press secretary to
Mississippi's Democratic Sen. James O. Eastland. He was an honorary
pallbearer at Eastland's funeral in 1986 and said in his book,
``Not a day goes by even now that I don't remember him and tell
another Eastland story.''
   Speakes first entered the White House in 1974 as an assistant to
President Nixon's press secretary, Ron Ziegler. Nixon resigned a
few months later and Speakes stayed on to serve as an assistant in
President Ford's press office.
   In the 1976 election, he was press secretary to Ford's running
mate, Sen. Bob Dole of Kansas. After Ford lost to Jimmy Carter,
Speakes went to work for the public relations firm of Hill &
Knowlton in Washington.
   Saying that he found the public relations business ``neither as
interesting nor as much fun as I had expected it to be,'' he went
to work for the Reagan campaign in 1980 and then returned to the
White House as a deputy press secretary.
   After he took over the chief spokesman's job, his relations with
the White House press corps were often contentious, with Speakes
accusing reporters of being out to get the president, and the
reporters accusing Speakes of not being candid.
   Speakes often said his credibility was his most precious
possession and he would not risk losing it by lying to the press.
   In his book, however, he says that at Reagan's 1985 summit
meeting with Mikhail Gorbachev in Geneva he had an aide ``draft
some quotes for the president,'' polished them and then told
reporters that they were what the president said to the Soviet
leader.
   ``In restrospect, it was clearly wrong to take such liberties,''
he said in his book. But, he added, ``I had been able to spruce up
the president's image by taking a bit of liberty with my P.R. man's
license.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
