<1ST_LINE>u a AM-WeatherpageWeather     04-15 0409</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Weatherpage Weather,0420</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Snow Falls in Northeast; Southwest Gets Cold Weather</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Snow fell Friday around the Great Lakes and over parts of New
England, while unseasonably chilly air settled over the desert
Southwest and heavy rain fell in Nevada and from the Plains into
the mid-Mississippi Valley.
   Snow fell across much of Michigan, northern Ohio and western New
York during the afternoon but little accumulated as temperatures
were above freezing. Snow reduced visibility to a quarter-mile at
Youngstown, Ohio.
   Higher elevations of Vermont got 1 to 2 inches of snow in the
morning.
   A winter storm watch was posted overnight for all of Vermont and
parts of northeastern New York state, with up to 6 inches of snow
possible.
   In the Southwest, the temperature at Yuma, Ariz., normally one
of the hottest cities in the nation, was just 56 degrees at noon
with rain. The normal high temperature at Yuma at this time of the
year is 86 degrees. Needles, Calif., at the same time was just 53
degrees.
   More than an inch of rain fell on parts of southern Nevada
during the night and more locally heavy rainfall was possible.
   Rain persisted from northeastern Oklahoma across the Ozarks of
southern Missouri and northern Arkansas to Tennessee. Temperatures
were chilly with an afternoon reading of 44 at Nashville, Tenn.
Rain at Paducah, Ky., mixed with sleet in the morning.
   Elsewhere, a few thunderstorms developed during the morning in
Texas in the Dallas-Fort Worth area and into southeastern Oklahoma.
   An overnight frost and freeze advisory was issued for northern
and central sections of Illinois and a frost advisory was issued in
parts of Indiana.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 p.m. EDT ranged from 31
degrees at Marquette, Mich., to 87 at Fort Stewart and Hinesville,
Ga. The nation's morning low was 17 degrees at Bismarck, N.D.
   For Saturday, scattered showers and thunderstorms were forecast
from Texas across the southern Rockies and Arizona to southern
Idaho. Rain and snow showers were forecast from New England to the
middle Atlantic states and the West Virginia mountains.
   Highs in the 40s or 50s were predicted from the northern and
middle Atlantic Coast states across the upper Ohio Valley to the
Great Lakes region, and in the mountains of northern Arizona; in
the 80s from Florida across the Gulf Coast region to southern
Texas, and in the 60s or 70s across most of the rest of the nation.
</TEXT>
