<1ST_LINE>u w AM-AsianBust 1stLd-Writethru a0754 04-15 0477</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Asian Bust, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0754,480</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Feds Break Up Chinese Drug Ring; Unveil Sting To Supply Rifles To
Libya</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: LEADS with 6 grafs to include undercover aspect of planned
sale, add DEA to agencies involved and include details on gun
suppliers. Picks up 6th graf pvs, bgng: The FBI</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETE YOST</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal investigators said Friday they have
broken up a Chinese heroin-trafficking ring, arresting 11 people in
Hong Kong and nine in the United States while seizing 137 pounds of
heroin worth over $100 million.
   Five of those arrested in New York were charged with conspiring
to supply 1,000 M-16 military rifles to undercover federal agents
and to provide false documents so the rifles could be shipped to
Libya.
   The breakup of the Asian ring was the culmination of a two-year
investigation called Operation Bamboo Dragon that was launched when
federal agents learned that a restaurant owner in the Chinatown
section of Washington was buying stolen firearms and distributing
cocaine.
   The FBI, the Bureau of Alcohol, Tobacco and Firearms, the Drug
Enforcement Administration and the U.S. Customs Service conducted
the investigation and law enforcement officials announced the
arrests at a news conference in Washington.
   Drug-importing Asian criminal gangs ``are moving in to fill the
void'' left by the successful prosecution of Sicilian Mafia members
in the United States, FBI Director William Sessions said in a
statement.
   ``This gang was capable of putting enormous firepower into the
hands of terrorists and drug smugglers,'' Customs commissioner
William von Raab said in a statement. Federal officials said the
ring had supplied 600 handguns, mostly to Chinese gangs.
   The FBI and ATF inserted undercover operatives into the ring,
including a Chinese-speaking agent who portrayed himself as a drug
dealer.
   The Cantonese-speaking federal agent, Frederick Yau, met with
gang members in Washington and Hong Kong to negotiate the purchase
of heroin from Asia.
   The heroin came from Burma and China and was transported to San
Francisco and New York City's Chinatown. It also was distributed to
Newark, N.J., Alexandria, Va., and Washington.
   U.S. members of the ring were selling hundreds of stolen or
illegally obtained hand- and machine guns and rifles on the streets
of New York City, usually to Chinese gangs.
   Many of the firearms were obtained with fraudulent
identification documents from gun shops in Fort Worth, Dallas and
Houston, Texas, the officials said.
   The Chinese gangs were buying AR-15 semi-automatic rifles _ the
civilian version of the Army's M-16 rifle _ and converting them
into fully automatic M-16s.
   Customs and ATF undercover agents bought 10 weapons from the
five people charged in New York City and ordered 1,000 more M-16s
that were to be delivered to Libya. Such shipments would have
violated the Arms Export Control Act, which sets up federal
licensing procedures for the sale of weapons to foreign countries.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
