<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FrisbeeInjury     04-15 0210</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Frisbee Injury,0216</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jury Awards Woman $300,000 For Injuries Suffered When Hit By
Teen-ager</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ALFRED, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The town of Ogunquit will appeal a $300,000
jury award to a Canadian woman who sued for injuries suffered when
she was knocked down by a teen-ager trying to catch a Frisbee on a
beach, an attorney said.
   Josee Noel, 50, of Mount St. Hilaire, Quebec, was struck from
behind by the teen-ager as she walked along the beach while on
vacation in July 1982.
   She said that she was knocked to the ground and broke her leg
but that complications during recovery kept her in a wheelchair for
three years.
   A Superior Court jury awarded Mrs. Noel $331,475 on Wednesday,
but Justice Paul A. Fritzsche reduced that to $300,000, the legal
limit on damages against a municipality.
   The incident occurred in an area where game-playing was banned.
Witnesses testified during the three-day trial that lifeguards did
not enforce the rule, although it was their job to do so.
   ``It was our contention that if a regulation is good enough to
have, it's good enough to enforce,'' said Mrs. Noel's attorney,
Robert H. Stier Jr.
   Ogunquit will appeal the verdict to the Maine Supreme Court,
said town attorney Jeffrey T. Edwards.
</TEXT>
