<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2123EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Iran-Contra     04-15 0566</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Iran-Contra,560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Judge Warns Against Unauthorized Disclosure of Classified
Documents</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ROWLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The judge in the Iran-Contra trial warned
Friday against the unauthorized disclosure of some 300,000
classified documents expected to be turned over to the defense by
prosecutor Lawrence E. Walsh.
   In an order detailing procedures for handling the documents by
the defense, U.S. District Judge Gerhard A. Gesell warned that
``unauthorized disclosure of classified information may constitute
violations of United States criminal laws.''
   ``Persons subject to this order are advised that direct or
indirect unauthorized disclosure, retention or negligent handling
of classified documents or information could cause serious damage,
and in some cases exceptionally grave damage, to the national
security of the United States or may be used to the advantage of a
foreign nation against the interests of the United States,'' the
judge said.
   The nine-page order requires that the defendants, their lawyers
and any witnesses must obtain approval of the court-designated
security officer before gaining access to classified documents.
   Access will be granted on a ``need-to-know'' basis and the
defendants, their lawyers and witnesses must sign an agreement not
to make unauthorized disclosures of the information contained in
the documents, Gesell said.
   ``Any violation of the terms of this order shall be immediately
brought to the attention of the court and may result in a charge of
contempt of court and possible reference for criminal
prosecution,'' Gesell said.
   Marine Lt. Col. Oliver L. North and former national security
adviser John M. Poindexter are accused of conspiring with arms
dealers Albert Hakim and retired Air Force Maj. Gen. Richard V.
Secord to divert profits illegally from the U.S.-Iran arms sales to
the Nicaraguan Contra rebels.
   At a hearing Tuesday, independent counsel Walsh said that as
many as 300,000 classified documents are being reviewed by an
interagency government task force. Walsh said he expected that
50,000 documents relevant to the case will be ready for defense
review by month's end.
   Gesell ordered that the defense is entitled to review the rest
of the material to determine if it is relevant to their case when
the matter goes to trial.
   The order requires that lawyers can only work with the documents
or discuss them with each other or witnesses in the special
security facility that is being constructed by the court security
officer.
   Gesell prescribed a type of word processing equipment, which is
apparently resistant to electronic eavesdropping, to be used by the
defense for preparing court pleadings based on the materials.
   All pleadings dealing with classified information must be
prepared in the facility and filed under seal with the court
security officer, who will delete classified references before the
briefs are placed in the public file, Gesell ordered.
   Before any classified document is introduced into evidence at
the trial, it must be declassified by the government agencies that
produced it.
   If the government refuses to declassify a document, the
Classified Information Procedures Act empowers the court to
substitute a statement of facts that the material would prove.
   The court could also agreed to delete certain classified
markings that reveal intelligence methods but were not pertinent to
the case.
   Gesell gave the defense until April 29 to file a challenge to
the application fo the classified information statute to the case.
The defense complained that the law requires procedures that
inhibit their ability to prepare their case.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0198 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1821EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Dukakis-Cuomo     04-15 0607</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dukakis-Cuomo,600</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cuomo Says Dukakis, Jackson, Gore All ``Singularly Important''
Democrats</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Stands for AM-Dukakis story listed with AM-Political Rdp on
digest</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MARC HUMBERT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ALBANY, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic presidential candidate Michael
Dukakis won praise but no endorsement Friday from New York Gov.
Mario Cuomo, who said all the contenders were ``singularly
important'' Democrats.
   Cuomo said at a state Capitol news conference that Dukakis, the
front-runner in polls preceding Tuesday's New York primary, was ``a
singularly important Democratic leader.''
   Two days earlier, the governor had told Jackson he was
``singularly important Democrat.''
   Questioned by reporters, Cuomo said all the Democratic
candidates, including Tennessee Sen. Albert Gore Jr., were
``singularly important'' no matter where they finish.
   Recent polls show Dukakis leading Jackson with Gore far behind
in the battle for the 255 delegates at stake in the primary, the
biggest delegate prize of the campaign season so far.
   Cuomo hasn't met with Gore since March 21 and is not scheduled
to.
   On Friday, the governor scrapped plans to make campaign stops
with all three candidates in the New York City area over the next
few days. His aides cited the press of state business.
   Earlier Friday, Dukakis spoke with students at a junior high
school in Brooklyn, warning against using illegal drugs and
engaging in an exchange with students on how widespread the problem
is.
   He met privately with some students and said they told him 25
percent to 50 percent of school-age kids were using drugs.
   Then, he walked around the crowded school auditorium, asking
students how many of their peers used drugs regularly.
   ``Crack can kill you, right? Who was killed by crack _ Lenny
Bias, right? ... In about four minutes, that young man's life was
snuffed out,'' he said, referring to the former University of
Maryland basketball star.
   At one point, he asked students what should be done to students
who use drugs. ``Should we suspend them?'' he asked, eliciting a
chorus of ``no'' from the students. ``Why not _ they're breaking
the law, aren't they?'' he said.
   Later, at a rally in Albany after his appearance with Cuomo,
Dukakis criticized the Reagan administration for not doing more in
the fight against illegal drugs.
   ``Why do we have money for Star Wars and not money for a war
against drugs?'' he asked. ``The greatest threat in this hemisphere
is not the Sandinistas, it's the avalanche of drugs.''
   Cuomo, during his news conference with Dukakis, said all three
candidates had grown during the campaign, but he declared ``that is
particularly true of Governor Dukakis.''
   ``If Governor Dukakis becomes the candidate of the Democratic
Party, he will be a superb representative of the Democrats,'' he
said. ``I believe he will be a winner in November and I believe he
would go on to be a great president.''
   During their news conference, Dukakis was asked if he had ``any
fear that when you get to the convention, you may be facing him
(Cuomo) as a competitor?''
   ``Should I have?'' joked Dukakis to Cuomo. The New York governor
said, ``No.''
   While Cuomo declared more than a year ago that he wouldn't seek
the Democratic presidential nomination, it was only in the past few
days that he has indicated he wouldn't accept a draft at a
deadlocked convention.
   When the questioning turned to whether the Massachusetts
governor would want Cuomo to serve in a Dukakis administration,
Dukakis said it was ``not the time to be thinking about who should
be in your administration.''
   ``Can we fix a time?'' asked Cuomo.
   ``But his mother always wanted him to serve on the Supreme
Court,'' said Dukakis.
</TEXT>
