<2ND_LINE>AM-SAfrica-Explosion, 1st Ld - Writethru,a0707,0397</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Explosion Kills Man Near Crowded Theater</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 9 grafs to UPDATE with police saying only one
injured, additional details; picks up 8th graf pvs: On Thursday...
^By GREG MYRE</NOTE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JOHANNESBURG, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bomb exploded in front of a
crowded movie theater in downtown Pretoria on Friday night, killing
a man and injuring a woman, police said.
   Police spokesman Eddie Everson said the blast occurred about
7:30 p.m. (1:30 p.m. EDT) on the street in front of the Sterland
Cinema complex. A second explosion happened about 15 minutes later
at a shop several blocks away.
   Everson said a man was killed in the theater blast, and police
are investigating whether he may have been the person who planted
the bomb. He said a woman was slightly wounded.
   He had said earlier that there were ``numerous'' injuries, but
amended his report.
   The spokesman said the dead man's body was ``very badly
mutilated,'' and a car in the street was destroyed. But he said
there was no damage to the eight-cinema complex, which attracts
hundreds of people on Friday nights.
   ``The possibility that the man killed was the person who placed
the bomb is being investigated,'' Everson said. ``At this stage
this has not been determined whether this is the case or not.''
   Police immediately evacuated the movie theaters and cordoned off
surrounding streets.
   The second blast occurred on a street where all the shops were
closed for the evening. Some windows were broken but there were no
injuries, Everson said.
   No one claimed responsibility for the explosions.
   On Thursday night, a bomb damaged the facade of the City Hall
building in downtown Johannesburg, but caused no injuries. No one
has claimed responsibility for the bombing.
   However, police have blamed virtually all bombings in recent
years on the African National Congress guerrilla group.
   The outlawed ANC, based in Lusaka, Zambia, wages a bombing and
sabotage campaign in a bid to overthrow the white-led government.
The ANC rarely confirms or denies involvement in bombings in South
Africa.
   There have been more than 60 bombings in South Africa since the
government declared a state of emergency in June 1986. Three
blacks, including a policemen, were killing March 17 in a car
bombing in Krugersdorp, about 20 miles west of Johannesburg.
</TEXT>
