<1ST_LINE>r p AM-LaCongress     04-15 0226</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-La Congress,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Voters To Replace Gov. Buddy Roemer</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW ORLEANS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Voters in northwest Louisiana decide Saturday
whether to send a Republican with a Democratic past or a four-term
Democratic state senator to Congress to serve out Gov. Buddy
Roemer's unexpired term.
   Republican Jim McCrery, a 38-year-old lobbyist for
Georgia-Pacific Corp. and a former aide to Roemer, led Foster
Campbell in this week's polls by 4 to 5 percentage points in the
race for the 4th Congressional District seat.
   If elected, McCrery, who switched from the Democratic Party to
the GOP in October, would be the first Republican from the district
since Reconstruction.
   Roemer, a Democrat, vacated the seat March 14, the day he was
inaugurated governor. The winner of Saturday's race will have to
run for re-election again in the fall. Roemer has made no
endorsement.
   Campbell, 41, of Elm Grove, lost an eye and broke several facial
bones March 13 when he drove his car off an unfinished, closed
portion of Interstate 49.
   The campaign has been a lively one, beginning with a field of 10
candidates, McCrery as the only GOP candidate.
   In the March 8 primary, McCrery led with 31 percent of the vote
followed by Campbell with 19 percent. The runoff election Saturday
was made necessary because no one had a majority.
</TEXT>
