<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2131EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ChildCareReport     04-15 0396</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Child Care Report,370</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Labor Task Force Report Higlights Child Care Needs,000</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By Crispin Y. Campbell</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Child care is ``a new urgency for America's
working parents'' and increasingly an issue that employers must
face, a Labor Department report said Friday.
   Labor Secretary Ann McLaughlin said the issue was ``a national
concern.''
   ``Let's start with a key fact: over half of the country's women
with pre-school or school-age children work,'' she said at a news
conference, noting that each group of children from infants to
latch-key children required a different programmatic response.
   The department's 12-member Task Force on Child Care, composed of
senior Labor Department officials, has reviewed proposed
legislation, major articles, surveys and studies on the issue to
determine the severity of the problem.
   The panel's report found the child care issue to be ``a matter
of new urgency for America's working parents, one that by simple
arithmetic is of considerable magnitude.''
   The task force said that there was ``widespread (public) concern
that a crisis exists ... in the ability of America's parents'' to
find child care, but the panel stopped short of describing the
problem as a crisis.
   ``We don't see it as a national ... crisis but we see it as a
terrific national concern,'' McLaughlin said.
   The report, entitled ``Child Care: A Workforce Issue,'' said the
federal government is already addressing the child care issue with
more than $6.9 billion spent on Head Start and other child care
programs. It said state and local governments have shown commitment
to funding for child care, training providers, referral systems and
defining standards for providers.
   But although many employers have realized the economic benefits
of responding to employee child care needs, others have yet to
grasp the impact of inadequate child care on worker performance and
absenteeism, the report said.
   McLaughlin said the Labor Department would conduct a
comprehensive review of all departmental laws and regulations to
evaluate their impact on work and family; recognize employers and
unions who develop new approaches to child care and publish and
promote examples; provide technical assistance and information to
labor and management, and increase the availability of child care
options in the Job Corps and the Job Training Partnership Act.
   McLaughlin said department's day care center would be expanded
as an employer model, as would the availability of assistance to
department employees.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
