<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-UN-Israel     04-15 0567</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-UN-Israel,0586</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Vetoes Resolution Opposing Israeli Deportations</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CANDICE HUGHES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>UNITED NATIONS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   America on Friday vetoed a Security
Council resolution that urged Israel to stop deporting Palestinians
from the occupied territories, saying the measure lacked balance.
   Arab diplomats denounced the action and said it hurt the latest
U.S. initiative to promote Middle East peace talks.
   Fourteen of the council's 15 members voted for the resolution
and Britain made an unusually harsh speech against Israel's policy
of deporting Palestinians allegedly linked to disturbances in the
occupied West Bank of the Jordan River and Gaza Strip.
   British Ambassador John Birch called the deportations ``brutal
and often indiscriminate actions'' and said they are ``immoral,
illegal and politically self-defeating.''
   ``World opinion has been shocked and disgusted _ rightly so _ by
the widespread suffering of the civilian population of all ages and
both sexes'' in the territories, he said.
   Arab League spokesman Clovis Maksoud said the veto ``mortally
wounded'' the U.S. peace initiative and would encourage Israel to
mistreat the 1.5 million Palestinians living under Israeli
occupation.
   ``The veto today ratifies that level of permissiveness that has
emboldened Israel to defy the international community,'' Maksoud
told a news conference after the council meeting.
   Zehdi L. Terzi, envoy of the Palestine Liberation Organization
that has observer status at the United Nations, told the council
the United States had isolated itself by killing the resolution.
``There's always a rotten apple in the box,'' he said.
   In casting the veto, U.S. Ambassador Herbert S. Okun said the
resolution's ``broad and sweeping condemnation of Israel contains
not a scintilla of balance. It contains no appeal or request for
calm.''
   The measure urged Israel to halt deportations, condemned human
rights violations in the occupied territories and called for a
U.N.-sponsored settlement of the Arab-Israeli conflict.
   Israel deported eight Palestinian civilians earlier this week
and issued deportation orders for 12 others as part of its effort
to quell four months of violence in the West Bank and Gaza that has
claimed more than 140 Arab lives. Two Israelis have died.
   Okun told the council the United States is engaged in a major
diplomatic effort to bring about direct negotiations between Israel
and its Arab neighbors.
   The Soviet Union and most Arab nations want a peace conference
under U.N. auspices that would include the PLO and the five
permanent members of the Security Council: the United States,
Soviet Union, China, Britain and France. Permanent members have
veto power.
   Other members of the council are Algeria, Argentina, Brazil,
Italy, Japan, Nepal, Senegal, West Germany, Yugoslavia and Zambia.
   Israel refuses to talk with the PLO, which it considers a
terrorist organization, and Prime Minister Yitzhak Shamir has
opposed an international peace conference, saying it might try to
force concessions that would jeopardize Israel's security.
   Despite its veto, the United States has been critical of
Israel's handling of violence in the occupied territories.
   On Jan. 5, it cast a rare vote against Israeli, joining the rest
of the Security Council in approving a resolution urging the Jewish
state to refrain from an earlier round of deportations.
   Israel defied the resolution and deported four Palestinian
activists to Lebanon.
   The United States on Jan. 14 declined to use its veto to protect
Israel and abstained as the council passed a resolution urging
Israel to let the deportees return.
   Okun said Friday the latest resolution was redundant.
</TEXT>
