<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Spain-Bomb     04-15 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Spain-Bomb,0343</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bomb Explodes at U.S. Air Force Facility, Causing Slight Damage</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-USO Bombing, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADRID, Spain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An explosive device blew up early Friday at
a U.S. Air Force radio-relay station causing slight damage and no
injuries, U.S. Embassy spokesman Bob Meade reported.
   He said the bomb had been placed near an air conditioning unit
at the Humosa relay station six miles east of the U.S.-Spanish air
base at Torrejon. The air base is 12 miles northeast of Madrid.
   The Spanish news agency EFE quoted an unidentified Defense
Ministry source as saying the bombing could be related to the
second anniversary of the April 15, 1986, U.S. air raids on Libya.
   The explosion occurred a day after a car bomb blew up in front
of a USO club in Naples, Italy, killing five people, including a
U.S. Navy servicewoman. Italian police said they believed a member
of the Japanese Red Army was responsible.
   A group calling itself the Organization of Jihad Brigades
claimed responsibility for the attack and said it was in revenge
for the U.S. bombing of Libya.
   Meade said no group or individual asserted responsibility for
the attack near Madrid. He said the blast damaged a maintenance
building but did not interrupt Air Force communications at Torrejon.
   There have been many demonstrations in recent years at Torrejon
protesting U.S. military bases in Spain and Spain's membership in
the North Atlantic Treaty Organization.
   In January, the United States agreed to withdraw within three
years a tactical wing of 72 F-16 fighter bombers from Torrejon.
That was part of a new eight-year pact on American military units
in Spain that will replace a five-year accord which expires May 14.
   The U.S. armed services maintain three air bases and a naval
station in Spain that involve some 10,000 military personnel.
   President Reagan ordered the air raids on Libya in retaliation
for alleged Libyan links to the bombing of a nightclub in West
Berlin that killed two U.S. servicemen and a Turkish woman.
</TEXT>
