<1ST_LINE>u a AM-PoliceSlayings     04-15 0349</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Police Slayings,0360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Four Arrested In Slayings Of Navajo Tribal Policemen</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARNI McENTEE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SALT LAKE CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Four Navajo men were arrested Friday in
the Dec. 4 slayings of two Navajo tribal police officers believed
beaten and shot while trying to break up a desert drinking party.
   The arrests capped an investigation in which FBI and Navajo
authorities questioned more than 100 tribal members about the
discovery of the bodies in a burned-out police van at a remote
desert site near Monument Valley on Dec. 5.
   U.S. Attorney Brent Ward said the four suspects were residents
of Monument Valley, a reservation town near the Arizona border
where they were arrested.
   Thomas Cly and Marques Atene, both 22; Vinton Bedoni, 31; and
Ben Atene Jr., 24, a cousin of Marques Atene, awaited arraignment
on federal charges of first-degree murder on an Indian reservation
and aiding and abetting.
   Four to 10 FBI agents had been in Monument Valley since the day
after the slayings, said FBI agent Robert Bryant.
   ``When you have two fellow police officers brutally shot down,
it is a priority with our agency, and certainly with the others
involved. These arrests today will bring these individuals before
the bar of justice,'' Bryant said.
   Navajo police said tribal officers Andy Begay, 35, of Halchita,
and Roy Lee Stanley, 27, of Oljeto, appeared to have been beaten
and shot in the head after responding to a disturbance near
Gouldings shortly before midnight Dec. 4.
   An argument may have developed when the officers tried to break
up a drinking party at the site, where a bonfire had been built,
police said. Teeth matching one of the officers and pools of blood
were found there.
   The officers' vehicles were taken into Copper Canyon and set
afire, the bodies placed in the prisoner compartment of one of
them, Navajo police said.
   A $10,000 reward had been posted in the case. In February the
FBI said that suspects in the slayings had been identified but that
investigators could not persuade witnesses to testify because they
apparently feared retribution.
</TEXT>
