<1ST_LINE>u a AM-SchnickTrial     04-15 0622</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Schnick Trial,0643</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Death Penalth Recommended For Farmer In Mass Slaying</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONNA BRYSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MARSHFIELD, Mo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury recommended Friday that a
southwestern Missouri dairy farmer be put to death for killing his
wife and two nephews, including a teen-ager whom he had originally
blamed for the killings.
   The jury which convicted James E. Schnick of Elkland of three
counts of first-degree murder had the alternative of recommending
life in prison. If a judge accepts the jury's recommendation,
Schnick would become the 57th person on death row at the Missouri
State Penitentiary, where there has not been an execution since
1965.
   The Webster County jury Thursday found Schnick guilty in the
deaths of his wife, Julie, and two nephews, Kirk Buckner, 14, and
Michael Buckner, 2. On Friday, they recommended the death penalty
on all three counts.
   Schnick also is accused but was not tried in the deaths of his
brother-in-law, Steve Buckner; Buckner's wife, Jeannette; and the
Buckners' two other sons, Dennis, 8, and Timmy, 6. Buckner and Mrs.
Schnick were brother and sister.
   All the victims died in an early morning shooting spree Sept. 25
at the Buckner and Schnick families' dairy farms in nearby Elkland.
The Schnicks' two young children were not injured.
   Schnick originally blamed the slayings on his nephew Kirk, and
claimed he killed the boy in self-defense. The allegation shocked
members of the community who knew the teen-ager, who was described
as quiet and hard-working.
   Within days, however, Schnick himself was charged in connection
with the seven deaths. Police said he confessed during questioning,
but he claimed during the trial that the confession was not freely
given.
   Webster County Prosecutor Donald Cheever said the crimes were
aggravated by the fact that Schnick may have killed his wife in
order to collect life insurance. The number of victims, and the
youth of many of them, also prompted Cheever to seek the death
penalty.
   ``It's difficult to imagine anything more defenseless and more
helpless in this world than a 2-year-old asleep in his bed,''
Cheever said in his closing arguments. ``Anyone who would kill an
infant in those circumstances deserves the most severe punishment
possible under the law.''
   Schnick's attorney pleaded for her client's life, on behalf, she
said, of his two surviving children.
   ``No one is minimizing the terribleness or the horror of what
has occurred ...,'' Susan Chapman said. ``Healing comes with time
and love and compassion. It's not going to come with vengence.''
   Ms. Chapman had called Schnick's friends and family members to
attest that he had been a helpful neighbor and caring father. She
said their testimony proved that ``there is the possibility of
redemption.''
   Daniel Foster, chief of psychology at the Federal Medical Center
at Rochester, Minn., testified that after evaluating Schnick and
interviewing many of his friends, he concluded that Schnick strove
all his life to please others and was frustrated by his inability
to satisfy those closest to him when he lost control Sept. 25.
   ``The acting out that he did ... is very unlikely ever to be
repeated,'' Foster said.
   The defense contended during the trial that Schick's confession
was gained under pressure, and that he had been under the influence
of medication on the day of the shootings.
   Schnick's long-time physician, Dr. J.C. Presley, said he
examined Schnick Oct. 2, three days before his confession, and
prescribed a painkiller.
   ``It dulls the awareness,'' Presley said. `` It tends tp make a
patient sleepy and impair his intellectual function.''
   But county coroner Dr. J.D. Blinn, called as a rebuttal witness,
said he prescribed the same painkiller often during his 41 years as
a general practitioner, and rarely noted that his patients reacted
with drowsiness.
</TEXT>
