<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2001EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Canada-Trade     04-15 0533</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Canada-Trade,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Yeutter Says U.S. Trade Bill Will be Vetoed</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BRADLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>VANCOUVER, British Columbia (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan will veto
the omnibus trade bill before Congress because Democratic leaders
insist on plant closure safeguards, U.S. Trade Representative
Clayton Yeutter said Friday.
   He said the dispute could delay and possibly jeopardize
congressional approval of the historic U.S.-Canada Fee Trade
Agreement.
   ``The labor unions got their way,'' Yeutter told the Vancouver
Board of Trade in a luncheon speech prior to a weekend meeting with
the trade ministers of Canada, Japan and the European Community.
   He credited Congress with the ``almost unprecedented'' deletion
of dozens of protectionist portions of the trade bill, to the point
where Reagan might be able to sign it.
   But he said the Democratic leadership informed the
administration on Thursday that they would not discard a section
requiring owners to give substantive notice before any plant
closures.
   ``That legislation is objected to vigorously by the American
business community and the administration,'' Yeutter said.
   ``Therefore, the trade bill is going to be vetoed. We believe we
can sustain the veto, which means we're back to ground zero after
two or three years' work on a trade bill.
   ``That could have implications for the Free Trade Agreement.''
   He said at the very least, the trade bill battle will delay
consideration of the trade accord for about 30 days, and ``bruised
feelings'' in Congress could erode support for it.
   The trade deal was negotiated with Prime Minister Brian
Mulroney's Conservative government last year and is set to go in
effect in January if ratified by Congress and Canada's Parliament.
   It would eliminate all tariffs in the world's biggest trading
partnership over a 10-year period and loosen non-tariff and
investment barriers.
   Yeutter said he remains confident the trade pact will be passed
this year, but said the vote could come after Labor Day instead of
prior to the summer recess as Reagan hoped.
   He said it is possible that congressional leaders will amend the
U.S. trade bill before a final vote next Thursday or Friday, or
revise it quickly after a presidential veto.
   ``I certainly wouldn't reach the conclusion the Free Trade
Agreement is in mortal danger,'' he told a news conference.
   Mulroney faces re-election in the next year and had hoped to
have the trade agreement approved in time for a possible early
election this fall.
   Yeutter joined newly appointed Canadian Trade Minister John
Crosbie, Japanese Trade Minister Hajime Tamura and Trade
Commissioner Willy De Clerq of the 12-nation European Community for
a weekend retreat on isolated Quadra Island near Vancouver.
   The regularly scheduled meeting was expected to focus on
progress in the Uruguay round of talks to revamp the 95-country
General Agreement on Tariffs and Trade.
   For the first time, Yeutter said, GATT is discussing world
trading rules for services such as insurance and computer software.
Washington also seeks more protection for patents, trademarks and
copyrights, as well as structural reform to improve the monitoring
of trade practices.
   He said he also looked for progress with Japan over higher
quotas for U.S. beef and citrus products. Otherwise, Yeutter said,
the United States will press its complaints before GATT.
</TEXT>
