<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lesotho-Emergency     04-15 0166</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lesotho-Emergency,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Overturns State of Emergency Declaration</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MASERU, Lesotho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Lesotho High Court voided the
national state of emergency Friday, declaring that the nation's
military rulers exceeded their powers when they imposed it Feb. 25.
   The Military Council led by Major Gen. Justin Lekhanya said it
would honor the decision. Lekhanya said in declaring the emergency
that its purpose was to counter a politically inspired crime wave.
   Security forces shot three people to death during the emergency.
   In a petition to the High Court, the Law Society of Lesotho
argued that Lekhanya did not have the powers to make the
declaration.
   It acted after three lawyers were detained two weeks ago under
emergency regulations. The court also ruled that the government
violated the rights of the detained lawyers.
   Lekhanya and the six-man Military Council assumed power in
January 1986 after ousting Prime Minister Leabua Jonathan in a
coup. Lesotho is completely surrounded by South Africa and
economically dependent on its powerful neighbor.
</TEXT>
