<1ST_LINE>u a AM-ArsonArrest     04-15 0338</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Arson Arrest,0349</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Teen Arrested for Setting Blaze That Killed 12-Year-Old</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIRGINIA BYRNE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A 15-year-old suspected crack user accused of
torching a home that his gang used as a hangout may have been
seeking revenge against a resident who had complained to police, a
detective said Friday.
   The resident's 12-year-old son was killed and six others injured
in the fire early Thursday.
   Antione Montgomery was accused of using a blowtorch to set fire
to a couch and a blanket in the house. He was arrested and charged
as an adult with murder, arson and assault Thursday.
   Queens Chief of Detectives Joseph Borrelli said the 15-year-old
and as many as nine other youths had taken over a man's first-floor
apartment in the building about six weeks ago for ``fun and games''
and to package crack.
   Another resident, Eyvonne Perkins, 31, called police Wednesday
night to complain that two gang members were throwing rocks at her
second-floor windows. They were gone by the time a patrol car came
by, police said.
   Montgomery returned at 5:45 a.m. and started the fire, police
said.
   ``It would appear the way they were comfortable in this
residence was going to come to an end and they would probably have
to leave,'' Borrelli said in speculating that revenge was the
motive.
   The detective said the man in the first-floor apartment moved to
another part of the house because ``he was intimidated and
fearful.''
   The house is just a few blocks from where a rookie police
officer was shot to death at point-blank range in February while
guarding the home of a man who had complained of drug dealing in
the neighborhood.
   The Tactical Narcotics Team has made 560 arrests, 467 of them
for narcotics, since designating the neighborhood a target area
March 4.
   In addition to the death of Michael Perkins, three family
members and three firefighters were injured, said.
   Investigators are looking for the other youths ranging in age
from 15 to 20, Borrelli said.
