<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PTLHearing     04-15 0468</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-PTL Hearing,0479</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>PTL Must Prepare to Sell Property, Judge Warns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GREENSBORO, N.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A bankruptcy judge granted PTL an
extension Friday to devise its reorganization plan, while the
ministry's court-appointed trustee said PTL would not be able to
make a $5.7 million payment due May 2.
   The trustee, David Clark, also said the ministry would lay off
an additional 125 people.
   PTL had been scheduled to make its first major payment May 2 to
start repaying the more than $60 million in debts accumulated by
former PTL leaders Jim and Tammy Bakker. However, federal
bankruptcy Judge Rufus Reynolds gave the ministry until May 15 _ a
month from Friday _ to modify its reorganization plan to include
possible sale of assests to pay the debt.
   Reynolds warned Clark that PTL should be prepared to sell
property not related to the church or its television program to pay
its debts, assets the ministry had hoped to avoid parting with by
holding a monthlong telethon in March on its evangelical television
show. However, only $2.2 million was raised.
   ``I visualize an orderly liquidation,'' Reynolds said.
``Whatever's left (of the property) would go to the ministry.''
   Clark said the reorganization plan might be revised to include
the sale of $3 million to $4 million of undeveloped land this year.
Other assets, including the Heritage Grand Hotel, could be sold as
a last move, he said.
   David West, PTL's director of public relations, echoed: ``If we
made a list of priorities of assets that could be sold, the hotel
would be the last.''
   Linda Ivey, a spokeswoman for the PTL in Fort Mill, S.C., said
although the May 2 payment of $5.7 million was scheduled to be the
first payment under the reorganization plan, the ministry has
managed to pay some creditors ``bills that they knew would come up
under that process.''
   For that reason, and because of mounting legal and
administrative costs of the bankruptcy, the amount due creditors in
the May 2 payment has fluctuated. PTL administrators had estimated
last month they would owe about $4.2 million. However, as of Friday
the amount had risen to $5.7 million, she said in a telephone
interview.
   Reynolds gave PTL the extension after a hearing on a government
motion to delay the May 2 implementation of PTL's court-approved
plan.
   In the motion filed in federal bankruptcy court in Columbia,
S.C., Justice Department attorneys argued that PTL remains on shaky
ground with the Internal Revenue Service, which is seeking more
than $55 million in back taxes.
   The U.S. government appealed the PTL reorganization plan on Dec.
29, and still opposes it.
   The reorganization plan anticipates that PTL will qualify as
tax-exempt. But so far, the IRS hasn't agreed to PTL's request and
has warned that PTL may lose its tax-exempt status.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
