<1ST_LINE>r p AM-Jackson 1stLd-Writethru a0705 04-15 0485</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jackson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0705,460</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Jackson Urges Queens Residents to ``Drive Drugs Out''</HEAD>
<NOTE>EDs: ADDS 3 grafs to UPDATE with Jackson addressing gay and
lesbian rally</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD M. ROTHBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Political Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jesse Jackson compared drug dealers to Klansmen
on Friday and urged residents of a Queens housing project to
``drive drugs out of your neighborhood.''
   Campaigning for support in New York's Democratic presidential
primary next Tuesday, Jackson walked through South Jamaica House, a
low-income public housing project.
   As he walked through the project hundreds of residents crowded
around reaching out to shake his hand or, at least, touch his coat.
Others waved from apartment windows.
   ``Ropes, sheets and hoods represent death,'' he told them,
adding that ``we never lost as many lives to Southern rope'' as to
drugs.
   ``The dope pusher, the dope trafficker, the drug warlords
threaten the fabric of our lives,'' he said.
   ``The dope pusher does not wear sheets and hoods, the dope
pusher is the hood who lives in the neighborhood,'' said Jackson.
   The crowd cheered when he urged them to join him in an effort to
rid their neighborhood of drugs.
   ``Our minds must rebel against the drug pusher,'' he said. ``Our
attitudes must rebel against the drug pusher. Our morality must
rebel against the drug pusher.
   ``We must drive drugs out of your neighborhood.''
   From the project Jackson went to a drug rehabilitation center
run by the Jamaica Community Action Program, where he said that
``as president I can substantially cut the supply of drugs, but the
people must cut down the demand for drugs.''
   While he spoke Jackson aides passed out a written summary of his
anti-drug proposal, which includes a $2 billion increase in federal
spending to combat trafficking.
   At a breakfast meeting with community ministers, Jackson
ridiculed Reagan administration anti-drug efforts, as well as the
positions being taken by his Democratic rivals.
   He described Massachusetts Gov. Michael Dukakis and Sen. Albert
Gore Jr. of Tennessee as captains and lieutenants in the war
against drugs.
   ``I'm the general in this war,'' he said.
   ``Now, everybody's fighting for the homeless,'' he went on.
``I'm a five-star general in that war.''
   He said other candidates were beginning ``to focus on teenage
mothers. Good, I'm the son of one.''
   Jackson also referred repeatedly to the shutdown of the
Williamsburg Bridge, a main commuter route between Brooklyn and
Manhattan.
   ``Because of lack of investment in the infrastructure, bridges
are falling,'' he said.
   ``We must rebuild the people even as we are rebuilding the
city,'' he said.
   Jackson later addressed several thousand people at a gay and
lesbian rally for his campaign in Greenwich Village.
   ``I stood with you because it was the right thing to do,'' he
told them.
   His statement that ``Testing for AIDS must be voluntary and
confidential'' drew loud cheers from the crowd that extended a full
block along 13th Street.
</TEXT>
