<2ND_LINE>AM-Iced Cocaine,0169</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Agents Seize Cocaine In Ecuadoran Fruit Pulp Shipment</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORT EVERGLADES, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal agents seized more than a
ton of cocaine hidden in frozen fruit pulp imported from Ecuador,
U.S. Customs officials said Friday.
   Suspicious Customs agents Wednesday had opened several plastic
containers of the pulp that arrived April 7, finding a 10-pound
packet of cocaine inside one, said agency spokesman Cliff Stallings.
   The shipment was put under surveillance and on Thursday two men
spotted unloading the containers were arrested on smuggling
charges, Stallings said. The pulp was thawed out and found to
contain about 2,500 pounds of cocaine.
   Customs gave no estimate of the value of the drug. However,
Metro-Dade police said that a pound of cocaine sells for $6,000 to
$12,000 on the street in Miami, depending on its quality and who is
selling it.
   Arrested were Nestor Pinango, 57, president of Frecar, the firm
to which the shipment was addressed, and Guillermo Gonzalez, 46,
also of Miami.
</TEXT>
