<1ST_LINE>u a AM-TaxDeadline 1stLd-Writethru a0740 04-15 0862</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Tax Deadline, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0740,0882</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>The American Sloth Begins Annual Tax Migration to the Post Office</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 3 gras to UPDATE with quote from Arkansas tax
preparer. PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `Paul Monroe ...'; SUBS 12th graf
pvs, `It was party...' with 6 grafs to UPDATE with Chicago
pie-throwing stunt, more details on Springfield fete; INSERTS 1
graf after 17th pvs `Deadline Day ...' with Ohio protesters
building missile from tax forms.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Procrastinators and folks simply trying to forestall the
inevitable _ taxes, that is _ made their annual trek to the post
office Friday to mail their 1040 forms.
   ``This happens every year,'' said John Tobias, mail supervisor
at the Willkes-Barre, Pa., post office.
   ``I think it's terrible that people have to wait for the last
minute,'' Tobias said. ``People call you today and ask you at the
last minute if you have tax forms in your office. And we don't.''
   Dan Jenkins of Mr. Tax of America in Jonesboro, Ark., said at 7
p.m. that his firm had 10 customers left with appointments before
the midnight filing deadline. ``My last one is at 8:30, which I
expect to finish about 11 p.m.,'' he said.
   Paul Monroe, regional manager for H&R Block in Boston, said he
sees the same people, year after year, in the waning hours of tax
season.
   ``They look forward to the excitement of April 15th. The
adrenalin starts flowing,'' Monroe said. ``It's like a non-contact
sport.''
   Postal Service consumer advocate Ann Robinson in Washington said
the post office expected to handle 30 million tax returns
nationwide in the ``last couple of days'' before the deadline.
   Post offices across the country were open until midnight to
place the all-important April 15 postmark on tax returns, or on
envelopes containing Form 4868 requesting an automatic four-month
extension of the deadline.
   ``We expect thousands to be here tonight,'' U.S. Postal Service
spokesman Vito Fortuna said Friday at New York City's main post
office. Tables and chairs were set up for those serious
procrastinators who arrived with their forms still blank.
   Anita Castro, a spokeswoman at the IRS' center in Andover,
Mass., said 450,000 returns arrived Friday morning with more on the
way.
   In past years, the center has received some strange returns such
as a coffin filled with dollar bills and checks written on edible
underpants. This year, she said, the center's 5,500 employees found
nothing unusual.
   ``So far it's just paper, paper, paper, tons of paper,'' Castro
said. ``It looks like a wagon train of paper.''
   Chicago taxpayers got a chance to vent their anger by throwing
luscious whipped cream pies at a mock IRS agent dubbed ``Shirdolph
Yurback,'' also known as Scott Goodman, part-owner of the Superior
Street Cafe.
   ``You know what I'm going to do with your taxes?'' he taunted
one passerby. ``I'm going to fund a study of South American
insects.''
   At $1 to $2 a throw, the stunt raised a couple hundred dollars
for a non-profit group for mentally retarded adults, Goodman said.
   It was party time in Springfield, Mass., where the post office
laid on a six-piece band, dancing raisins and a singing letter
carrier in a costume which was half Elvis Presley, half regulation
blue. His song: ``Return to Sender.''
   ``It's become a tradition,'' said Springfield Postmaster Jon
Steele, who decided in 1983 to liven up a long night and ease the
pain by offering free coffee and music April 15. This year a radio
station threw in free sandwiches.
   More than 7,000 tax returns were processed between 5 p.m. and 7
p.m., according to Mary Hartford, a spokeswoman for the post office.
   Dave Mazer, communications manager for the postal service in Los
Angeles, said no extra workers were called in Friday though some
employees would work overtime.
   ``Believe it or not, with automation, we can handle this
additional volume of mail with no problems,'' Mazer said. ``It is
really not that difficult for us. We do this every year as a public
service. ... We live in a world of people who do things at the last
minute.''
   In Atlanta, the Westin Peachtree Plaza concocted an 800-pound
cake decorated like an 11-foot-long Form 1040 and invited people to
``take a bite'' out of the IRS.
   Deadline Day publicity stunts in New York included free samples
of antacid which were distributed outside the main post office, and
an ``IRS Stress Relief Clinic'' opened by a toy company, which
invited taxpayers to come in and yell at a dummy.
   In Columbus, Ohio, 15 protesters from Ohio State University
displayed a missile made of income tax forms outside a federal
office building. They also erected a structure of cans of food they
said they would donate to the poor in lieu of paying taxes for
military purposes.
   State tax officials in Texas reported a pleasant surprise in
their mail Friday _ cashiers' checks totaling $82,000 from a
penitent but anonymous tax evader.
   ``Please forgive our mistakes and shortcomings,'' said a short
note, which explained that the names on the checks were not real.
   ``Maybe so,'' said Texas Comptroller Bob Bullock, ``but the
money is.''
</TEXT>
