<HEAD>Union: FAA Safety Checks Sideline 10 Eastern Jets; Feds, EAL Mum</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES throughout with number of planes grounded reported to
be 15. No pickup.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Eastern Airlines planes grounded by
safety violations grew to at least 15 Friday as a federal crackdown
found problems including a fuel leak, a missing maintenance log and
a cracked wing flap, the Machinists union said.
   The airline and the Federal Aviation Administration refused to
confirm the number, saying they will detail no violations until the
inspection is complete. As of Thursday, the FAA had put the number
of planes grounded at six.
   ``They didn't want to see a running box score,'' FAA spokesman
John Leyden said of his agency's policy change after two days.
   The unprecedented inspection of all Eastern planes began after
the FAA slapped the company with a $823,000 fine for safety
violations. U.S. Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said
officials have been unsatisfied with Eastern's performance since
its 1986 takeover by Texas Air Corp., which also will undergo a
30-day inspection of its operating practices.
   Eight planes were found to have safety violations Friday
according to reports from union members around the country, said a
union spokesman who spoke on condition of anonymity for fear of
company retaliation.
   The latest groundings were in Kansas City, Mo., Boston, St.
Louis, Tallahassee and Atlanta, the union spokesman said. Planes
grounded by safety violations can be returned to service once they
are repaired.
   In addition, union officials said a 757 in Atlanta was grounded
on Wednesday and its passengers ordered off minutes before the
flight was to take off for Miami because the airline had failed to
repair fire-detection wiring in an engine a week and two warnings
after it was reported by an FAA inspector.
   Four planes were briefly sidelined Friday in Kansas City for
violations ranging from a seat on a Boeing 727 that reclined to
block an emergency exit to a wheel well leak on a DC-9, the union
said.
   In Boston an A-300 AirBus was sidelined Friday with a wing flap
dent and a fuel leak in an engine. The plane was fixed later in the
day, the union said.
   A St. Louis flight to Miamia was held for repairs Friday
morning, the union said. The Boeing 727 was found to have a cracked
wing flap. Late Thursday, DC-9 bound for Atlanta, was taken out of
service after FAA inspectors found it lacked a flight maintenance
log and was missing landing bumper pads.
   In Tallahassee, the battery relay switch on a DC-9 was found not
to be working. The switch turns on the plane's electrical
equipment, the union spokesman said.
   A DC-9 taken out of service at Atlanta when inspectors
discovered a duct in the tail section was overheating, the union
spokesman said.
   The eight Friday groundings were in addition to six the FAA
reported on Thursday and the one reported to have taken place
Wednesday.
   Leyden said about 20 percent of Eastern's 267-plane fleet had
been looked over by FAA inspectors in 23 cities when the agency
stopped reporting its findings Friday morning. Inspections were
expected to continue as flights arrived in those cities during the
30-day review that began Wednesday.
   Eastern spokewoman Karen Ceremsak said news of the sidelined
planes was being overblown. Some mechanical problems occur daily,
she said.
</TEXT>
