<1ST_LINE>u a AM-DoctorIndicted 2ndLd-Writethru a0844 04-15 0440</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Doctor Indicted, 2nd Ld - Writethru, a0844,0445</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researcher Indicted for Allegedly Falsifying Grant Request Data</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS lead and INSERTS one graf after 6th graf pvs, `Breuning
``knew ...' to ADD that charges of the first of their kind in the
nation.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By THOMAS GINSBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BALTIMORE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A psychologist was indicted Friday on charges
of submitting false data to win a $200,000 federal research grant.
A federal prosecutor said the charges were the first of their kind
in the nation.
   Stephen E. Breuning, 35, was charged in connection with a grant
received in 1982 from the National Institute of Mental Health in
Bethesda while he was a faculty member at the University of
Pittsburgh Medical School.
   The money already has been repaid by the university, U.S.
Attorney Breckinridge Willcox said in a statement.
   Breuning, now director of psychological services and behavorial
treatment at the Polk Center in Polk, Pa., submitted a 1981 grant
request for a study titled ``Stimulant Drug Use with Mentally
Retarded Children'' while at the university from 1982 to 1984, the
statement said.
   The indictment said Breuning's applications cited the results of
seven studies of hyperactive mentally retarded children.
   Breuning ``knew the ... studies had not been completed at the
University of Pittsburgh as described,'' and that ``the studies
that were ongoing were not obtaining the results as described,''
the indictment said.
   Willcox said that the indictment is believed to be first time
criminal charges have been brought against an individual in
connection with falsified research.
   ``We have ... addressed a problem that I suspect is more
widespread than we think: fraudulent research data in the medical
field,'' Willcox said. ``Let this investigation send a clear
message to doctors and researchers who play fast and loose with
their research that they will have to deal with the criminal
justice system in addition to their peer review panels.''
   In addition to two counts of making false statements, Breuning
was charged with obstructing a National Institute of Mental Health
investigation by falsely testifying at a 1985 hearing that he had
submitted a ``corrected version'' of his grant request.
   ``We vehemently deny the allegations and think they're patently
untrue,'' Breuning said by telephone from his Pittsburgh home
Friday night.
   If convicted, Breuning, who holds a doctorate in psychology from
the Illinois Institute of Technology, could receive up to 10 years
in prison and $20,000 in fines on the false statement counts, and
five years and $250,000 in fines on the obstruction count,
officials said.
   George Huber, a spokesman for the University of Pittsburgh, was
not available for comment, a university employee said Friday night.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
