<DOCNO> AP880415-0227 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0046EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-China-Film     04-15 0453</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-China-Film,0470</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Last Emperor' Sparks Legal Controversy in Chinese Congress</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Debate over whether the Oscar-winning film, ``The
Last Emperor,'' was filmed illegally in the Imperial Palace was a
hot topic in China's legislature this week.
   Delegates to the National People's Congress called on Vice
Minister of Culture Ying Ruocheng to give his account of the
affair, according to a report earlier this week in the Beijing
Evening News (Beijing Wanbao).
   Ying, an accomplshed actor, was closely involved with the film
directed by Bernardo Bertolucci. Ying played the supporting role of
warden in the war criminals prison where the emperor is sent for
``remolding and education.''
   The film crew used Imperial Palace buildings to shoot interior
scenes, but filming is forbidden in the palace under China's
historical preservation law.
   The law, which took effect in April 1985, is aimed at protecting
wooden structures from irreparable fire damage.
   During the 1{-hour question-and-answer session held Monday, Ying
told delegates that the contract with the Italian film company was
signed in March 1984, before the preservation law was issued, the
daily said.
   In addition, he cited the value of propagating China's cultural
heritage through film and assurances that the film company would
use fire prevention measures, the paper said.
   The director of the National Historical Preservation Bureau, Lu
Jimin, also defended the filming in the palace.
   ``In light of the contract being signed first and, moreover, a
letter from officials of the Italian Communist Party requesting
help and cooperation, we decided to make this a special case.''
   Some congressional delegates complained that the treatment of
the foreign film makers was an affront to China's attempts to
develop a modern legal system and establish ``rule by law.''
   ``In the final analysis, did the contract obey the law or
overturn it?'' Hebei province delegate Li Zhuang was quoted as
asking.
   The debate was triggered when producers of an all-Chinese film
crew making a television series, also entitled ``The Last
Emperor,'' wrote a letter to a government advisory body in March
complaining that they had been denied access to palace buildings.
   ``Is law greater in China, or is power? Do foreigners have to
obey our laws or not?'' the letter asked.
   The letter appealed to the Chinese People's Political
Consultative Conference to ``criticize and halt unhealthy
tendencies and to reaffirm the integrity of Chinese lawmaking.''
   According to the Beijing Evening News report, Ying Ruocheng and
his colleagues promised that film or television crews would not be
given special privileges again.
   The delegates ended their annual session on Wednesday.
   The Chinese media has reported with little comment the awarding
of nine Academy Awards, including best picture, to ``The Last
Emperor.''
   The film has not reached Chinese theaters.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
