<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18 and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>A Belter Gives Her All</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARY CAMPBELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A belter, says singer Nell Carter, is one who
gives his or her all.
   ``You're afraid you might hyperventilate or crack, but you do it
for the excitement of it,'' the Tony award-winning performer said.
``Head singers have to hold everything tight to get the note. I
like belters, people who have that noncontrol but control.''
   Carter is also an Emmy winner who spent six seasons delighting
TV audiences on the sitcom ``Gimme a Break.'' She was interviewed
while in New York for a nine-day engagement at the Village Gate.
   ``I have a Las Vegas show,'' she said. ``One critic said on a
scale of one to 10 we were 11. I'm not doing that show.''
   The dinner show in Las Vegas, she said, is easy. ``They like
anything as long as it's recognizable. You get a chance to really
wail a song, do something with a great arrangement. The late show,
you have a lot of drunks. You sing whatever they want to hear.
Torch songs seem to go over.''
   She's choosing from among 60 songs in her New York show, which
opened April 15. ``I wanted to sing Harold Arlen this time and some
country songs and I'm learning `One of Us Was Wrong' from 1899 and
some Sophie Tucker songs. If you were to put this show on canvas,
it would be very abstract.''
   Carter won a Tony for best featured actress in a musical for her
performance in ``Ain't Misbehavin','' the revue of Fats Waller
songs which opened on Broadway in 1978, and she will be in the
revival this August. She sings Waller's ``Keepin' Out of Mischief
Now'' in her show.
   She left ``Ain't Misbehavin''' after nine months to have her
tonsils out, sang Gershwin at the King Cole Room of the St. Regis
Hotel, was in ``Black Broadway'' at Town Hall and then returned to
``Ain't Misbehavin''' in San Francisco and Los Angeles to fulfill
her contract.
   ``They've always cast the part to look like me,'' she said.
``People will say they saw me in St. Louis.''
   In those days, and until about four years ago, Carter said she
did not appreciate her talent.
   ``I was hanging out with the wrong crowd, participating in
things I wouldn't choose to do now,'' she said. ``Now when I'm on
stage I know why they're applauding. I know what I just said. I
remember what I did last night.
   ``I'm not saying I was a loose woman. I did have my episode with
drugs.
   ``I was able to have a good career while I was doing terrible
things to myself. I don't see why I did not die. I think it must
have been a death wish for me to even be involved in the things I
was doing. Thank God I didn't die. Now I don't want to. It's a
different world for me now.''
   Growing up in Birmingham, Ala., Carter listened to her mother's
recordings of Dinah Washington and B.B. King, and her brother's
Elvis Presley records. She liked Doris Day, the Andrews Sisters,
Johnny Mathis, and mentions Cleo Laine and Barbra Streisand as
singers she admires.
   ``If Liza Minnelli wants to sing with me, I won't turn her down
_ I'll give the poor kid a break,'' she said. ``I would love to
sing with Joe Cocker. His soul is so bare.''
   However, Carter would like to have been an opera singer. ``When
I was growing up, it was not something you aspired to. I was a
weirdo to want to be in show business. Most kids wanted to be
teachers or nurses.''
   Carter has a daughter from a previous union and has been married
for six years. ``I'm not going to tell you anything about him,''
she said. ``He is a very private person, a very nice man. His
family does not understand publicity. They don't like it.''
   She collects crystal and antique silver picture frames and is an
avid reader, favoring biographies and history.
   She hopes to work with the producers of ``Gimme a Break'' again
and wants to get back on Broadway.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
