<NOTE>$Adv18</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Mon AMs, April 18, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>WASHN: more accountable.</HEAD>
<HEAD>HEALTH</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Jackson promises a national health care program covering all
Americans ``no matter what their income.'' It would cover nursing
home costs and be funded ``by earmarked health taxes and general
revenues.''
   Dukakis has promised to make universal health insurance a basic
right, but proposes to do it without ``creating a big new
bureaucratic program'' or spending ``a dime'' by requiring most
employers to offer health insurance as a fringe benefit.
   Massachusetts has just become the first state to move in that
direction, and similar legislation is already pending in Congress.
The Massachusetts plan, which exempts firms with five or fewer
employees, will cost that state $550 million or more through 1992.
   Gore has been instrumental in legislation creating an organ
transplant network and tougher regulation of companies that make
infant formula. He says, ``We must provide compassionate,
affordable health care so that hospital costs are not driven to
unbearable levels by the need to care for individuals who cannot
pay.''
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WELFARE, JOBS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   
   Dukakis promises an overhaul of welfare programs along the lines
of Massachusetts' successful effort to place welfare recipients in
jobs.
   Both Jackson and Gore support raising the $3.35-an-hour minimum
wage and to require future raises to keep pace with inflation.
Jackson also has called for a national minimum welfare benefit,
with two-parent families eligible. States are now free to set their
own Aid to Families with Dependent Children benefits, and to bar
payments to intact families.
   All three Democrats have vowed to step up federal efforts to
stop drugs. Jackson says he would boost the Reagan budget on drug
enforcement, prevention and treatment from $3.9 billion to $6.7
billion.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Mon AMs, April 18</NOTE>
