<NOTE>For Release Sunday, April 17, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>AP SPOTLIGHT: Israel _ The Changing Numbers</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: CORRECTS Population of West Bank and Gaza section to 850,000
in West Bank and 650,000 in Gaza, sted 836,000 and 545,000.
CORRECTS Immigration section to 1987, sted 1988. CORRECTS economy
section to 1987, sted 1988. CORRECTS military section to 1987, sted
1988.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Here are some comparative facts about Israel,
when the country was founded and now.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ISRAEL'S POPULATION
   Israel's population in 1948, according to government statistics,
was 872,700, including 716,700 Jews, and in 1949 was 1,173,900,
including 1,013,900 Jews. The population in 1988 is 4,331,300, of
whom 3,561,400 are Jews.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   POPULATION OF WEST BANK AND GAZA
   There were 585,900 in the West Bank when Israel captured it from
Jordan in 1967, and the population is 850,000 in 1988. In Gaza,
which belonged to Egypt, the population was 380,800 in 1967 and is
650,000 in 1988.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   IMMIGRATION
   The number of immigrants to Israel was 170,200 in 1950, but by
1987 had declined to 9,500.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   ECONOMY
   Israel's gross national product was $1.28 billion in 1950 and
$31.37 billion in 1987.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   AREA
   Including East Jerusalem and the Golan Heights, which have been
annexed, Israel's area is 13,330 square miles. There are 2,126
square miles in the West Bank and 140 in the Gaza Strip.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   MILITARY
   Defense expenditures have increased from $10.25 million in 1948
to $4.3 billion in 1987. The military has grown in size from 34,000
personnel to 170,000 with 370,000 reservists.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   LEADERS
   Israel's prime ministers have been David Ben-Gurion 1948-54,
Moshe Sharett 1954-55, David Ben-Gurion 1955-63, Levi Eshkol
1963-69, Golda Meir 1969-74, Yitzhak Rabin 1974-77, Menachem Begin
1977-83, Yitzhak Shamir 1983-84, Shimon Peres 1984-1986, and
Yitzhak Shamir since 1986.
   Those who have served as president are Chaim Weizman 1948-52,
Yitzhak Ben Zvi 1952-63, Zalman Shazar 1963-73, Ephraim Katzir
1973-78, Yitzhak Navon 1978-83, and Chaim Herzog since 1983.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Sunday, April 17</NOTE>
