<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0728EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a e BC-WeekendTV-Magnum Adv29-01   04-15 0781</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekend TV-Magnum, Adv 29-01,0799</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv29-01</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions, April 29-May 1, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Magnum Finale Promises No Reunions</HEAD>
<NOTE>With LaserPhoto</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By CHRISTINE DONNELLY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HONOLULU (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In what was billed as the series ender,
``Magnum, P.I.'' concluded last season with our hero getting gunned
down and walking off into an ethereal landscape that looked
suspiciously like heaven.
   But star Tom Selleck agreed to do 13 more episodes, and Magnum's
walk through the clouds was explained as an out-of-body experience.
   On Sunday, ``Magnum'' ends its eight-year run on CBS with a
special two-hour episode. This time, there will be no catch, no
reincarnation, no next season.
   ``After this episode, the audience would have a very hard time
figuring out how we could ever do a reunion show,'' said Selleck on
a break in filming. ``There's a finality to this show. We wanted to
do something that would threaten the franchise.''
   Chas. Floyd Johnson, the show's co-executive producer, wouldn't
give away the ending, but did say the finale will answer some
questions.
   ``It will touch on the issue of whether Jonathan is really Robin
Masters. It will deal with every one of the characters in at least
looking at what their lives will be like after `Magnum,''' he said.
   Selleck plays Thomas Magnum, a former Naval intelligence officer
turned private eye, perpetually on the brink of poverty but living
in high style, thanks to the largesse of never-seen wealthy mystery
writer Robin Masters.
   John Hillerman plays Jonathan Quayle Higgins, the British major
domo who runs Masters' estate and antagonizes Magnum, even as he
comes to his aid. Larry Manetti and Roger E. Mosley are Magnum's
Vietnam buddies, Rick and T.C.
   Set against the exotic backdrop of the islands, ``Magnum, P.I.''
plots ran from silly to deadly serious. The show made Selleck an
international star.
   In its early years, the CBS series consistently landed in the
top 10 of the Nielsen ratings. But in 1984, it was scheduled
against NBC's ``The Cosby Show'' and its ratings sagged. After some
juggling by CBS, ``Magnum'' moved to Wednesday night and regained
much of its audience.
   ``It's important to me that we go out while people still want
us,'' Selleck said. ``This show is too special to me to let it die
a natural death. No matter what the rest of my films did, or even
the success of `Three Men and a Baby,' it all came to me by way of
this show, and I've always tried to take care of `Magnum.'''
   ``Three Men and a Baby'' marked Selleck's first major screen
success after several starring roles.
   Selleck's reputation as an actor was initially overshadowed by
his image as a pin-up. But he eventually won an Emmy award as best
actor in a dramatic series. Working in Hawaii, he said, protected
him from the buffeting of sudden fame.
   ``I've been lucky over here, I've been sheltered from a lot of
the stuff tht goes on on the mainland,'' Selleck said. ``It's great
to be chosen favorite this or that, but a whole lot of baggage goes
with all those titles. And then what happens when you're not at the
top of the opinion polls? That's why, even though I appreciate it,
I try not to buy into that stuff and being in Hawaii has just made
that easier. Plus, I love it here.''
   He said he will maintain his ties to the islands. He has formed
a production company with Johnson and ``Magnum'' supervising
producer Chris Abbott and hopes to produce a new series here,
though without Selleck as star.
   Selleck's dual role of producing and starring in ``Magnum'' the
past two years resulting in an ``unnatural existence,'' he said.
   ``It just takes up too large a part of my life _ which is all my
waking hours _ and in the long run I just don't think that's very
healthy, physically or emotionally,'' said Selleck, who last year
married actress Jillie Mack.
   He planned to begin working in July on ``Her Alibi,'' a romantic
comedy directed by Bruce Beresford. Until then, he said, he'll
relax.
   ``I asked for the time off because I just don't know how I'm
gonna feel after Magnum ends,'' Selleck said. ``I think I really
need to take the time off to just see what happens. That's why I
really have very few kinds of goals or direction right now.''
   Saying goodbye won't be easy, Selleck said.
   ``There's a huge part of me that would love `Magnum' to go on
forever,'' he said. ``I really do believe that it'll be about the
best job I'll ever have.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Weekend Editions, April 29-May 1</NOTE>
