<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     04-15 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0233</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Close Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices are benefiting from the stock market
drop and from rumors about the scope of OPEC's planned meeting with
non-cartel exporters, market watchers say.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May-delivery price for
West Texas Intermediate crude closed up 18 cents per barrel to
$18.30 on Thursday. It was the highest since a Dec. 11 close at
$18.31.
   Refined products traded on the exchange were mixed. Heating oil
rose 0.49 cent per gallon to 49.51 cents, and unleaded gasoline
fell .06 cent a gallon to 52.36 cents.
   ``We had a strong day here today, but it was nervous
throughout,'' said Peter Beutel, assistant director of Elders
Futures Inc., an energy futures trading concern in New York.
   Traders said some buying in the oil market came from investors
who dumped stocks and were seeking havens for their money. The
stock market tumbled after the Commerce Department reported a
widening trade deficit in February.
   Others said the market was driven partly by rumors that the
Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries was expanding its
list of non-cartel guests at a previously announced meeting on
April 23.
   News of OPEC's plans to enlist outside support for boosting oil
prices has been the key reason for a market rally over the past few
days.
</TEXT>
