<DOCNO> AP880415-0248 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BankBid Bjt   04-15 0669</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Bank Bid, Bjt,0693</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bank of NY Stockholders Back Bid for Irving</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By VIVIAN MARINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   With the backing of its own shareholders
secured, Bank of New York Co. now turns its full attention to
convincing Irving Bank Corp. stockowners that its hostile $1
billion-plus takeover bid is a good deal.
   Chairman J. Carter Bacot said he had met privately with some of
Irving's biggest stockholders, and that bank officials would
continue soliciting others via telephone and mail until Irving's
annual meeting next Thursday.
   ``It's a unique fit,'' Bacot told Bank of New York shareholders
at their yearly gathering Thursday. ``Virtually all their
businesses blend well into our's. We believe no other merger could
make as much sense ...''
   Bank of New York is offering $15 in cash and 1.575 of its common
shares for each of Irving's roughly 18.1 million common shares
outstanding, a proposal Irving has rejected as inadequate during
their extended and bitter takeover fight.
   At Bank of New York's annual meeting, Bacot said preliminary
tabulations showed shareholders solidly backed the company by
granting it permission to issue as many additional common shares
and convertible securities as needed to complete the Irving
acquisition.
   The exact result of the vote on the stock question is to be
released April 22.
   Bank of New York, which holds a 4.9 percent stake in Irving, is
seeking to gain control of that company's board of directors and
has nominated a slate of 16 nominees.
   Analysts said they could not predict whether Bank of New York
could succeed.
   ``I can't take bets on that one ... though I'm sure Bank of New
York is feeling very bullish'' following Thursday's meeting, said
Rosemarie Conforte, a banking analyst with Moody's Investors
Service.
   ``I think that's a very close call,'' said Stephen Berman, a
banking analyst with County Securities USA. ``I think they (Irving
shareholders) may be persuaded, but it's a coin flip almost.''
   Many analysts agree that a combination of the two would not be
such a bad idea because both New York banks operate in a similar
marketplace and offer similar services such as securities
processing.
   But Irving repeatedly has spurned the company's takeover offers,
which began about seven months ago, maintaining it wants to remain
independent.
   Irving representatives had urged Bank of New York shareholders
Thursday to ask management to abandon all efforts to merge the two
banks. Irving argued that combining the two would dilute the value
of Bank of New York stock, hurting earnings and dividends.
   ``We are convinced that the cost of integrating the two
companies would create a further drain on earnings and that any
benefits of combining the two firms would not be recognized for
three to five years,'' said Robert A. Falise, an executive vice
president for legal affairs at Irving.
   But Bacot maintained dilution was not a problem. He also said a
takeover would not reduce Bank of New York's dividends, which have
increased annually for the past 11 years.
   Bank of New York began its current tender offer last month after
receiving regulatory approval.
   Both the Federal Reserve Board and the New York State Banking
Board said a merger wouldn't hurt competition in the nation's
biggest financial center. Irving has asked the federal courts to
overturn the Fed's decision.
   Irving has taken a number of other steps to tryto defeat Bank of
New York's advances, including instituting an anti-takeover
``poison pill'' defense that is designed to make any hostile buyout
prohibitively expensive.
   Hostile takeover efforts are rare in the banking industry. A
merger between New York Bank and Irving would create one of the
nation's 15 largest bank holding companies with combined assets of
more than $40 billion.
   Bank of New York began its takeover efforts six months ago with
an offer of $1.4 billion, or $80 in cash and securities. It revised
the offer to $68 in cash and securities following October's stock
market crash, and lowered the bid a second time in late January.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
