<DOCNO> AP880415-0249 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0156EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Trade-Markets Bjt   04-15 0514</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Trade-Markets, Bjt,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bigger Trade Deficit Knocks $100 Billion Out Of Wall Street</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Will be led with early market activity. Stands for PM-Economy
Rdp.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PETER COY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Investors remain cautious about the nation's
economic outlook today after a report of a rising U.S. trade gap
knocked them for a loop and sparked a $100 billion selloff on Wall
Street.
   The Commerce Department's report Thursday that the trade deficit
rose to $13.8 billion in February sparked a 101.46-point decline to
2,005.64 in the Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar fell about 2 percent against the
Japanese yen and West German mark despite central bank purchases
aimed at bolstering the dollar, and bond market interest rates rose
to their highest levels since January.
   The trade report raised concerns that the dollar would remain
under pressure despite a months-old agreement by major
industrialized nations to support it. That agreement was reaffirmed
Wednesday by the United States, Japan, West Germany, Britain,
France, Canada and Italy at a meeting in Washington.
   Investors worried that the Federal Reserve might try to support
the falling currency by pushing interest rates higher.
   On Wall Street, declining stocks outnumbered advancing ones
nearly 11 to 1 in the worst day since the widely-followed Dow Jones
average fell 140.58 points on Jan. 8.
   The Dow industrials had climbed nearly 130 points from April 5
through Tuesday, largely on anticipation that February's trade news
would be favorable.
   The value of U.S. stocks fell by $99.7 billion in Thursday's
plunge, according to a 5,000-stock index measured by Wilshire
Associates of Santa Monica, Calif.
   In the bond market, the yield on the Treasury Department's
benchmark 30-year Treasury bond jumped to roughly 8.86 percent
Thursday, the highest since January, from 8.73 percent late
Wednesday.
   The trade report also battered major foreign markets. In London,
the Financial Times-Stock Exchange 100-stock index fell 1.3 percent
on Thursday.
   In Tokyo, stocks fell sharply at today's opening but later
recovered much of their losses. The key Nikkei Stock Average of 225
issues, down more than 250 points at one time, finished the morning
session at 26,967.83, down 143.52 from Thursday's record close.
   The dollar opened a sharp 1.7 percent lower against the Japanese
yen in Tokyo but later stabilized on reports of heavy dollar-buying
by the Bank of Japan.
   Some economists called the markets' fears an overreaction.
   ``The quality (precision) of the numbers obviously leaves
something to be desired,'' said Raymond Worseck, economist at A.G.
Edwards & Sons Inc. in St. Louis.
   The trade report indicated consumers were continuing to spend
strongly, sucking up imports, Worseck said.
   The trade deficit was the highest since the record gap of $17.6
billion in October. It was up from January's $12.4 billion gap, but
was down from a deficit of $14.4 billion in February 1987.
   ``It's just one of those glitches that keep the financial
markets interesting. The trend is still for improvement in the
trade deficit,'' said James Solloway, director of economic research
at Argus Research Corp. in St. Louis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0250 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Stocks-Analysis Bjt   04-15 0436</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stocks-Analysis, Bjt,0452</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Wall Street Stumbles In Post-Crash Recovery</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CHET CURRIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rebuilding confidence in the stock market after
the crash last October is proving to be an elusive and
time-consuming mission.
   The market's latest bid to rally collapsed on Thursday when the
Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, the best known measure of
market trends, fell 101.46 points to 2,005.64, for its
fifth-largest loss ever.
   From April 5 through Tuesday of this week, the Dow industrials
had climbed nearly 130 points, largely on anticipation of a
continuing flow of favorable news on the nation's trade balance and
the outlook for the dollar in foreign exchange.
   But the word from the Commerce Department on Thursday morning
was that the trade deficit widened in February, with imports
exceeding exports by $13.83 against $12.44 billion the month before.
   In effect, that wiped out with a single stroke the basic premise
behind the recent rally.
   Stock market analysts said persistent strength in imports, in
particular, raised fears that the Federal Reserve soon might feel
the need to tighten credit to restrain the economy as well as to
support the dollar.
   ``You got a nasty bit of news,'' said Larry Wachtel at
Prudential-Bache Securities. ``The market is saying that the
economy is too strong.''
   Wachtel also said the withdrawal from the market since last fall
of many investors frightened away by the crash had left stocks in a
fragile position, vulnerable to volatile swings.
   ``It's really a day-trader's market,'' he said. ``When we were
rallying, there wasn't a lot of volume.
   ``And when the market started to come down, there were no
buffers on the downside _ no small investors, no pension managers,
no foreign investors.''
   That leaves Wall Street in a paradoxical plight. Investors large
and small seem inclined to stay clear of the stock market until it
shows signs of greater stability.
   But it looks as though those investors' presence may be needed
if that stability is going to be attained.
   In the meantime, market analysts and professional money managers
still are groping for some indication of where the market ought to
settle out, and of what level of stock prices ``makes sense'' in
the aftermath of the crash.
   As Jay Donnaruma, an analyst at First Albany Corp. in Albany,
N.Y., put it in his latest market commentary: ``In the current
environment, all the normal road signs that usually provide one
with direction appear to have been stolen by vandals.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
   EDITOR'S NOTE: Chet Currier has reported on Wall Street for The
Associated Press since 1974.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0251 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0329EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Stocks-Collar Bjt   04-15 0594</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stocks-Collar, Bjt,0611</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dow Drop Tests 50-Point Collar, Revives Debate Over Program
Trading Limit</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The first major test of Wall Street's
computerized trading ``collar'' in braking a big fall in stock
prices is getting mixed reviews, with some calling the limit
helpful and others saying it may have worsened the drop.
   ``The collar has got some holes in it,'' Leigh Stevens, a
PaineWebber Inc. strategist, said Thursday after the Dow Jones
average tumbled 101.46 points, its fifth-worst daily decline ever.
   The slide represented more than double the 50-point swing
necessary to activate the collar, which when triggered bans the use
of New York Stock Exchange computers for so-called index arbitrage
program trading for the rest of the day.
   The drop marked the first time since the NYSE imposed the
restriction on Feb. 4 that a decline activated the 50-point
trigger. The collar took effect once before on April 6 when the
average rose 64.16 points.
   ``At the present time, it's not working,'' Peter J. DaPuzzo,
head of retail equities at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said as
selling swept the market even once the collar took effect at about
1:55 p.m. EDT.
   The limit is part of an NYSE effort to restore stability to a
market still suffering after-effects of the epic crash nearly six
months ago. Some crash studies have suggested program trading
aggravated the October plunge, and the Big Board has expressed
concern that the practice is undermining investor and regulator
confidence.
   ``It's really premature to assess whether the collar works,''
said NYSE spokeswoman Sharon Gamsin. ``It wasn't designed to stop
the Dow average from moving. We only have evidence of two days.
When we get more data, we'll analyze it. If it's necessary to take
further action, we might.''
   Some traders said they believed the collar lessened the impact
of what would have been a heavy selloff under any circumstances.
Investors rushed to dump stocks largely because of economic worries
linked to the government's report of a wider-than-expected trade
deficit for February.
   But others said the braking effects of the collar were
overwhelmed by big brokerage houses that executed sell orders
manually or used forms of program trading not covered by the
restraint. A few traders said they believed the collar actually
worsened the drop because it only left sellers in the market.
   ``Once this thing goes below 50, nobody shows up to do any
buying,'' said Joseph Barthel, a technical strategist at Butcher &
Singer Inc.
   In index arbitrage, brokers use computers to buy or sell massive
amounts of stocks in New York and the equivalent stock-index
futures in Chicago, in order to profit from price disparities.
   Although many brokerages have applauded the NYSE's limit on the
technique, others have been critical because they say it severs an
important relationship between the stock and futures markets.
   Studies of the stock crash have concluded the relationship
between financial markets was an important element in the October
crash. A presidential panel's crash study, for example, suggested
that a system of ``circuit breakers'' applying simultaneously to
all markets trading stocks or stock-index futures would help
prevent another crisis.
   ``I have a couple of problems with the whole collar concept,''
said Howard Schneider, a futures-market expert and securities
lawyer who is critical of the NYSE's post-crash strategy.
   ``Clearly, you can't disconnect the stock exchange from the
futures market. They're all one big ball of wax,'' Schneider said.
``If you have only the stock exchange with a circuit breaker, it
doesn't do a damn thing.''
</TEXT>
