<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0330EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-CornBread     04-15 0539</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Corn Bread,0556</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Researchers Hope New Corn Bread Appeals to Consumers, Helps
Farmers</HEAD>
<HEAD>Laserphoto planned</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ROBERT LEE ZIMMER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>CHAMPAIGN, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A new kind of corn bread that combines
down-home color and flavor with a firmness that stands up to
slicing could help shrink the nation's corn surplus if it goes over
well with consumers, government researchers say.
   This is not old-fashioned corn bread that crumbles into the ham
and beans. This firm new loaf _ made from flour that's half wheat
and half finely ground corn _ can be sliced, buttered, toasted and
used for sandwiches.
   ``It gives people a new bread product, and it could enable
farmers to sell more of their corn at a higher price,'' said U.S.
Department of Agriculture food technologist Kathleen Warner.
   The bread was developed at the USDA laboratory in Peoria. Warner
said the goal was to develop a bread that used as much corn flour
as possible ``so it would make a big impact on using up surplus
corn supplies.''
   As it turned out, the ideal flour formulation was half corn and
half wheat, with extra wheat gluten to improve its structure. The
dough is leavened with yeast.
   Traditional corn bread is made mainly from coarser cornmeal and
baking powder.
   Warner said the new corn bread resembles a home-baked or
specialty bakery loaf rather than typical supermarket sandwich
bread. But she said wholesale bakers could modify the formula ``to
make it lighter and fluffier'' if that is the kind of loaf their
customers want.
   ``The next step is to encourage industry to try this and find a
market for it,'' Warner said.
   The $16 billion-a-year wholesale bread- and cake-baking industry
uses about 100 million pounds of flour annually, according to
Gordon Davidson, editor of the Milling and Baking News.
   ``I can't even predict what consumer interest would be'' for the
new corn bread, said William Hoover, president of the American
Institute of Baking. ``I like corn bread, so if it has that flavor
it might appeal to some of the public.''
   Hoover noted that sales of a new product usually reflect the
amount of money spent on marketing and advertising. Bakers would
have to believe the new corn bread is ``delightfully good tasting''
to make a major investment in promoting it, he said.
   During the 1970s, Purity Baking Co. of Decatur marketed a
product called Country Corn Bread, using a smaller percentage of
corn flour. President Chuck Webb said that version had a rich
golden color, and because corn flour holds moisture well it also
stayed fresh longer.
   ``It is just one of those items that was very successful at the
time, but tastes change and it eventually was replaced,'' said Webb.
   ``People today are searching for new varieties'' and this could
be a good time to offer a new kind of corn bread, he said.
   A popular new corn bread also could help the nation's dry
millers, who use about 2 percent of the U.S. corn crop, said Betsy
Faga, president of the American Corn Millers Federation.
   ``The industry certainly is looking for new uses for dry milled
corn _ every possible outlet,'' said Faga. ``This certainly could
be a new one for them.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0253 </DOCNO>
