<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SocieteGenerale     04-15 0581</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Societe Generale,0601</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shareholders Stall De Bendetti's Bid For Societe Generale</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Societe Generale de Belgique SA
shareholders have dealt Carlo De Benedetti a setback in his
attempted takeover of the giant holding company, but the Italian
financier still wields some clout over the enterprise.
   At a 12-hour special shareholders meeting on Thursday,
shareholders spurned the bid by De Benedetti and two allies to win
seats on the Societe Generale board of directors. The trio got
votes from only 44.5 percent of the shares registered, and needed
51 percent to win election to the board.
   But because he commands a huge block of shares, De Benedetti
retains much clout within the company and may win yet a board seat.
   ``Today's votes will not be for the long term,'' De Benedetti
told the more than 1,150 shareholders before the vote, which was
taken at a meeting held in a tent next to Societe Generale's head
office.
   ``In one week, one month, six months or one year, we will play a
major role in Societe Generale. Without me...no stable management
of Societe Generale is possible.''
   Management of Societe Generale, Belgium's biggest holding
company, was relieved after the marathon meeting.
   ``We fought it out. There was a winner and a loser,'' said
Director Etienne Davignon.
   Shareholders added 12 members _ all rivals of De Benedetti _ to
the board of directors with a majority of 55 percent of the vote.
The previous board had 11 directors.
   Right up through the start of the meeting, De Benedetti had met
with his rivals to seek a compromise. But the talks failed when De
Benedetti continued insisting on control over day-to-day management
of the venerable, 166-year-old Societe Generale, which has stakes
in some 1,300 companies worldwide.
   De Benedetti, who sparked the heated takeover battle for Societe
Generale three months ago, had sought election along with two
allies, including Andre Leysen, chairman of Belgium's Gevaert NV.
   Societe Generale nominated the remaining 12 candidates, allies
of France's Cie. Financiere de Suez and Groupe AG. The two
companies, heading an alliance of smaller Belgian, French,
Luxembourg and Swiss interests, led the fight against De Benedetti.
   The vote indicated how many shares each faction controls.
   Under Belgian law, shareholders are not required to disclose the
amount of their holdings, leaving only speculation over which group
holds a majority.
   De Benedetti, who spent some $1.7 billion to raise his Societe
Generale holdings, claims he and his allies control 48 percent of
the company.
   Suez and Groupe AG say they hold 50.7 percent, after spending
about $850 million to beef up their stake.
   At Thursday's meeting, a De Benedetti aide made an official
statement complaining about ``irregularities'' in the voting,
including extensive delays in tallying the vote caused by computer
malfunctions.
   Analysts said the protest may have been made to allow De
Benedetti to protest the vote in court, although there were no
immediate threats of legal action.
   De Benedetti also is fighting a legal battle over Societe
Generale's issuance of 12 million new shares in an attempt to
dilute his stake. The stock was issued Jan. 18, the day De
Benedetti launched his hostile bid.
   De Benedetti, the chairman of Italy's Olivetti SpA, wants to
turn Societe Generale _ which has interests in mining, engineering,
manufacturing, chemicals, banking, and other areas _ into a
pan-European holding company before 1992. That year, the European
Economic Community is to remove regulatory curbs on the free
movement of goods and services.
</TEXT>
