<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-TexasAir-Finances Bjt   04-15 0680</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Texas Air-Finances, Bjt,0701</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Federal Inquiry Will Examine Texas Air's Complex Financial
Structure</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARCY GORDON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The squad of federal investigators probing Texas
Air Corp. faces the task of unraveling a labyrinthine corporate
structure adopted by the nation's biggest airline company.
   The Department of Transportation on Wednesday charged 25
accountants, auditors, economists and financial analysts with
delving into a complex structure that has steeped the ailing
carrier in controversy and made it the target of labor union
hostility.
   Houston-based Texas Air, which commands 20 percent of the U.S.
market, is the parent company of major carriers Eastern Airlines
and Continental Airlines.
   A key figure in the government's probe will be Texas Air
Chairman Frank Lorenzo who aggressively built the company from a
small intrastate carrier into an airline empire. Unions and other
critics have accused Lorenzo of siphoning off Eastern and
Continental assets into the parent company.
   Recent Texas Air filings with the Securities and Exchange
Commission indicated that both Eastern and Continental ``are under
substantial, increasing financial pressure,'' Transportation
Secretary Jim Burnley said in announcing the investigation.
   Documents indicate, for example, that Texas Air's cash reserves
were drained last year at a rate of more than $1 million a day, and
that the company has around $7 billion in liabilities related to
leasing planes.
   The government's financial probe will examine the corporation's
management and business practices and the relationships between the
parent, Eastern and Continental, said DOT General Counsel B. Wayne
Vance. The department's deputy general counsel, Rosalind Knapp,
will head the investigation.
   While Texas Air controls Eastern and Continental, Houston-based
Continental itself is the parent of other Lorenzo acquisitions:
Frontier Airlines, People Express and New York Air. All three have
ceased operating _ Frontier is in bankruptcy _ but Continental has
absorbed their assets.
   Texas Air also operates several commuter carriers: Rocky
Mountain Airways, Britt Airways, Bar Harbor Airlines and
Provincetown-Boston Airlines.
   Together, the Texas Air carriers have a huge debt of around $5.4
billion, but Lorenzo has set up a corporate structure that
insulates the parent itself from most of the burden. The parent
company sustained record losses of $466 million last year.
   The Wall Street Journal recently likened the complex corporate
architecture to a house of many rooms: Every room has a paying
tenant and a bank can foreclose on an individual room, but not on
the whole house. The landlord has many partners, but no one can
challenge his management of the property.
   The setup allows cash to move upstream from loss-making Texas
Air units to the parent _ in the form of management fees, rents on
planes and airport gates, commissions on fuel purchases and others.
   In its order for an investigation, the DOT said a number of
financial transactions between the parent and Eastern and
Continental ``raise questions concerning whether substantial funds
and other resources are being diverted from the air carrier
subsidiaries.''
   The department questioned, for example:
   _Texas Air shifting Eastern's profitable computer reservation
system into a separate subsidiary in exchange for a note ``which
may be less than the system's fair market value.''
   _Eastern paying ``substantial fees'' for management services,
fuel purchases and other activities provided by the parent company.
   _Eastern accepting a no-interest note, instead of cash, for $16
million in reimbursements owed to the airline as part of its
acquisition by Texas Air.
   _Texas Air borrowing $25 million from Eastern in March 1987 in
exchange for an unsecured note at a time when Eastern was having
cash flow problems.
   Texas Air recently proposed to spin off Eastern's profitable
Northeast shuttle service in exchange for an infusion of $225
million in cash and securities for the strapped airline, but that
attempt has been blocked by federal courts.
   While the DOT looks into the financial condition of Texas Air,
Eastern and Continental, the Federal Aviation Administration is
undertaking a stringent safety investigation of Miami-based
Eastern. The FAA on Wednesday fined Eastern $823,000 because of
``recurring trends'' of violations of safety regulations, and on
Thursday temporarily grounded five Eastern planes for minor safety
violations.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0255 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0721EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f PM-MercedesIncentives     04-15 0431</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mercedes Incentives,0447</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mercedes Offers Trip Tix For Car Pickups</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL J. WAKIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Mercedes-Benz of North America wants you to
have a nice vacation in Europe.
   So the luxury automaker is offering free plane tickets on one
condition: that the trip include the purchase of a Mercedes in West
Germany.
   Since March 30, Mercedes has been giving two round-trip economy
plane tickets, or one business-class ticket, on Pan Am or Lufthansa
flights to customers who purchase and pick up autos from its
factory near Stuttgart.
   As under most European pick-up programs, the company pays for
shipment of the car back to the United States and for a 2.5 percent
import duty.
   The net savings, according to spokesman A.B. Schuman at
Mercedes' U.S. headquarters in Montvale, is about 8 percent off the
retail price.
   Schuman said the free offer caters to overseas buyers who
frequently combine a European tour with their auto purchase, which
in turn saves the cost of renting an automobile.
   European delivery has been part of luxury-car marketing since
the early 1960s, Schuman said, and Mercedes' current gimmick is
part of a long-term marketing strategy.
   Mercedes sold 2,090 cars to Americans in West Germany last year,
out of a total 89,900 purchased for use in the United States.
   In an increasingly competitive luxury car market, Mercedes'
ticket offer has more to do with gaining a competitive edge than
with boosting European delivery sales, said spokesman Thomas O.
McGurn at rival BMW of North America in Montvale.
   Schuman said it was too early to tell the results of the
Mercedes' program, but a sales manager at the nation's largest
Mercedes dealership said he was pleased.
   ``It's done the job here,'' said Jerry Carter at Downtown L.A.
Motors in Los Angeles. Four buyers lured by the ticket offer made
deals on Wednesday and one called last weekend, when advertisements
for the program began appearing, Carter said.
   The ticket offer is one example of how luxury car makers are
competing for buyers, who have become reluctant because of
confusion over the new tax laws that went into effect in 1987, the
October stock market crash and the continuing decline of the
dollar, which has boosted foreign car prices, said BMW's McGurn.
   BMW, for instance, has boosted its advertising and is offering a
lower percentage financing on leasing rates.
   Of 87,800 domestic sales, 1,610 BMWs were picked up in Europe,
McGurn said.
   Saab-Scania of America Inc., based in Orange, Conn., reported
741 European deliveries for 1987 from four European locations, said
spokesman Jim Ventrilio.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880415-0256 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0345EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-National-Fairchild     04-15 0639</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-National-Fairchild,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Sporck Says National-Fairchild Merger A Huge Success</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVE WILSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTA CLARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The hard rain that fell on National
Semiconductor Corp. ceremonies honoring Silicon Valley pioneer
Fairchild Semiconductor Corp. has been practically the only thing
to dampen the recent merger of the two companies.
   The union of the two chipmakers has come off much more smoothly
than many analysts and rivals thought it would, without the
bloodbath of personnel cuts and violent organizational disruptions
predicted by some.
   National acquired struggling Fairchild on Oct. 1 for $122
million, after political pressure nixed a $200 million buyout by
Japan's Fujitsu Ltd., and found a silicon treasure trove, according
to National boss Charles E. Sporck.
   There were layoffs as the combined companies trimmed from 38,000
to 36,000 workers and there were ``ruffled feathers,'' Sporck
admits, as employees made adjustments and, in some cases, switched
jobs.
   But he says that a dynamic company has emerged from the merger,
with a broad range of products, solid research departments and
worldwide clout.
   ``I'm unaware of any other combination of two companies where a
merger's been pulled off so well in such a short period of time,''
Sporck said Thursday in his first interview on the merger since
last fall.
   Sporck said National will post revenue of about $2.5 billion
when its 1988 fiscal year ends May 31, enabling the company to leap
from 11th to fifth among world chip companies.
   He also estimated National would surpass the 12 percent growth
rate he thinks the industry will post over the next year as it
continues its recovery from a severe slump.
   ``The sum of the two companies is exceeding the parts
involved,'' said Michael Boss, analyst for San Jose-based market
research firm Dataquest Inc.
   ``It wasn't apparent from the figures for 1987,'' Boss said,
``but we really expect this to be a very good year for National. We
see some very good blending together of technologies and markets.''
   Sporck said National got more than it bargained for.
   ``Our estimates were conservative, both in terms of the
financial impact and technology,'' he said. ``There was a
perception on our part, as well as the industry's that Fairchild
had a somewhat empty basket in terms of product. It wasn't until
after we truly started looking seriously that we realized that was
a misconception.''
   Sporck said he particularly is impressed with Fairchild's high
speed and custom chips used for supercomputers and military
applications. Added to National's other lines of chips, the
combined company can offer customers a wide range of technologies.
   ``There is a trend among customers to reduce the number of
suppliers,'' he said. ``It saves money dealing with fewer people,
and they realize, as we do, that more profitable relations occur
when the two engineering organizations work closely together.
   ``It's a benefit we really didn't understand when we first
started the Fairchild involvement.''
   Huddled under golf umbrellas, Fairchild's eight founders
gathered among about 2,000 guests Thursday as Sporck praised it as
``the granddaddy of all semiconductor companies'' and dedicated the
new $75 million Fairchild Research Center.
   It was National's way of preserving the name and spirit of the
company that spawned Silicon Valley's biggest chipmakers, including
Intel, Advanced Micro Devices and National.
   ``Fairchild had tremendously talented people and an unusual,
free-swinging environment,'' said Sporck, who joined Fairchild as a
production manager and rose to head of the semiconductor division
before he left to join National in 1967.
   ``They were prepared to accept unusual behavior from people
given they have talent,'' he said. ``One of the negatives of that,
of course, is we bred a lot of entrepreneurs and they went out and
started a lot of companies, which wasn't necessarily in the best
interests of Fairchild. But all of us have a tinge of nostalgia for
Fairchild.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
