<DOCNO> AP880415-0257 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 0348EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SteelImports     04-15 0335</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Steel Imports,0346</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steel Imports Down In February</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Steel imports declined in February to the
target set by the Reagan administration for its quota program,
except for metal imported by U.S. companies for rolling on their
own mills.
   But American producers said Thursday that the 1.9 million tons
imported in February in both categories represented the highest
single-month level since November 1986.
   ``Increasing volume of semi-finished steel imports, badly needed
by domestic rolling mills themselves, continues a trend evident
since the beginning of 1988,'' said Erwin L. Klein, president of
the New York-based American Institute for Imported Steel.
   The AIIS is composed largely of European steelmakers who sell
products in the United States. The Washington-based American Iron
and Steel Institute represents domestic companies. Both intepret
U.S. Commerce Department data separately.
   The importers said February steel imports, excluding 284,900
tons of semi-finished metal headed for U.S. mills, totaled 1.6
million tons, or 18.8 percent of the domestic market. They said
that's close to the 18.5 percent goal set by President Reagan in
launching the quota program in late 1984.
   Including semi-finished steel, February imports represented 22.1
percent of the U.S. market. That was up from 21.8 percent in
January, when 1.8 million tons entered the country, but down from
25 percent in February 1987, when 1.8 million tons entered a
smaller domestic market, the AIIS said Thursday.
   The U.S. producers calculate the administration's goal as 20.2
percent of the market, including semi-finished steel.
   The importers said semi-finished steel represented 15 percent of
February's total imports.
   ``Even these sharply increased semi-finished steel imports are
still unable to satisfy demand, as indicated by escalating
petitions of American rolling mills to the U.S. Commerce Department
for short-supply allocation,'' said Klein, vice chairman of the
import firm STEELINTER USA Inc.
   The short supply petitions are requests for permission to import
steel in excess of the quotas, which the administration negotiated
at the request of the domestic producers. Unless extended, the
quotas will expire in September 1989.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
