<1ST_LINE>r f PM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh     04-15 0258</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Wheeling-Pittsburgh,0267</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Steelmaker To Pay $85 Million In Pension Agreement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WHEELING, W.Va. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh Steel Corp. has
agreed in principle to pay $85 million to the Pension Benefit
Guaranty Corp. to settle all pension insurance claims against the
company.
   Under the settlement announced Thursday, which is subject to
approval by the U.S. Bankruptcy Court, Wheeling-Pittsburgh will pay
about $60 million in cash and a secured note for $25 million upon
confirmation of the troubled steelmaker's bankruptcy reorganization
plan.
   The settlement is over PBGC claims stemming from the termination
of seven Wheeling-Pittsburgh pension plans serving 21,500 workers
in November 1985, seven months after the company filed for
protection under Chapter 11 of the federal bankruptcy law.
   PBGC, a government agency that insures pension plan participants
against losses, says it has claims totaling more than $600 million,
although the claims are limited by law to 30 percent of the
company's net worth.
   In a news release issued from Washington, PBGC said the
settlement granted it full recovery of its original claims for
unpaid contributions due to the pension plans during the period the
company filed for bankruptcy protection.
   ``This agreement provides PBGC a substantial recovery, but
allows the company to move ahead with its reorganization,'' sid
Royal S. Dellinger, the agency's chief negotiator. ``It also
confirms that failure to meet pension promises is very costly.
   Wheeling-Pittsburgh stated that it was ``pleased that the
parties were able to resolve their differences without further
litigation, and that one of the major obstacles to a plan of
reorganization has been removed.''
</TEXT>
