<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Kodak-Panama     04-15 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Kodak-Panama,0273</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Kodak Furloughs Employees in Panama</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ROCHESTER, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Eastman Kodak Co. has given its workforce
in Panama a 15-day paid furlough because of the extreme difficulty
in doing business there, a company spokesman said today.
   The catalyst for the shutdown of Kodak's marketing facility,
retail film and camera shops and mini-lab processing centers was
last Friday's economic sanctions imposed by President Reagan, said
Kodak spokesman Henry Kaska.
   ``We weren't ordered to close, but it just doesn't make sense to
stay open,'' Kaska said. ``We are not permitted to pay our utility
bill. We can't pay the phone bill. We were also concerned about the
security of our people traveling in that country.''
   The sanctions were ordered April 8 by Reagan in an effort to
force military leader Manuel Antonio Noriega to surrender his hold
on the Central American country.
   They include prohibiting payments to the Noriega regime by all
U.S. citizens and organizations in Panama, freezing the U.S. assets
of the Panamanian government, and prohibiting any person or company
in the United States from making any payments to the regime.
   Kaska said he didn't have an exact figure on the number of Kodak
employees, but estimated it was less than 1,000. He said the
furlough went into effect Tuesday.
   ``After the 15 days we'll reevaluate and reassess and determine
whether there should be another furlough,'' Kaska said. ``We hope
the situation will stabilize within a month.''
   He said Kodak would continue to service its copiers in the
Panama Canal Zone and will keep its photo processing mini-labs open
there.
</TEXT>
