<HEAD>Grain, Soybean Futures Open Steady To Lower</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened steady to
slightly lower today on the Chicago Board of Trade.
   Analysts said prices could fall on more profit-taking after last
week's sharp gains. But any early selling pressure was limited by a
continuation of the wave of buying that ended Thursday's session.
   ``There's not a whole lot going on,'' said Joel Karlin, research
analyst for Research Department Inc. in Chicago. ``We might have
some general liquidation today.''
   The grain markets were a bit jittery after Thursday's
stock-market plunge. The Dow Jones industrial average opened only a
few points below Thursday's close, but was down nearly 25 points by
mid-morning.
   In early trading, wheat was unchanged to 1\ cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.15\ a bushel; corn was \ cent
lower to \ cent higher with May at $2.04\ a bushel; oats were \
cent to } cent higher with May at $1.62\ a bushel; soybeans were 3{
cents lower to { cent higher with May at $6.76 a bushel.
