<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Stocks, 1st Ld-Writethru,0231</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>London Stocks Close Lower But Above Worst Levels</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: updates with close.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices closed lower Friday, but well above
their worst levels of the day as bargain-hunting and takeover
rumors helped the market regain some lost ground.
   The Financial Times-Stock Exchange index of 100 selected stocks
fell 8.6 points, or 0.5 percent, to 1,778.6.
   The index fell 24.1 points at the opening, but dealers said the
real low for the day came in trading before the official opening,
when the index was down as much as 38 points.
   Volume was moderate at 472.9 million shares, down from 517.3
million on Thursday.
   Share prices were marked down sharply from the outset of
trading, following Thursday's plunge on Wall Street, when the Dow
Jones industrial average lost more than 100 points.
   But British institutional buyers were attracted by the low
prices and the market rose steadily in the morning until it was
down 4.6 points in the early afternoon.
   Weakness in the early going on Wall Street took London prices
down from their best levels.
   However, dealers were heartened by the market's resilience in
the face of New York's sell-off Thursday.
   ``We're coming into the area where the market is looking
attractive to fund managers,'' said Michael Howell, European
equities strategist at Salomon Brothers International.
</TEXT>
