<1ST_LINE>u f BC-Dollar-Gold     04-15 0300</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Dollar-Gold,0315</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Retreats Further on New Economic Data, Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against major foreign
currencies on Friday after another disappointing set of U.S.
economic indicators, but dealers said central bank intervention
tempered its fall.
   The pound rose strongly as investors again moved in to take
advantage of higher British interest rates.
   Gold prices moved up around the globe.
   The dollar was hurt by news that U.S. producer prices increased
a larger-than-expected 0.6 percent during March and that industrial
output climbed 0.1 percent, less than expected, during the month.
   However, any further fall in the dollar was tempered by reported
intervention from the Deutsche Bundesbank, the U.S. Federal Reserve
and the Bank of England.
   ``The dealers didn't wish to take on the central banks,'' one
trader said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends as Europe's begins, the
dollar fell 2.02 yen to a closing 124.13. Later, in London, it was
quoted at 123.90 yen.
   In London, it cost $1.8890 to buy one pound, dearer than $1.8755
Thursday.
   Other late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday's
rates, included: 1.6605 West German marks, down from 1.6635; 1.3720
Swiss francs, down from 1.3745; 5.6325 French francs, down from
5.6390; 1.8630 Dutch guilders, down from 1.8680; 1,232.50 Italian
lire, down from 1,244.00; and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, down from
1.2368.
   Gold rose in London to a late bid price of $456.25 a troy ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $451.
   In Zurich, gold was higher, closing at a bid $455.50, compared
with $450.50 late Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $5.45 to close at a bid $454.93.
   Silver bullion prices rose on the London market where the metal
was trading at a late bid price of $6.49 a troy ounce, compared
with Thursday's $6.43.
</TEXT>
