<DOCNO> AP880415-0278 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1452EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a f BC-WeeklyBonds Adv16-17   04-15 0699</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Weekly Bonds, Adv 16-17,0725</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$adv 16</NOTE>
<NOTE>$adv 17</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Weekend Editions April 16-17</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bond Market Jolted by Unexpected Economic Strength</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The bond market got an earful of economic news
this past week, and didn't like a lot of what it heard.
   ``It was a week of surprises, all of them negative,'' said
William Griggs of the financial consulting firm Griggs & Santow
Inc. in New York.
   The reports on March retail sales and wholesale prices and the
February trade deficit indicated the economy is growing faster than
post-stock market crash pessimists had expected and that inflation
may be accelerating.
   Faster economic growth and rising prices are the enemy in the
bond market, and prices slumped on the news, pushing long-term
yields toward their highest levels since they exceeded 9 percent in
mid-January.
   By midafternoon Friday, the prices of some long-term Treasury
bonds were priced to yield 8.93 percent, up from 8.68 percent at
the end of the previous week and from 8.3 percent in early February.
   The government reported Wednesday that retail sales rose 0.8
percent in March, stronger than most analysts had expected. ``It
was another indication that the consumer has the ability to spend
and is doing it,'' Griggs said.
   More disconcerting was news the next day that the nation's trade
deficit had widened to $13.8 billion in February. Most analysts had
expected a contraction in the deficit to the $11 billion to $12
billion range.
   Continued strength in imports raised the possibility that
inflation would accelerate, possibly prompting the Federal Reserve
Board to tighten credit conditions in an effort to ward off higher
prices.
   Adding to inflation concerns was Friday's report that wholesale
prices rose 0.6 percent in March or about twice as fast as most
analysts had expected.
   ``That was one more bit of bad news that the market could have
done without,'' said Elliott Platt, research director for
Donaldson, Lufkin & Jenrette Securities Corp. in New York.
   He said next month's wholesale price figure could be even worse
if oil prices continue their recent rise.
   Most economists caution against reading too much into any single
economic report, noting that they are often subject to revision.
   But Robert Chandross, chief economist for Lloyds Bank PLC in New
York, said the rise in wholesale prices nonetheless indicates
``something is going on, on the inflation front that is pretty
negative.''
   ``I had thought April was going to be difficult, and this raises
the likelihood that the Fed will have to tighten further,'' he
said. ``They may not do it right away but if we get some strong
employment figures for April, it would leave them no alternative.''
   Sun Won Sohn, chief economist for Norwest Corp. in Minneapolis,
said the series of economic reports ``was extremely disappointing''
because the consensus estimates were wrong in each case.
   Sohn said he had expected long-term rates would decline in May,
but said the latest reports prompted him to delay that projection.
He is now looking for long-term rates to edge up to 9 percent and
not begin falling until July or August. He expects long-term rates
will be as low as 8.3 percent by November.
   DLJ's Platt expects long-term rates will rise as high as 9.25
percent by the end of the month, but then decline as low as 8
percent by early summer.
   But Griggs is decidedly more pessimistic. He said the gyrations
in the dollar have introduced a new element of risk for foreign
buyers of U.S. securities, and that rates will rise to compensate
them for that.
   Combined with the federal government's continuing strong
borrowing demands and an expected acceleration of inflation, Griggs
said he expects long-term rates will rise to 10 percent or more by
the end of the year.
   Chandross is looking for long-term rates to stay in a narrow
range, rising to 9 percent before slipping to 8.75 percent during
May.
   ``There is enough skittishness in the economy right now that
there is a self-correcting mechanism at work under which rising
rates dampen certain kinds of economic activity and that leads
rates to fall,'' he said.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv Weekend Editions April 16-17</NOTE>
