<HEAD>Soybean Futures Plunge On Heavy Fund Selling</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices fell sharply Friday on the
Chicago Board of Trade amid heavy liquidation by speculative
investment funds. The grains also closed lower.
   Analysts said Chicago-based C&D Commodities, the largest
speculative firm on the floor, led the decline by selling large
numbers of contracts for soybeans and soybean products that it had
purchased in recent weeks.
   The funds were reacting to a number of factors, including good
harvest weather for the South American soybean crop, disappointing
export sales last week and relatively high cash prices for soybeans
and soybean products, said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed
analyst for Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   ``We're just way out of whack with prices of cottonseed meal and
corn,'' he said.
   At the close, wheat was 2{ cents to 3} cents lower with the
contract for delivery in May at $3.12} a bushel; corn was 1\ cents
to 2\ cents lower with May at $2.03 a bushel; oats were } cent to
1{ cents lower with May at $1.60 a bushel; soybeans were 14 cents
to 16{ cents lower with May at $6.61 a bushel.
