<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2035EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-EconomyGlance     04-15 0464</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy Glance,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mixed Signals, Mixed Reactions in Markets</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Here, at a glance, are developments in the economic picture
Friday:
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WHOLESALE PRICES</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Energy and food prices shot upward as wholesale prices jumped
0.6 percent in March, the biggest increase in 11 months. The
increase erased a 0.2 percent drop in Feburary.
   If the March rate held for 12 months, the annual inflation rate
would be 7 percent, compared with 2.2 percent for all of 1987.
   Overall, wholesale prices rose at an annual rate of 3.1 percent
from January through March.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>INDUSTRIAL PRODUCTION</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Production at the nation's factories, mines and utilities edged
up 0.1 percent in March, somewhat counterbalancing signs that
inflation is reheating.
   Gains in production of autos and business equipment offset
declines in construction supplies and consumer goods other than
cars.
   The slight March advance followed no change in February and,
according to economists, indicates that the pickup in wholesale
prices may not be sustained.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>BUSINESS INVESTMENT</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Businesses plan to increase capital spending by 8 percent this
year to $419.9 billion, raising hopes manufacturers will expand
factory capacity enough to ease inflation pressures. It would be
the best gain since a 9.6 percent rise in 1985.
   Businesses spent $388.7 billion last year, a 1.7 percent
increase over 1986.
   The estimate, based on a survey completed in March, represented
an increase over a November survey, when businesses said they
planned to spend 7.3 percent more.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>WALL STREET</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices were widely mixed, showing signs of steadying after
Thursday's steep slide. The Dow Jones average rose 8.29 to
2,013.93, reducing its loss for the week to 76.26 points.
   At the same time, interest rates rose in the credit markets,
pushing yields on long-term Treasury bonds close to the 8.95
percent level.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>DOLLAR</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   The dollar finished lower against other currencies after the
wholesale prices report, but dealers said central bank intervention
tempered its fall.
   In Tokyo, the dollar fell 2.02 yen to a closing 124.13. Later,
in London, it was quoted at 123.90 yen.
   In London, it cost $1.8890 to buy 1 pound, higher than $1.8755
Thursday.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>FINANCE MINISTERS</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   World finance leaders ended a tumultuous meeting of the
International Monetary Fund with words of assurance to nervous
financial markets and further efforts to rescue the U.S. dollar.
   The dollar's rout shattered the optimistic tone the finance
ministers hoped to impart in their first high-level discussions
since the Oct. 19 stock market collapse. The group's final
communique predicted continued growth for the world economy this
year at a ``steady, moderate'' pace.
   World Bank President Barber Conable said the overriding issue
facing the two lending organizations was reducing the poor
countries' debt burden, estimated to total $1.245 trillion by the
end of this year.
</TEXT>
