<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1706EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Texaco     04-15 0701</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Texaco,0725</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texaco Reinstates Dividend; To Sell $2 Billion More in Assets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARIANN CAPRINO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Texaco Inc. announced Friday it will resume
paying a quarterly dividend and will sell off an additional $2
billion in assets as part of its restructuring.
   At its first meeting since Texaco emerged from Chapter 11
federal bankruptcy court reorganization on April 7, the oil giant's
board of directors authorized a 75-cent quarterly dividend, a move
analysts said is intended to bolster shareholder support for the
current management team.
   In closing trading on the New York Stock Exchange, Texaco jumped
$1.62{ to $48.75.
   Texaco had been barred from paying dividends after it filed for
bankruptcy protection on April 12, 1987, in the wake of its epic
legal battle with Pennzoil Co. The dividend will be paid June 10 to
shareholders of record May 3.
   In addition to authorizing the dividend, directors said they
planned to sell off $5 billion in assets to help reduce the
company's debt load.
   Texaco said in its 1987 annual report that it hoped to raise at
least $3 billion through the sale of assets, but Friday's action
increased that amount by $2 billion.
   James W. Kinnear, Texaco's president and chief executive
officer, said in a statement that the resumption of dividends ``at
a substantial rate demonstrates Texaco's confidence that this
expanded restructuring will enable us to build a more profitable
company on a solid core of our most productive assets.''
   While Texaco can afford the roughly $726 million a year in
dividend payments, experts noted that the extra expense will eat up
nearly 100 percent of the company's projected earnings for the year.
   The $3-a-share annual dividend ``is not justified by Texaco's
current earnings prospects,'' said Bruce Lazier, vice president for
energy investments at Prescott Ball & Turben Inc. ``They probably
will not earn much more than the $3 (a share) rate.''
   Lazier called the dividend decision a ``defensive move''
designed to offer shareholders an incentive to ``ride along with
current management'' rather than side with corporate raider Carl C.
Icahn, Texaco's largest shareholder and sharpest critic.
   ``For shareholders hoping for liquidation, this is a nail in
that coffin,'' Lazier said, referring to rumors that Texaco would
have been dismembered if Icahn won control. He unsuccessfully
sought a board seat.
   Speculation had been brewing in recent weeks that Texaco would
take some action to boost the value of its stock, so Friday's
announcement was not a complete surprise.
   ``I think (the dividend) will quell a lot of shareholder''
dissent, said James Van Alen, an oil analyst at Janney Montgomery
Scott in Philadelphia.
   As part of its asset sale, Texaco said it would dispose of
unidentified ``producing, manufacturing and marketing assets, both
domestic and overseas.''
   Last week Texaco confirmed it is negotiating to sell its
Deutsche Texaco AG subsidiary, which operates 1,903 gas stations in
West Germany. Officials said the operation could fetch as much as
$1.7 billion.
   Texaco previously announced plans to sell 60 million barrels of
U.S. oil and natural gas reserves.
   Kinnear said in a statement issued from Texaco's headquarters in
White Plains, N.Y., that the asset sales would serve to
``de-emphasize our presence in manufacturing and marketing.''
   He said the company also would ``pursue rigorous programs to
streamline management and to set and achieve strict operating and
financial objectives.''
   Under a reorganization plan approved March 23 by a federal
bankruptcy court judge, Texaco transferred $3 billion to Pennzoil
on April 7 to settle its 4-year legal battle with the Houston-based
company.
   Texaco had filed for protection from its creditors under Chapter
11 of federal bankruptcy laws to avoid having to post a potentially
ruinous multibillion-dollar security bond while appealing a $10
billion damage judgment awarded to Pennzoil by a Houston jury in
November 1985. The award stemmed from Texaco's acquisition of Getty
Oil Co. after Getty had agreed to sell part of its assets to
Pennzoil.
   Also at the board meeting, former PPG Industries Inc. Chairman
L. Stanton Williams was elected to the board of directors to
replace Elvis Mason, who resigned. Mason is the managing partner of
Mason Best Co., a privately held merchant banking company based in
Dallas.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
