<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Dollar-Gold     04-15 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Dollar-Gold,0566</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Mixed on New Economic Data, Gold Prices Rise</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The dollar closed mixed against major foreign
currencies Friday amid speculation that interest rates would soon
rise.
   Gold prices increased. Republic National Bank of New York quoted
a bid of $455.25 for a troy ounce of gold as of 4 p.m. EDT, up from
$452.65 late Thursday.
   The government's announcement of a 0.6 percent increase in
wholesale prices for March was viewed as mildly bullish and had a
stabilizing influence on the dollar, said Dan Holland, a trader at
Discount Corp.
   Traders believed the Federal Reserve might be moved to tighten
credit _ thereby raising interest rates _ to counter a surge in
inflation.
   Higher interest rates would have a calming effect on the dollar,
which fell sharply on Thursday after the government released
disappointing balance of trade figures.
   Another government report Friday, of a 0.1 percent in industrial
production, produced market speculation that companies were buying
foreign machinery to increase their output, Holland said. Traders
believe higher output would lead to increased exports, and
eventually a shrinkage in the nation's trade deficit.
   The Commerce Department said Thursday the deficit widened to
$13.8 billion in February. Financial markets had expected the gap
to narrow.
   Holland described trading Friday as quiet.
   In Europe, the dollar fell, but central bank intervention
tempered its slide, dealers said.
   While American markets interpreted Friday's economic figures as
positive for the dollar, overseas traders saw them in a negative
light and sold dollars. The wholesale price figure was larger than
expected and the industrial output number was lower than
anticipated.
   In Tokyo, where trading ended before the figures were released,
the dollar fell 2.02 yen to a closing 124.13. Later, in London, it
was quoted at 123.90 yen and in New York, it rose to 123.80 yen
from 123.725 yen late Thursday.
   In London, it cost $1.8890 to buy one pound, higher than $1.8755
Thursday. In later New York trading, sterling rose to $1.9003 from
$1.8739.
   Other late dollar rates in New York, compared with late
Thursday's prices, included: 1.66095 West German marks, down from
1.66275; 1.3725 Swiss francs, up from 1.3720; 5.6345 French francs,
up from 5.6325; 1,232.625 Italian lire, down from 1,233.00; and
1.2333 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2365.
   Late dollar rates in Europe, compared with late Thursday: 1.6605
West German marks, down from 1.6635; 1.3720 Swiss francs, down from
1.3745; 5.6325 French francs, down from 5.6390; 1.8630 Dutch
guilders, down from 1.8680; 1,232.50 Italian lire, down from
1,244.00; and 1.2335 Canadian dollars, down from 1.2368.
   Gold rose on the Commodity Exchange in New York, closing at
$455.90 a troy ounce, compared with $452.65 late Thursday.
   In London, bullion rose to a late bid price of $456.25 an ounce,
compared with late Thursday's $451. In Zurich, gold was higher,
closing at a bid $455.50 an ounce, compared with $450.50 late
Thursday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $5.45 to close at a bid $454.93
an ounce.
   Silver rose on the Comex in New York. It closed at $6.455 a troy
ounce, up from $6.325 late Thursday.
   Silver also rose on the London market where the metal was
trading at a late bid price of $6.49 an ounce, compared with
Thursday's $6.43.
</TEXT>
