<1ST_LINE>u f AM-OilPrices     04-15 0214</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Oil Prices,0222</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Rise Again</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil prices continued to advance Friday in light
trading, reaching the highest levels since December.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, the May-delivery price for
West Texas Intermediate crude, which closed up 18 cents per barrel
Thursday, rose another 7 cents to $18.37. It was the highest since
a Dec. 11 close of $18.31 per 42-gallon barrel.
   Among refined products traded on the exchange, wholesale heating
oil rose .24 cent a gallon to 49.75 cents after a 0.49 cent rise
Thursday, and wholesale unleaded gasoline rose 0.25 cent a gallon
to 52.61 cents after falling .06 cent Thursday.
   Traders said Friday's gains were based largely on internal
market influences rather than any outside news.
   ``What you have today is more of an absence of sellers rather
than any aggressive buying,'' said Jayne Ball, a trader in the
energy futures department at Dean Witter Reynolds Inc. in New York.
   Prices have advanced recently in response to plans for a meeting
of oil producers from inside and outside the Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries on April 23.
   Gains also had been spurred Thursday by investors who dumped
stocks as the market tumbled in response to the Commerce
Department's disappointing report on U.S. trade.
</TEXT>
