<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Knight-Ridder     04-15 0221</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Knight-Ridder,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Knight-Ridder Amends Its `Poison Pill' Plan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Knight-Ridder Inc. said Friday that its board of
directors amended a shareholders' rights ``poison pill'' plan to a
make it even tougher for a hostile takeover of the media giant.
   The board also authorized a stock buyout of up to 5 million
common shares, four months after it approved the purchase of up to
2 million shares. Spokesman Frank Hawkins said the stock was needed
for several reasons, including employee share and option plans.
   More than 40 percent of Knight-Ridder stock is owned or
controlled by directors, officers, employees or founding families.
   Under the poison pill amendment, shareholders would be able to
buy additional common shares at a discount should someone acquire
up to 20 percent of the company's outstanding stock, said Hawkins.
   ``The effect of that is to make a hostile takeover attempt
extremely dilutive,'' he said.
   Meanwhile Friday, Knight-Ridder President James K. Batten, 52,
was elected chief executive officer. Batten, a 31-year veteran
newsman of Knight-Ridder, replaces Alvah H. Chapman Jr., 67, who
remains as chairman.
   Knight-Ridder publishes 30 daily newspapers, including the Miami
Herald and the Philadelphia Inquirer, owns and operates eight
television stations and is a joint venture partner in cable
television and newsprint manufacturing operations. It also owns
49.5 percent of The Seattle Times.
</TEXT>
