<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     04-15 0764</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0789</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Soybeans Plunge On Poor Export Outlook</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices plunged as much as 16 cents a bushel
Friday on the Chicago Board of Trade amid heavy selling prompted by
a dismal outlook for export sales, analysts said. Grain futures
also retreated.
   On other markets, cattle futures finished higher after reversing
sharp losses; pork futures moved lower; oil futures advanced for
the fifth straight day; precious metals and stock-index futures
posted slight gains.
   Soybeans declined on a combination of bearish fundamentals,
including good harvest weather for the South American soybean crop,
disappointing export sales last week and relatively high cash
prices for soybeans and soybean products, analysts said.
   ``We're just way out of whack with prices for cottonseed meal
and corn,'' making soybeans less attractive on the world market,
said Richard Loewy, senior grain and oilseed analyst for
Prudential-Bache Securities Inc. in New York.
   The government released grain export sales figures Thursday for
the week ending April 7, showing shipments of both soybeans and
soybean meal were down about 60 percent from the previous week.
   The rally last week that pushed new-crop soybean futures well
above $7 a bushel likely persuaded more farmers to plant soybeans,
another bearish factor, said Joel Karlin, an analyst for
Chicago-based Research Department Inc.
   Analysts said Chicago-based C&D Commodities, the largest
speculative firm on the floor, led the decline by selling large
numbers of contracts for soybeans and soybean products that it had
purchased in recent weeks.
   Wheat settled 2{ cents to 3} cents lower with the contract for
delivery in May at $3.12} a bushel; corn was 1{ cents to 2{ cents
lower with May at $2.02} a bushel; oats were { cent to 1{ cents
lower with May at $1.60 a bushel; soybeans were 13 cents to 16
cents lower with May at $6.62{ a bushel.
   Cattle futures rode a roller coaster on the Chicago Mercantile
Exchange with the contract for April delivery falling to 72.50
cents a pound, then rallying to settle at 73.97 cents, 15 points
above Thursday's settlement.
   Traders were counting on Friday's lower wholesale beef prices
and forecasts for warmer weather to spark a resurgence of retail
buying for outdoor cookouts, said Chuck Levitt, an analyst in
Chicago for Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   ``The abiltiy of the market to shake off its early severe losses
today indicated anticipation of better retail business next week,''
he said.
   The lower prices for pork futures reflected concerns about the
week's unusually high slaughter numbers, Levitt said.
   ``There is no sign of a seasonal letup in supplies,'' he said.
``Until we start to see the marketings subside, the market will
struggle with the large production.''
   Live cattle settled .10 cent lower to .37 cent higher with April
at 73.97 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .05 cent lower to .30
cent higher with April at 79.67 cents a pound; hogs were .32 cent
lower to .07 cent higher with April at 44.70 cents a pound; frozen
pork bellies were .03 cent lower to .90 cent higher with May at
52.05 cents a pound.
   Crude-oil futures advanced for the fifth straight day on the New
York Mercantile Exchange on expectations that OPEC and non-OPEC
countries will agree to limit oil production when they meet in a
session tentatively scheduled for April 26.
   Some members of the Organization of Petroleum Exporting
Countries appear unwilling to cut their production, but the market
has so far ignored those bearish signals, said Michael Rothman,
senior oil analyst for Merrill Lynch Capital Markets in New York.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 7 cents to 8 cents
higher with May at $18.37 a barrel; heating oil was .24 cent to .43
cent higher with May at 49.75 cents a gallon; unleaded gasoline was
.25 cent to .33 cent higher with May at 52.61 cents a gallon.
   Gold futures advanced on New York's Commodity Exchange in quiet
trading following the government's release of a report showing a
0.6 percent rise in wholesale prices last month. Silver was nearly
unchanged.
   The market was expecting an increase of about 0.3 percent in
wholesale prices, and analysts had expected the inflationary
implications of a greater rise to send gold prices soaring.
   Gold settled $1.90 to $2.80 higher with June at $458.50 a troy
ounce; silver was 0.5 cent to 1 cent higher with May at $6.475 a
troy ounce.
   Stock-index futures posted slight gains on the Chicago
Mercantile Exchange, where the contract for June delivery of the
Standard & Poor's 500 index settled 0.4 point higher at 258.80.
</TEXT>
