<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Georgia-Pacific     04-15 0560</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Georgia-Pacific,0579</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mill Closed, 400 Laid Off; Company Suspects Sabotage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WOODLAND, Maine (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Georgia-Pacific Corp. has suspended
operations at its pulp and paper mill here and temporarily laid off
400 employees while repairs are made to equipment that company
officials said Friday may have been sabotaged.
   The closing follows a weeklong shutdown at a Georgia-Pacific
mill in Vermont because of what the company also termed apparent
acts of sabotage.
   Labor leaders have denied union involvment in the incidents at
both mills.
   The Woodland mill was shut down Thursday after a maintenance
employee discovered two pounds of sand blasting shot in the gear
box and lube system of a paper pulp washer in the bleaching plant,
mill manager Jerry Robinson said.
   ``The machine has just been destroyed,'' spokeswoman Beth
Zoffmann said from the company's headquarters in Atlanta. ``If we
can't make bleached pulp, we can't make any paper. And we can't
make any bleached pulp.''
   Robinson said the mill would remain closed and the 400 hourly
workers laid off indefinitely while the washer is repaired and an
investigation conducted into other areas of the mill.
   Company officials said the pulp washer was ``apparently
sabotaged,'' and Maine State Police detectives have been called in
to conduct a criminal investigation, Lt. John Whynott said.
   Zoffmann said she did not know who might have tampered with the
equipment, which was located in an area accessible to all
employees. She also declined to say if the incident was related to
stalled contract negotiations.
   There is ``no evidence to indicate that it is,'' she said. ``I
guess it would be speculation'' to say the union was involved.
   Jimmy Dinardo, vice president of the United Paperworkers
International Union in New England, said he did not believe union
members were responsible.
   ``The international does not condone anything like sabotage,''
he said. ``And I don't believe the company has proof of anything
like that.''
   Labor negotiations, under way since July between
Georgia-Pacific, the UPIU and several smaller trade unions, have
been stalled and no date has been set to resume the talks. The
unions have been working without a contract since August.
   Among the sticking points are the union's demands for premium
pay on Sundays, as well as the company's desire for more
flexibility in assigning jobs and the opportunity to keep the mill
open on holidays. Management of the pension fund has also been an
issue.
   This is not the first time equipment has been damaged at the
mill and the cause attributed to sabotage. In September, another
machine in the bleaching plant was found damaged during a regularly
scheduled maintenance shutdown. Zoffmann said no one was found at
fault in that incident and the investigation is continuing.
   In Vermont, the Georgia-Pacific paper mill in Gilman was shut
down April 6-13 because of what the company termed apparent acts of
sabotage. Zoffmann said 185 workers, including 140 union employees,
were sent home while police began an investigation into the dumping
of dye in a vat of wallpaper stock.
   Police also are investigating an April 3 fire that damaged a
garage and two vehicles at the Littleton, N.H., home of the Gilman
mill's personnel manager.
   Workers at the Gilman mill have been without a contract for six
months and authorities in Vermont have questioned whether the
incidents are labor-related. Union members have emphatically denied
any connection.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
