<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Speakes-Truth     04-15 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Speakes-Truth,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Speakes Said In Post-Crash Interview That Truth Is Crucial in
Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Speakes Resigns</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Larry Speakes said in a television interview
after the October stock market crash that his job as White House
spokesman had taught him the value of truthfulness.
   Speakes, who joined Merrill Lynch & Co. as vice president of
communications last year after his departure from Washington,
resigned Friday because of an uproar over his disclosure that he
had invented quotes for President Reagan.
   In an appearance on the syndicated television show, The Wall
Street Journal Report, on Oct. 29, Speakes said there is ``no
substitute for the truth in a crisis.''
   ``In a crisis, as I found out previously, the thing you want to
do is get to as many people as you can with the facts, to give them
the story and the truth,'' he said on the broadcast.
   He was responding to a question about post-crash Merrill Lynch
advertisements, which had been criticized as overly optimistic
about the outlook for stocks.
</TEXT>
