<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1903EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Eastern     04-15 0549</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Eastern,0568</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Union Says FAA Safety Checks Sideline 10 Eastern Jets</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DONALD W. SWINTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of Eastern Airlines planes sidelined
with safety violations grew to at least 10 Friday, as a federal
crackdown found problems including a fuel leak, a missing
maintenance log and a cracked wing flap, the Machinists union said.
   The airline and the Federal Aviation Administration refused to
confirm the number, saying they have stopped detailing the
violations.
   ``They didn't want to see a running box score,'' said FAA
spokesman John Leyden. ``We'll summerize it at the end of the
inspection.''
   Four more planes were found to have safety violations Friday,
according to a Machinists official who spoke on condition of
anonymity.
   ``They're calling in from around the country,'' the official
said of machinists supplying their union with information after the
FAA stopped making it public.
   Meanwhile, Machinists union President Charles E. Bryan put out a
bulletin to Eastern's 12,000 machinists urging them to report
thoroughly on threats some employees have said they received from
management after they spoke voluntarily with FAA inspectors.
   The latest temporary groundings were in Boston, St. Louis,
Tallahassee and Atlanta, the unidentified union official said.
   In Boston, Flight 945, an A-300 AirBus, was sidelined at 9 a.m.
EDT Friday with a wing flap dent and a fuel leak in an engine. The
plane was fixed by 12:30 p.m., the official said.
   A second St. Louis flight was held for repairs Friday morning,
the official said. Flight 465, a 727 to Miami, was found to have a
cracked wing flap. Late Thursday, Flight 267, a DC-9 bound for
Atlanta, was taken out of service after FAA inspectors found it
lacked a flight maintenance log and was missing landing bumper pads.
   The battery relay switch on a DC-9 was found not to be working
in Tallahassee. The switch turns on the plane's electrical
equipment, the official said.
   The tenth plane was a DC-9 taken out of service when inspectors
discovered a duct in the tail section was overheating, the official
said.
   The four Friday groundings were in addition to six the FAA
reported on Thursday.
   Leyden said about 20 percent of the EAL 267-plane fleet had been
looked over by FAA inspectors in 23 cities when the agency stopped
reporting its findings Friday morning. Inspections were expected to
continue as flights arrived in those cities during the 30-day
review that began Wednesday.
   Eastern officials have refused to reveal the number of safety
violations found in their fleet.
   Eastern spokewoman Karen Ceremsak said news of the sidelined
planes was being overblown. She noted that some of mechanical
problems occurred daily and were fixed.
   However, a Minneapolis-Atlanta flight that Eastern had cleared
for takeoff was emptied of passengers and sidelined Thursday
because of a fuel leak, NBC News reported.
   In addition to the planes stopped Friday, the
Minneapolis-Atlanta and St. Louis flights, DC-9s and 727s were
sidelined in Miami, New York and Rochester, N.Y.
   The inspection of all Eastern planes began after the FAA slapped
the company with a $823,000 fine for safety violations. U.S.
Transportation Secretary Jim Burnley said officials have been
unsatisfied with Eastern's performance since its 1986 takeover by
Texas Air Corp., which also will undergo a 30-day inspection of its
operating practices.
</TEXT>
