<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 1910EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WestSuit     04-15 0420</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-West Suit,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Closing Arguments Heard In West Publishing Case</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two computerized legal research services
squared off in federal court Friday for closing arguments in a
two-week copyright infringement trial a defense lawyer called a
case of ``the emperor's new clothes.''
   West Publishing Co. filed suit against one of its competitors in
1985, alleging copyright infringement. West, based in St. Paul,
accused Mead Corp. and Mead Data Central of illegally using West's
copyright material in Lexis, their computerized legal research
service.
   MDC, which distributes Lexis, is a subsidiary of Mead Corp., a
paper products manufacturer based in Dayton, Ohio.
   ``A case of the `emperor's new clothes' is how I referred to
this in my opening statement,'' Mead lawyer David C. Greer told the
court. ``The arrangements in this case are nothing more than legal
finery which have been rigged up by some tailor.''
   Last year, Mead sued West, claiming that West is an illegal
monopoly. West also has filed an antitrust suit against Mead,
bringing to three the number of lawsuits in which the two are
engaged.
   The copyright infringement trial, heard by U.S. District Judge
James Rosenbaum, is part of an 11-count complaint. The remaining 10
counts will be resolved by judicial order once Rosenbaum issues his
ruling on the copyright issue.
   West's National Reporter System publishes judicial opinions for
every state and federal court, and the company's Key Number Index
System organizes and classifies case law.
   West asks that Mead and Mead Data Central be permanently
enjoined from continuing to copy West's materials and that the
court impound and destroy all infringing materials.
   ``Mead took (our materials). They knew it. And they expected to
derive great revenue from it,'' West lawyer Vance K. Opperman
argued. ``We have both the right to copy and the right to display.
Both have been infringed.''
   But Mead claims there's been no infringement because West is not
entitled to a copyright.
   ``In no case does copyright protection from an original work or
authority extend to an idea ... And if we have anything here, all
we have is an idea or concept,'' Greer argued.
   Greer said Mead only wanted to make ``fair use'' of the
materials and should have access to them.
   ``West, I submit, confused access to the law with access to West
books ... But West doesn't own the law,'' Greer said.
   Opperman argued that West's system reflects originality and is
therefore protected by copyright.
   ``This is the product of great intellectual effort, great
creativity,'' Opperman said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
