<1ST_LINE>u f AM-Koppers 1stLd-Writethru   04-15 0529</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Koppers, 1st Ld-Writethru,0546</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>Eds: Updates throughout with additional detail; raises findings on
Shearson's role; tightens</NOTE>
<HEAD>Judge Blocks Koppers Takeover</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EARL BOHN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PITTSBURGH (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge Friday blocked investors led
by Britain's Brian C. Beazer from proceeding with a $1.7 billion
hostile takeover of Koppers Co., but the judge left the door open
for Beazer to salvage the proposed deal.
   U.S. District Judge Maurice B. Cohill Jr. said that the novel
role played by Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc. in the takeover
apparently requires the investment banking firm to file financial
disclosure statements just like any other bidder. Shearson did not
make the filings.
   Cohill said that ``since ... there is a great probability that
the defendants have violated the Williams Act,'' he was suspending
the takeover until a trial can be held or the violations in the
$60-per-share tender offer are corrected.
   The Williams Act is intended to prevent manipulation of the
stock markets.
   The Beazer group did not immediately indicate whether it would
appeal Cohill's order or attempt to correct the technical defects
and continue soliciting shares.
   The tender offer was due to expire at midnight Friday, but the
suitors are expected to extend the offer during the weekend.
   Beazer wants to combine his British and American holdings in
construction and building materials with the Pittsburgh-based
Koppers, a major U.S. producer of building materials and chemicals.
   Shearson maintained that its partial ownership of Beazer's
takeover company, BNS Inc., is merely an extension of traditional
lending practices in corporate acquisitions.
   ``The Shearson interests appear to be somewhat stealthily
pioneering the brave new world of equity financing,'' the judge
said in his 95-page opinion and order. ``As the legendary camel
once got his nose in the tent, intending to follow with its entire
body, so Shearson seems to be pursuing an agenda of its own.''
   Shearson's new approach prompted members of Congress to propose
legislation against the takeover and to call for investigations.
   Cohill said, ``this is a difficult case'' made all the more
complex by Shearson's ``quite novel'' role as
``broker-dealer-investment banker-adviser-owner.
   ``The facts are intricate and complicated; the law is fuzzy,''
he said.
   Cohill also said Beazer's plans to borrow $864 million from a
bank syndicate led by Citibank likely violate Federal Reserve Board
rules about posting stock as collateral on loans used to buy the
stock.
   The order is the second against the tender offer in a federal
court.
   A judge in Los Angeles has blocked it on antitrust grounds. The
U.S. 9th Circuirt Court of Appeals will hear arguments May 13 on
Beazer's attempt to overturn the Los Angeles ruling.
   Beazer's plans to sell Koppers' chemical operations stoked fears
of losing 1,100 jobs in Pittsburgh, and Cohill said the takeover
should be halted for now because ``the potential ramifications ...
to the Pittsburgh community are uncertain and possibly adverse.''
   In a countersuit, the Beazer group said Koppers's filings in
response to the tender offer also violated securities laws. But
Cohill said the tender offer apparently ``is invalid under federal
securities laws'' and ``until ... a valid tender offer is made,
Koppers is not obligated'' to file the proper disclosures.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
