<FILEID>AP-NR-04-15-88 2022EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-GMSalaries 1stLd-Writethru   04-15 0505</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-GM Salaries, 1st Ld-Writethru,0519</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>GM Chairman Receives At Least $2.2 Million For 1987</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to CORRECT time element in stock issuance.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JANET BRAUNSTEIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Auto Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   General Motors Corp. Chairman Roger Smith
received at least $2.2 million for 1987 in salary, exercised stock
options and stock grants, the nation's largest automaker reported
Friday in its proxy statement.
   Smith received $867,000 in salary, earned $513,121 exercising
stock options and was awarded a stock bonus worth $800,000 when it
was granted on Dec. 7. The stock, issued in blocks over a
three-year period that began in January, is worth considerably more
now.
   GM President Robert Stempel received at least $1.2 million for
1987: $517,000 in salary, $73,523 on exercised stock options and
$600,000 in the stock bonus. Stempel became president in August,
when he replaced the retired F. James McDonald.
   In all, GM paid $13.6 million in 1987 salaries to its top 58
executives and gave stock awards worth $16.2 million on Dec. 7 and
$21.1 million on Friday to 4,961 executives.
   Ford Motor Co., the No. 2 automaker, paid $247.9 million in
bonuses for 1987 to 5,166 executives, it reported in a proxy
statement mailed Tuesday.
   Ford Vice Chairman Harold Poling earned nearly $11 million in
1987: $808,697 in salary, $2 million in cash bonuses and nearly
$8.1 million on exercised stock options.
   Ford Chairman Donald Petersen, who exercised no stock options,
received $2.8 million in cash bonuses and $929,934 in salary.
   GM's profit rose to $3.6 billion in 1987 from $2.95 billion in
1986, but for the second year in a row it earned too little on its
U.S. automaking business to pay profit-sharing to its 350,000
hourly U.S. workers.
   The outcry over the millions of dollars executives received in
bonuses for 1986 prompted GM's board of directors in 1987 to switch
to an all-stock bonus and spread each stock grant over several
years.
   United Auto Workers union President Owen Bieber and Vice
President Donald Ephlin said the 1987 compensation received by top
GM executives ``still can't be justified rationally and constitutes
an insult to common sense and fairness.''
   During a time when GM's automaking business is earning so
little, they said in a statement, ``we will leave the executives to
forego all increases and supplementary awards in the spirit of
shared sacrifice.''
   Ford distributed a record $636 million in profit-sharing checks
in March to more than 156,000 hourly and salaried employees, an
average of more than $4,000 each.
   On Friday, GM's common stock closed at $72.75 a share, up from
$71.62{. GM Class E stock, based on earnings of its Electronic Data
Systems Corp. subsidiary, declined to $41 a share from $41.62{.
   GM Class H stock, based on earnings of GM Hughes Electronics
Corp., closed at $30.25 a share, up from $30.
   When the stock bonuses were granted Dec. 7, GM common stock was
worth $56.19 a share, Class E stock was worth $31.19 a share and
Class H stock was worth $23.22 a share.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
